INSERT INTO `speakers` VALUES (1,'','',0,0,'Jeroen.van Dijk53fce21ea3f50.jpeg',0),(5,'you','me',0,0,'',0),(7,'','',0,0,'Richard.Tuin5404c847b39a1.jpg',0),(10,'','',1,1,'Richard.Tuin54062cb57d04f.jpg',1),(13,'','PHPBenelux Crew',0,0,'Michelangelo.vanDam5406be1ab2393.jpg',0),(14,'Meat lover','I wil tell later',0,0,'Paul.Borgermans5406e350b4f53.jpg',0),(17,'','',0,0,'Jeroen.vanDijk5406e89de9224.jpeg',1),(18,'','This is a speaker bio',1,1,'Richard.Tuin5406ef8eefc89.jpg',1),(19,'','Chris is a PHP writer and developer from Cape Town, South Africa. He\'s married, has two kids, builds robots and runs rebuildinglaravel.com + tutorials.io.',1,1,'Christopher.Pitt54072343d16a4.jpg',0),(20,'','Tobias, from Cologne, Germany, has been developing PHP applications for close to a decade now and is currently working towards a Bachelor\'s degree in Scientific Programming. For the last four years, he has been aiding the team at PHPBenelux as a volunteer. He regularly contributes talks to his local user group and is currently employed at dimensional GmbH, where he helps create high-perormance web and mobile applications.',1,1,'Tobias.Gies54072363732c9.png',0),(21,'','Joshua Thijssen is a freelance consultant and trainer. His daily work consists of maintaining code bases, working on different projects and helping other to achieve higher standards in both coding and thinking. He is the lead developer of Saffire - a web/system language, author of the PHP|Architect book \"Mastering the SPL library\", founder of the Dutch Web Alliance and regular speaker at national and international conferences.',0,1,'Joshua.Thijssen540723cee9699.jpg',0),(22,'Speaking history: http://lanyrd.com/profile/thomas-shone/sessions/','I\'ve been working with PHP since 2005 and have been working remotely since 2010. Until recently I lived in South Africa.\n\nI have a fondness for Composer, php-fig and security stuff. On occasion I\'ve been known to point out vulnerabilities in payment gateways. On occasion I\'ve been threatened with legal action for doing this.',1,1,'Thomas.Shone540729680c279.jpg',0),(23,'I\'m awesome, really. Ok, i\'m just a nice guy.','Rafael Dohms is an experienced PHP Developer, Evangelist, Speaker, and Contributor. During his years of experience, he has become an active member of the community and founded three user groups. He moved to the Netherlands in search of new challenges and to share his passion for code quality and innovation. In his spare time, he also helps manage the AmsterdamPHP User Group, amongst other projects.',1,1,'Rafael.Dohms54072aa0ac5de.jpg',0),(24,'','Chris Hartjes has been building web applications of all shapes and sizes since 1998, ranging from catalogs for CD compilations for professional DJâ€™s to large-scale dating web sites. By day he works with the team at Roave (http://www.roave.com). By night he works on his burgeoning info-product empire, plays simulation baseball and gets his butt kicked at Magic the Gathering. All day long he is on Twitter. A huge consumer of open-source software, Chris tries to give back to the community via his blog, by speaking at conferences, and by co-organizing TrueNorthPHP (Canada\'s only dedicated PHP conference). He is also a big believer in the power of testing and automation as secret weapons for organizations to deliver high quality applications quickly. He lives in Milton, Ontario, Canada with his long-suffering wife, two daughters, a furry pig masquerading as a cat, and the reincarnation of the Roman god of the underworld in feline form.',1,1,'Chris.Hartjes54072cf08d9c6.jpg',0),(25,'','Amsterdam resident, evangelist of packages, maintainer of Flysystem, member of The PHP League and serial Laracon EU speaker.',1,1,'Frank.deJonge54072d2997b2b.jpg',0),(26,'','Jonathan Reinink is a long time (late 90\'s) front and back-end web developer with a keen interest in PHP. Jonathan currently serves as the Director of Web Development at Compass Creative, a Canadian based marketing company that provides branding and websites to trades businesses. Jonathan spearheads their SaaS product, Worksites.net, a do-it-yourself website builder for contractors. After hours, Jonathan runs a second SaaS product, Church Social, a niche web-based management product for churches. In recent years Jonathan has transition from being a \"lone wolf\" developer to being much more active in the PHP community. Most notably, Jonathan has contributed Plates, a native PHP template system that\'s part of The PHP League. Jonathan has a strong design sense and is an advocate of using good design to help promote technical projects.',1,1,'Jonathan.Reinink540733d595d65.jpg',0),(27,'awarded for an uncon talk during PHPBenelux 2014, \nwon the DPC14 uncon (so was provided a slot in DPC15), \ndid a PHPBenelux meetup talk in May 2014 (for which the claim is not approved yet in joindin), \nhttps://joind.in/talk/view/11349, \nhttps://joind.in/user/view/19241,','Stijn Vannieuwenhuyse is a young software-developer who currently works for ONE-Agency. He started his career as a PHP-developer, more specifically by refactoring legacy Symfony-applications using techniques from TDD, BDD and DDD. Nowadays heâ€™s exploring Modelling, CQRS and event-sourcing while building greenfield applications. When Stijn is not programming, heâ€™s timekeeping major track and field competitions.',1,1,'Stijn.Vannieuwenhuyse540735a328f32.jpg',0),(28,'I have received great feedback as an up-and-coming speaker, for example, most of my feedback has been 4-5 \"thumbs\" out of 5 on Joind.in (you can see my Joind.in profile here: https://joind.in/user/view/22381); and I\'m REALLY passionate about speaking!\n\nI recently spoke at Brno PHP Conference in Czech Republic, and am looking forward to presenting a talk at the awesome Nomad PHP EU meetup in December. I have spoken across many user groups in the UK, and you can see all my talk history on my website at http://www.jamestitcumb.com/talks including all relevant Joind.in links where possible.','James is the founder of the UK based PHP Hampshire user group, a Zend Certified Engineer and Development Manager at Protected.co.uk. His day job sees him working on ZF2 and legacy projects. During his downtime, he continues to run the PHP Hampshire user group, as well as keeping up with active contributions to open source projects, such as the Browser Capabilities Project.\n\nSince getting an Amiga 500 as a young boy, James has been fascinated with the world of programming and technology. He quickly embarked on a captivating adventure learning languages through time, from AmigaBASIC to C/C++. Then 11 years ago, he discovered his true calling - PHP.',1,1,'James.Titcumb5407405c239b9.png',0),(29,'','',1,1,'',0),(30,'Ratings for my previous talks can be found via http://techblog.wimgodden.be/conference-talks/ or http://joind.in/user/view/416','Wim Godden has been working with open source technologies since 1997 and has been involved in open source projects such as OpenX and PHPCompatibility.\nNext to web development, he\'s worked with a wide range of technologies (from database clusters to Internet backbone design) and focuses a lot of his time on high-scalability projects and on coaching/training web engineers.',0,0,'Wim.Godden54077c150146d.png',0),(31,'While I will be able to attend the entire conference, I must speak on Friday before 2:00pm due to the onset of the Jewish Sabbath and the technical complications that presents.','Yitzchok Willroth is an independent web application developer and software development consultant living in Lakewood, New Jersey. A start-up veteran, dev bootcamp instructor and frequent conference attendee, Yitzchok is the organizer of the ShorePHP User Group and an active participant in the PHPMentoring Initiative. Passionate about clean code and robust application architecture, he is also a strong proponent of remote teams as a way for software organizations to thrive while affording developers a healthy work:life balance.',1,1,'Yitzchok.Willroth5407a6cf874d7.jpg',0),(32,'Iâ€™ve spoken at OSCON twice (2013 and 2014), php[tek] in 2014, True North PHP in 2013, linux.conf.au in 2013 and 2014, and OSDC in 2011, among other user groups and miniconf talks along the way. These talks have been on topics ranging from PHP to embedded Android devices to using HTML 5 animation for UX, and those talks that have been delivered at conferences with speaker review systems have been received well.','Adam is a PHP Agenteer (it\'s totally a word) at New Relic who spends most of his time swearing at C compilers and the PHP API, usually not in that order. In between said bouts of invective, Adam works on various open source projects, including PHP, and continues in his ongoing quest to find the best beer in the world. (Well, OK, itâ€™s totally Westvleteren 12, but itâ€™s a good excuse to drink more beer.)',0,0,'Adam.Harvey5407d4e4183ed.jpg',0),(33,'','Ibrahim AshShohail is a Zend Certified Engineer working as a Senior Developer at Tamkeen Technologies based in Riyadh, SA. He graduated from KSU with a bachelor degree in Computer Science. Ibrahim has been working on PHP for +8 years. His passion for open-source started two years ago and he has been trying to contribute to the wonderful community since then. A Laravel advocate since 3.x.\nFind him on twitter: @ibrasho',1,1,'Ibrahim.AshShohail54081621f082a.jpg',0),(34,'I started and regularly write for http://www.masterzendframework.com.','Matthew Setter is a software developer and freelance technical writer with over 14 years of professional software development experience, gained in Australia, England and Germany. He is the author of Zend Framework 2 Foundations, writes for a variety of publications including PHP Architect magazine and SitePoint.com, and is regularly developing with PHP and related technologies.',1,1,'Matthew.Setter54080b05278e8.jpg',0),(35,'','A little bit too fake',1,1,'Igor.Wiedler54081cda447cd.jpg',0),(36,'Will probably be traveling by train instead of the airport.','Opensource enthusiast, starting speaker.',1,1,'WillemJan.Zijderveld542457b83a15c.jpg',0),(37,'PJ has spoken at Cascadia Ruby, LonestarPHP, Dublin WebSummit, RailsConf 2013, RailsConf Israel, Ruby Conf (US) 2013 (keynote), Steel City Ruby, Windy City Rails, Devs Love Bacon (UK), Big Ruby Conf, Brighton Ruby Conf, Codemash, MagmaConf, RubyConf India (keynote), RubyConf Philippines, and various user groups around the world.','A Ruby developer for the last several years, PJ currently works at Engine Yard as a Community Engineer. Additionally, he organizes the Western New York Ruby Brigade. Traveling to conferences and Ruby meet ups around the US and Canada, PJ likes to spread the word on the importance of community and coding, stressing the importance of outreach and focusing on the human side of being a coder.',0,0,'PJ.Hagerty5408792b6e2b2.png',0),(38,'','For the last 12+ years, Chris has been involved in the PHP community in one way or another. These days he\'s the Senior Editor of PHPDeveloper.org and @phpquickfix &amp; @websecquickfix as well as the web application security site Websec.io. He\'s written for several PHP publications and has spoken at conferences in both the U.S. and Europe and is an organizer of the DallasPHP User Group and the Lone Star PHP Conference.',0,0,'Chris.Cornutt5408857167744.png',0),(39,'','Maarten Balliauw is a Developer Advocate at JetBrains. His interests are all web: ASP.NET MVC, PHP and Microsoft Azure. Maarten also co-founded MyGet, hosting private NuGet feeds for teams. He\'s a Microsoft Most Valuable Professional (MVP) for Microsoft Azure and an ASPInsider. He has published many articles in both PHP and .NET literature such as MSDN magazine and PHP architect. Maarten is a frequent speaker at various national and international events. His blog can be found at http://blog.maartenballiauw.be.',0,0,'Maarten.Balliauw5409d74b725f5.jpg',0),(40,'May be able to work out some form of sponsorship with Zend.','Adam Culp (@AdamCulp) author of \"Refactoring 101\" and consultant at Zend Technologies is passionate about developing with PHP and contributes to many open source projects.  He organizes the SunshinePHP Developer Conference and South Florida PHP Users Group (SoFloPHP) where he enjoys helping others write good code, implement standards, refactor efficiently, and incorporate unit and functional testing into their projects.  He is a Zend Certified PHP 5.3 Engineer, and holds a seat on the Zend Framework Certification Advisory Board.  When he is not coding or contributing to various developer communities, he can be found hiking around the United States National Parks, teaching judo, or long(ultra) distance running.',1,1,'Adam.Culp540a10b490f4d.png',0),(41,'','Geshan is a seasoned software engineer, with more than 6 years of professional web development experience. Currently in Dubai, UAE serving Namshi as Quality and Maintenance Lead. He is focused on enterprise application architecture and methodologies. With a keen interest on REST architecture and Service Oriented Architecture (SOA) he believes in agile methods for software engineering. He is also interesting in Quality Assurance (QA) , blogging when he gets time for it is also something he likes.',1,1,'Geshan.Manandhar540c1142eef9d.jpeg',0),(42,'','Scrum master and developer @sensiolabs for almost 3 years now, I\'m a happy, curious and enjoying sharer. I\'m also a trainer on Symfony.',1,1,'Sarah.Khalil540d798d2c19c.jpg',0),(43,'Hi guys, I truly would like to come to Antwerp, I really enjoyed the conference when I was there in 2011 and 2012, it was simply amazing.\nYou can check my profile on https://joind.in/user/view/956\nIf you have any issue for the reimbursements, even if it will be challenging, I will try to cover the expenses myself.','Alessandro Cinelli (a.k.a. cirpo) is currently working as Lead Developer at Namshi (http://namshi.com),  the fashion e-commerce in the Middle East located in Dubai.\nHe has a keen attention for enterprise patterns, methodologies, clean code and everything related to performances.\nHe loves to share and give back to the community, thatâ€™s why he actively contributes to open source projects and when he was in Italy he has been a board member of the Italian PHP, Javascript User Group, WEBdeBS and had co-organized several events such as agileday, phpday, jsday, nosqlday and nodejsconf some of which were the first of their kind in Italy. He is also working to setup a brand new web comminity in Dubai',1,1,'alessandro.cinelli540dcbb4624fa.png',0),(44,'I\'m a volunteer hospital magician at a children\'s hospital through an organization called Open Heart Magic.\n\nI\'m a competitive West Coast Swing dancer. I compete around the US in the \"Rising Star\" and \"Jack &amp; Jill\" divisions. :)','Sammy Kaye Powers is a web developer with over a decade of professional experience. He is obsessed with learning new things and loves to share what he has learned with the community. Over the past few years he has focused on Facebook app development (http://www.sammykmedia.com/) and has developed many annoying apps on Facebook. FarmVille is not included in that list. He has since become one of the top contributors to the official Facebook PHP SDK (https://github.com/facebook/facebook-php-sdk-v4/graphs/contributors) and blogs about the latest-and-greatest in the Facebook development world (https://www.sammyk.me/). He is also the host of a new brand new PHP podcast called the PHP Roundtable (http://www.phproundtable.com/).\n\nMore about Sammy: https://www.sammyk.me/about',1,1,'Sammy.Powers540e8ab510023.jpg',0),(45,'','...',1,1,'AnneJulia.Scheuermann540eae71c643e.jpeg',1),(46,'','Jan-Willem is a experienced freelance software architect, technical consultant and Amazon Web Services specialist. In the last 15 years he combined technical skills with practical, hands-on business insights for several companies and organisations.',0,1,'JanWillem.Eshuis540ec623d2cb8.jpg',0),(47,'I am new to speaking at conferences but have been giving corporate presentations for quite some time.  So far I have given 3 talks at conferences.  My first talk, Domain Driven Design, was an Uncon at ZendCon in 2013 (http://joind.in/9594).  I recently gave 2 talks at the PHP Minicamp / Drupal Camp LA conference at UCI in Orange County, CA.  The first was Getting Started with Vagrant (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TRqVh2WSD7w).  The second was Asynchronous PHP and Real-time messaging.','Steve Rhoades has been developing with PHP since 1999 and professionally since 2000.  He currently works as a Senior Software Engineer and leads a large development team at Panasonic Avionics, headquartered in Lake Forest, CA.  Steve has recently developed a passion for Evented Programming and Asynchronous Processing in PHP and is an active open source contributor to projects such as ReactPHP and Zend Framework.    When Steve is not banding out code he can usually be found on the baseball field with his two sons or at the park with his daughter.  Follow him on twitter @steverhoades.',1,1,'Steve.Rhoades5422f84f582a8.jpg',0),(48,'Coming from Amsterdam Centraal Station (train) ;)','Erika Heidi started her career as sysadmin, changing her focus to development after some years and embracing PHP as her main language, about 10 years ago. A Linux user since that time when you had to use minicom to connect to the Internet, Erika wrote the Vagrant Cookbook and created open source projects like Phansible, Placephant and dev-human. She works now as developer evangelist at Digital Ocean.',0,0,'Erika.Heidi5425b5b70956e.JPG',1),(49,'https://joind.in/user/view/582','Harrie Verveer has been working with PHP as a professional since 2004 and is currently employed as a senior PHP developer at bax-shop.nl. Bax-shop.nl is the largest web shop for sound, stage and studio equipment in the Netherlands and Belgium, and is quickly expanding to other countries in Europe as well. Harrie helped organizing the Dutch PHP Conference in 2011 and 2012 and is a regular speaker at conferences and user group events around the world, where he shares his experience and knowledge gained from working with a wide variety of technologies. In his spare time Harrie enjoys playing tennis, playing golf and playing guitar in his own cover band.',0,1,'Harrie.Verveer54100ff8523fa.jpg',0),(50,'','Richard has been involved in the PHP/open source community for sometime mainly in the UK and Japan. After living in Japan for over 15years speaks fluent Japanese and is quite nifty at using chop-sticks. \n\nHe has been an active contributor to open source projects such as Lithium, BEAR.Sunday and also a couple of his own projects.\n\nHe has been freelancing with a good chunk of that time at the BBC.',1,1,'Richard.McIntyre5411efa7cfe9c.jpg',0),(51,'Currently working on Autotrack.be (de Persgroep) for Enrise.com','With more than a decade in professional web application development Nick Belhomme has contributed in a number of ways to the PHP Community. He is a domain-driven design enthusiast and his consulting focus is the design and construction of enterprise applications. He speaks and is frequently found at conferences. Understanding the changing needs of the Internet he created â€œFirestorage Plus!â€, a Firefox Add-on which is downloaded by thousands and used by hundreds on a daily basis. In his spare time he likes to travel, take hikes with his lovely wife and loves nature.',0,1,'Nick.Belhomme5411f6e012ec9.jpg',1),(52,'','Michelle Sanver is co-president of PHPWomen, an inclusive &amp; global network providing support within the PHP community. She also works as a software developer at Liip, based in ZÃ¼rich, Switzerland.\n\nMichelle loves anything community related and is a big advocate of Open Source. She is a code-passionate colourful geek and with more than 10 years of PHP experience she is eager to share her extensive knowledge.',1,1,'Michelle.Sanver54120abad88cb.png',0),(53,'Since we designed the workshop togehter, we\'ve included our three names in the bio. Also, it would be hard to run a smooth workshop with just one speaker without help. If it\'s an issue about funding travel cost for all three of us, we would ask our employer, who\'s usually very generous about conference travel. This would be the first time that we\'re holding this workshop, but we have experience giving talks and holding workshops (at least I have in Node.js).','Franz Thoma, Julian Exner, and Franziska Hinkelmann are software consultants for TNG Technolgoy Consulting in Munich. For their client, they work on migrating a legacy enterprise PHP application to several smaller modular applications that areto be maintained and further developed by a team of 25 developers. They focus on clean, maintanable code with high test coverage that can be easily understood and extended even by new team members. They have contributed to various open source projects such as Mockery and are active members in the PHP Usergroup Munich.',1,1,'Franziska.Hinkelmann542bd28b1ad8d.jpeg',0),(54,'','Matthias Noback started his professional career 12 years ago as a freelance web developer. After working as a PHP developer for various companies, he decided to try something else; though programming will always be his passion, he has now taken this further and is also teaching, writing and consulting. He is the author of \"A Year With Symfony\" (https://leanpub.com/a-year-with-symfony) and regularly posts on his blog \"PHP &amp; Symfony\" (http://php-and-symfony.matthiasnoback.nl/).',1,1,'Matthias.Noback541347bd369d9.jpg',1),(55,'I have requested travel and hotel reimbursement BUT my company would be willing to pay for those expenses instead if you could give us an equivalent sponsorship in return.','Shaunak Kashyap has been working in the Internet software industry for over a decade. In this time Shaunak has worked at small and large companies (Yahoo) alike. He started his career at a startup in Connecticut, worked at a Hollywood production company (World Poker Tour) in LA and eventually settled in Silicon Valley. Today, Shaunak works from his home office as a Developer Advocate at Rackspace.',1,1,'Shaunak.Kashyap54135afc343ba.png',0),(56,'PHPBenelux is one of my favorite conferences. It would be an honor to be able to present.','Pablo Godel is a Sommelier of New Technologies. He has been working with PHP since the mid-90s when he started the PHP mailing list for spanish speaking developers. During the last years he has been using (and contributing to) many open source projects like Symfony, AngularJS. He previously founded was CTO of ServerGrove, and now provides consulting services around PHP, Symfony and DevOps. In his leisure time he likes to spend his time with his family, travel and sailing.',1,1,'Pablo.Godel5413628eac67e.png',0),(57,'I\'m Awesome.','Gary Hockin has been a web developer for over 15 years. He\'s a valued contributor to both Zend Framework 1 and 2, in addition to being on the ZF2 documentation team. Gary is Technical Lead of Training and Certification for Zend, along with being part of Roave, the badass PHP developers. When not working or spending time with his wife and two daughters, Gary can sometimes be found at the pub playing competitive pool.',1,1,'Gary.Hockin54156529770c7.jpg',0),(58,'I can also fly out of JFK or EWR depending on whatever is cheaper','Daniel is a Senior Engineer for Croscon living in New York City. In his laughably short free time, he co-organizes the QueensJS user group, continues to assist co-orgaizing the Lone Star PHP conference, speaks at conferences, eats way too much souvlaki at the cart down the street. He is Yolo Certified, a cat lover, and despite his last name not Canadian',1,1,'Daniel.Cousineau5417689d6fb3d.jpg',0),(59,'Joind.in profile: https://joind.in/user/view/2660\nI have in the past been able to get my company to pay for travel and hotel, but I can\'t guarantee it until a proposal is accepted. It\'s a sort of chicken and egg situation.','I believe that building great software starts with building a great team. At GSN Games, I run the development and QA groups for gsn.com. We build awesome software that deals with crazy traffic and we have a lot of fun doing it. If you aren\'t having fun writing the code, the final product won\'t be any fun. I honestly love my job and the team I work with.',1,1,'',0),(60,'','My name is Antonio Peric and I am CEO and Lead Developer at Locastic (www.locastic.com). Locastic is agency based in Split, Croatia and specialized id developing web and mobile applications. \n\nLast 8 years I am developing custom web applications for clients and last 3 and half years I am working with Symfony2 framework. I have built a lot of various projects on Symfony2: ecommerce, social apps, custom CMS and a lot more. Also I have experience in providing Symfony trainings and consulting for our clients. Work for some large clients as Replay, OshKosh, Carters, Arena Italia and more.\n\nLast two years I am also focusing on giving talks at conference. Here is list of my talks:\n2011 - Why Symfony2 framework is good choice? (Web strategija Croatia)\n2012- Why Symfony2? - ZgPhp Group\n2013 - Symfony workshop - Croatia\n2013 - Sylius - PHP Conference Croatia\n2013 - Symfony workshop - eZSummer Camp (http://ezsummercamp.com/)\n2013 - few small talks in local user groups\n2014 - PHPDay Verona\n2014 - WebCampLjubljana, Slovenia\n2014 - Started Symfony User Group Croatia (www.symfony-croatia.org)\n2014 - Building RESTApi with Symfony2 Workshop-  PHPSummerCamp, Croatia\n2014 - ZgPHPConference 2014, Building SPA with Sf2 and NG\n\n\nIn my free time I am working on my PhD in Computer Science and contributing to Sylius (one of awesome contributors and evangelist of Sylius)\n\nHere is my company profile, where you can see some of my works: http://www.locastic.com/dl/locastic_company_profile_2013.pdf',1,1,'Antonio.PeriMaar541978f46c2be.jpg',0),(61,'Previous slides: https://speakerdeck.com/bastianhofmann/\nPrevious talk ratings: https://joind.in/user/view/11182\nFull speaking history: http://lanyrd.com/profile/bastianhofmann/','Bastian works as a Software Engineer at ResearchGate, the social network for researchers and scientists. There he is mainly responsible for designing the web frontend\'s software architecture and developing APIs. Before that he created the games and application platform and the APIs of the VZ-networks. When he is not developing stuff, he frequently speaks at international conferences on software architecture, scaling web applications and open standards and protocols.',1,1,'Bastian.Hofmann541a1fb8c008a.jpg',0),(62,'','Emanuil Slavov is working in software business for more than 13 years. He has worked with software in industries such as secure file transfers, email based network security, electronic money transactions, anti fraud techniques, social media. His main speciality is systems thinking about software testing and where it fits in the big picture. Helps organisations achieve quality software products by working with product managers, developers, quality assurance, operations.',1,1,'',0),(63,'','Andreas startet dabbling in programing in the 1980s, hacked through HTML and PERL in the 1990 and fell in love with PHP in 2001. Besides his family and work as software engineer and jack-of-all-trades at a german corporate publisher he still finds the time to run the PHP-Usergroup in Frankfurt/Main and maintain PHP.ug. To find a good solution he always wants to fully understand the problem.',1,1,'',0),(64,'I *may* need travel/hotel reimbursement, depends on job situations come January. Probably won\'t though :)','Davey Shafik is a full-time developer with over 14 years of experience in PHP and related technologies. He is a Community Engineer at Engine Yard and has written three books, numerous articles, and spoken at conferences the world over. He is best known for his books, the Zend PHP Certification Study Guide and PHP Master: Write Cutting Edge Code, and as the originator of PHP Archive (PHAR) for PHP 5.3.\n\nDavey is passionate about improving the tech community. He co-organizes the Prompt initiative (prompt.engineyard.com), dedicated to lifting the stigma surrounding mental health discussions, and has worked with PHPWomen since its inception.',0,0,'Davey.Shafik542638bdc806c.jpg',0),(65,'','Alessandro Nadalin is a seasoned technical leader, currently in Dubai working for Rocket Internet, who pays a lot of attention to enterprise patterns, methodologies and SOA.\nHe has been involved in projects for the italian government, Samsung, Nissan, ENI and in the e-commerce scene in the Middle East.\nWhen heâ€™s not working, you can find him speaking at some conference, riding his motorcycle, blogging or eating some indonesian food in the old side of Dubai.',1,1,'Alessandro.Nadalin541dd565ba888.jpeg',0),(66,'Even though I\'m relatively new to the community I have learned a lot through it and I would like to give back to it.\nI\'m a first time speaker, though I do plan on giving the talks that I\'m sending in at an earlier time. I\'m testing them out at work and hope I get a chance to do one or more during one of the many meet-ups (PHPBenelux or Symfony). This way I can build up some experience and get some feeling with standing in front of a crowd.\nI\'m also focussing more on the soft skills for these talks as my technical skills are far below the average PHPBenelux speakers (each and every one an inspiration).','Kenneth Schabrechts is a PHP developer at King Foo, a web development company based in Aarschot.  He\'s been working with PHP since 2010. Not only is he interested in the technical aspects of the field but also likes to explore and expand his soft skills.\nAfter learning so much thanks to the community he feels it is time to give back.\n\nIn his spare time he helps organise the HackerFuel meet-ups, ride his bike and spends time with his lovely wife and daughter.',0,1,'Kenneth.Schabrechts541de78e7a0f0.jpg',0),(67,'Prior experience for you to consider:\n\nDavid is an organizer of the annual Northeast PHP conference held in Boston, Massachusetts\n\nJoind.in Ratings\nhttp://joind.in/user/view/21749\n\nCinematic UX Interview\nhttp://2014.northeastphp.org/uploads/audio/kelleher-interview.mp3\n\nSemantic Web Talk\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SOnWncxJX6k&amp;t=1m57s\n\nStage Performance Experience\nhttp://panelpicker.sxsw.com/vote/42672\n\nCollege Lecturer Biography\nhttp://www.emerson.edu/academics/faculty-guide/profile/david-kelleher/239','David Kelleher is a college professor, multimedia artist, and freelance PHP/MySQL and UI developer with 15 years of industry experience, and is an organizer for the annual Northeast PHP Conference. As a digital production generalist, David has taught courses and given talks on diverse topics ranging from database optimization to visual effects production. He loves the intersection of the arts and emerging technologies, working on projects like a juggling gesture interface for electronic music theater.',1,1,'David.Kelleher541e4f72216b0.jpg',0),(68,'I\'ll likely come by train! As for reimbursements, I have said yes now, but it\'s possible that later discussion mean work will cover it.','Derick Rethans is a PHP internals expert, author of Xdebug and an OpenStreetMap and mapping enthusiast.\n\nHe has contributed in a number of ways to the PHP project, including the Xdebug debugging tool, and various extensions and additions. He\'s a frequent lecturer at conferences, the author of php|architect\'s Guide to Date and Time Programming, and the co-author of PHP 5 Power Programming. He is now working at MongoDB to work on the PHP driver for MongoDB.',1,1,'Derick.Rethans541f41b248a0c.jpg',0),(69,'','Co-founder and business developer of Netgen, eZ Publish CMS Specialist, eZ Publish Innovation Board member, @eZSummerCamp and @PHPSummerCamp organizer, recently digging deep into Symfony and Sylius',1,0,'Ivo.Luka542099c290e16.jpg',0),(70,'','Jachim Coudenys is a PHP developer at King Foo. Since discovering PHP in 2002 (4.1.0), his work and after-work activities brought him from the world of development to server management, development workflows, etcâ€¦ By reading and experiment, visiting user groups and conferences, he constantly tries to get better at solving various computer problems. Next to being a long-time member of PHPBenelux, he is co-organizer of PHP-WVL, a user group in West Flanders (BE).',0,1,'Jachim.Coudenys54211996bf797.jpg',0),(71,'I am one of the founders of the first Belgian local PHP User Group, PHP-WVL. Organising meetups and presenting each meetup, has greatly boosted my presence on a stage. Granted, the audience is not of a comparable size as a conference room. But once you have the confidence to talk to 30 people, the next 100 comes easier. Since my previous performance on PHPBenelux in 2012, I have now 2 years of experience teaching Ju-Jitsu to both children and adults. This has also helped greatly in containing my nerves and speaking up in front of an audience.','Tom is an all-round web developer with little over 10 years of experience between his first HTML page and his current position at King Foo. He has a very strong passion (and preference) for anything PHP and Javascript related. Coming from an age without frameworks, he knows how to handle raw code, and even finds pleasure in doing so. Tom is driven by a desire to constantly evolve and bring his skills to the next level. This brings him to conferences all around the world, and PHPBenelux meetings all around the country. When he\'s disconnected from the web, he enjoys spending time with his family, practicing his Ju-Jitsu skills, and playing couch potato.',0,1,'Tom.VanHerreweghe54211a7fc2f82.jpeg',0),(72,'','I am doing professional web developing since 2007.\n\nSince 2012 I\'m working at the german shopware AG responsible for the core development of our open source shopping system Shopware4 (https://github.com/ShopwareAG/shopware-4).',0,1,'Benjamin.Cremer5421666ab448f.jpg',0),(73,'Presented at PHPBenelux 2013 (unconf) and other conferences and user groups. More info at http://luka.muzinic.net/talks','Passionate about being a developer, teacher and mentor for newcomers into world of programming. Involved in organizing ZgPHP user group meetings, workshops and conferences. Currently working as senior software engineer for HomeExchange. Enjoys playing and watching odd and unpopular sports, at least in Croatia.',1,1,'Luka.Muzinic54218bef48f32.jpg',0),(74,'','Tobias is CTO at Sitewards in Frankfurt, who specialize in e-commerce solutions.\nPreviously he was well regarded as a freelance consultant and software architect. Over the past years he has built up a development team at Sitewards that thrives to be at the cutting edge of web development.\nWith passion of inspiring people he takes part in and speaks at conferences worldwide. He also publishes articles in a wide range of magazines, several blogs and has written a book about web security.',1,1,'Tobias.Zander542266e30424e.jpg',0),(75,'','Generic PHP Developer',0,0,'',0),(76,'','Dustin Whittle is a Developer Evangelist at AppDynamics where he focuses on helping organizations manage application performance. Before joining AppDynamics, Dustin was CTO at Kwarter, a consultant at SensioLabs, and developer evangelist at Yahoo!. He has experience building and leading engineering teams and working with developers and partners to scale to meet demand. When Dustin isn\'t working he enjoys flying, sailing, diving, golfing, and traveling around the world. Find out more at dustinwhittle.com or follow him @dustinwhittle.',1,1,'Dustin.Whittle5423419f4f256.jpg',0),(77,'','Beau Simensen (@beausimensen, beau.io) has been a professional polyglot programmer since 1998. He owns Dragonfly Development (dflydev.com), a consulting company, and is Co-founder and Chief Software Architect for REFLX Labs, a wearables startup out of Seattle. An active open-sourcer, he created Sculpin (sculpin.io) and helped create Stack PHP (stackphp.com). He is also the Sculpin representative to the PHP Framework Interoperability Group (PHP-FIG). Beau is a proponent of framework agnostic code. Unglue all the things!',1,1,'Beau.Simensen54234b3f372f1.jpg',0),(78,'','â€¢ MSCS Student @ Georgia Institute of Technology\nâ€¢ Senior Software Engineer @ Square Labs\nâ€¢ Research interests: Virtualization, Distributed Systems, Automated QA Systems\nâ€¢ Open Source Contributor: ZF2, Phing',0,1,'Victor.Farazdagi5423deae75a06.jpg',0),(79,'','Julien is a web&amp;system architect. He\'s been using PHP for a decade together with frameworks such as Symfony.\nHe is now working at SensioLabs and is a PHP contributor and PHP 5.5/5.6 release manager.\nHe tries to make PHP better and more efficient.',1,1,'Julien.PAULI54251e7c3b10d.jpg',0),(80,'I have spoken at Meet Magento, Magento Live, the IPC and the PhpUnconference. Some talks have been videoed so I can provide links if desired.','David is Senior Software Architect as Sitewards in Frankfurt Germany, who specialize in e-commerce solutions. His main passion is with Magento and other e-commerce software, having worked in that field for the past 7 years.\n\nHe also likes to champion developer welfare and enjoys a challenge with regular expressions.',1,1,'David.Manners54252b4405cb7.jpg',0),(81,'I would prefer to travel by train :-) Can book ticket myself and reimburse, that would be easiest - or i can check with Liip about sponsorship for the travel.','David Buchmann works at Liip AG as Symfony expert. He is maintaining the Symfony Content Management Framework, a core developper of the PHP content repository implementation Jackalope and co-author of the FOSHttpCacheBundle. When he is not coding, he enjoys travelling with his girlfriend, music and boardgames.',1,1,'David.Buchmann54257053c1914.jpg',1),(82,'','Aaron is a Polyhistoric man of the web. Currently Technical Architect on the Conde Nast Platform Team and a WordPress Core Committer, he works to improve developer happiness and is dedicated to making internet usable and enjoyable by everyone.',0,0,'Aaron.Jorbin54259a77bb4f7.jpeg',0),(83,'','Patrick has been into web technologies since the \"bad old days\" when animated GIFs were required on all sites and the BLINK tag still had some supporters. He suffered through several years of procedural programming in PHP4 before discovering the glories of OOP in PHP5. Patrick is a Senior Web Developer at POLITICO, and regularly works with Doctrine, Symfony, and several less fun technologies. After hours, he\'s the founder and organizer of the Lake / Kenosha County PHP Users Group.',1,1,'Patrick.Schwisow5425d80f0a882.jpg',0),(84,'','',1,1,'Kayla.Daniels5426218acb981.jpg',0),(85,'Coordinator and developer for the Open Source PHPOffice suite of libraries for PHP: PHPExcel, PHPWord, PHPPowerPoint, PHPProject and PHPVisio','Mark is Head of Design and Development at Innoved (Innovative Solutions for Education) Learning, based in Wigan; a company which (coincidentally) shares offices with his favourite Rugby League team, the 2013 Superleague and Challenge Cup winners, and which occasionally gets him free tickets to attend Warriors games.\n\nHe has been working in the computer software industry since before symbolics.com was registered as a domain name, before the term \"cyberspace\" was first used in fiction, when Linus Torvalds and Rasmus Lerdorf were still at high school, and Mrs. Zuckerberg had yet to give birth to a bouncing baby social network enabler; and has been developing for the Web in a variety of languages since the days when the Tim Berners-Lee\'s creation comprised less than 1,000 sites.\n\nOver those years, he has contributed to a number of open source projects: some still extant, others lost to history. Currently he is coordinator and lead developer for the PHPExcel library, and a coordinator and developer on the PHPOffice library suite (PHPWord, PHPPowerPoint, PHPProject and PHPVisio). Most recently, he has been working on new datastructures such as Tries, Quadtrees and Matrices; hoping that he\'ll be able to get them included in SPL.\n\nHis particular interests include PHP integration with office suites, Textual analysis, Geodata and geographic information systems, and \"big data\" and data analysis.',0,0,'Mark.Baker54269df66567d.jpg',0),(86,'','Stephan HochdÃ¶rfer currently holds the position of Head of Technology at bitExpert AG, a company specializing in software and mobile development. His primary focus is everything related to web development as well as automation techniques ranging from code generation to deployment automation.',1,1,'Stephan.Hochdrfer5428462165145.jpg',0),(87,'','Michael Cullum has been an open source contributor and PHP developer for the last nine years. He is an official team member at phpBB and works a lot with Symfony, PHP FIG and Composer.',1,1,'Michael.Cullum5428b25e6a1bb.jpg',0),(88,'Recent talks:\n- IBM SmartCloud for PHP developers workshop (September 2013 - Hebrew)\n- AWS Summit Tel Aviv 2014 Bar Takeover - Zend Server on AWS Marketplace (September 2014 - English)\n- IBM Linux on Power (September 2014 - Hebrew)\n- IBM SmartCloud handson workshop (August 2014 - Hebrew)\n- DPC 2013 - Zend Developer Cloud Demo (June 2013 - English)\n- AWS Summit Tel Aviv 2011 - Introduction to Zend Developer Cloud (November 2011 - English)\n- ZendCon 2010 - Developing Modern Application with Amazon Cloud (November 2010 - English)','Sr. Director of Technology and Cloud Infrastructure at Zend technologies and a Zend Certified Engineer since 2005. I am in charge of driving execution on Zendâ€™s Cloud initiative and managing the IT and eBusiness teams. In the last 8 years I have been leading the technological teams at Zend including all web sites design and development, hosting, IT strategy and infrastructure. Before joining Zend, I led web development teams in various companies in Israel and has more than 12 years of Web and PHP development experience.',1,1,'Boaz.Ziniman54294a0451bcc.jpg',0),(89,'','Alvaro Videla works as Developer Advocate for RabbitMQ/Pivotal. Before moving to Europe he used to work in Shanghai where he helped building one of Germany biggest dating websites. He co-authored the book \"RabbitMQ in Action\" for Manning Publishing. Some of his open source projects can be found here: http://github.com/videlalvaro. Apart from code related stuff he likes traveling with his wife, listening/playing music and reading books.\nYou can find him on Twitter as @old_sound.',1,1,'Alvaro.Videla542969d47fa9c.jpeg',0),(90,'','I\'m me',0,0,'Martin.deKeijzer542969cd6b2eb.jpg',0),(91,'My company, New Relic, can cover all of my travel costs. :)','Noelle is a seasoned Community and Developer Relations Manager with a special place in her heart for open source.  She currently spends her days at New Relic running meetups, user groups, hackathons, and other Community Programs after previously working at Engine Yard and NextSpace. \n\nOriginally from the San Francisco Bay Area, Noelle spends her free time playing guitar, recovering her HTML &amp; PHP skills, reading , and trying to find the best burrito in Oakland.',0,0,'Noelle.Daley5429a9e4e592b.jpg',0),(92,'','Brandon has been a software developer since 2003. Ever since discovering that he could use software to automate routine tasks, heâ€™s been hooked. Brandon is passionate about software development, and is an expert teacher and author on object-oriented development practices.\n\nBrandon blogs, speaks and writes regularly about software development topics. Brandon worked for Mozilla on the Socorro project, working daily to make Firefox better. Brandon now runs his own company, teaching, speaking and writing about software topics, along with occasional freelancing. Brandon is also an instrument rated private pilot and enjoys traveling.',1,1,'Brandon.Savage542ab26cd4971.jpg',0),(93,'I can fly out of BWI, or from IAD or DCA ... BWI is just preferred, but often the others are cheaper.\n\nI am a seasoned presenter with over 45 conferences (and 60+ presentations) under my belt, with a 5-star average rating on joind.in.','Eli has been building Web Applications for over 19 years and fell in love with PHP the day that PHP 4 was released. Since then he\'s been a strong advocate for PHP and used it in every project he\'s work on.  He is currently the Managing Editor and Conference Chair for php[architect] and Founding Partner &amp; CTO of musketeers.me. He is also an avid writer (blogs, articles and books), and has spoken at numerous conferences.',1,1,'Eli.White542ab6b831b00.jpg',0),(94,'','Alex Bilbie is a software developer and devops ninja. He is a founding member of The PHP League of Extraordinary Packages and is currently writing his first book - OAuthello, a book about OAuth.\n\nAlex writes about life as a developer on his blog, is an active FOSS contributor and is an advocate of open data and it\'s potentials.\n\nHe is a former university researcher and lecturer on software development.',1,1,'Alex.Bilbie542afb7046b2e.jpg',0),(95,'','Joeri Sebrechts is the lead web developer at mcs.fm, a software and services vendor specializing in real estate, facility and workplace management. He has been spearheading the effort to deliver a large enterprise web application suite used in over 60 countries. He is always trying to figure out better ways to build software, and has never met a piece of software that couldn\'t be improved further. He is a local Antwerp resident who lives together with his wife, son and cat, but not necessarily always in that order.',0,0,'Joeri.Sebrechts542b0183c8218.jpg',0),(96,'I\'ll probably drive or take a train.','Damien Seguy has been contributing to PHP across three continentsÂ : translated documentation in France, secured applications in Canada and promoted Open Source in China. He provides pragmatic approach to code industrialisation and reviews. Most recently returning to Europe, he is CTO at exakat, automating PHP code audits with fast tools and cutting edge technology.',1,1,'Damien.Seguy542b08eb4e3f0.jpg',0),(97,'','',0,1,'Nick.deGroot542b22751c045.jpg',0),(98,'I\'ve had the opportunity to speak at Zendcon twice as well as the Austin stop on the CodeWorks tour a few years ago, and I\'ll be speaking at PHPWorld in November 2014. I\'m really digging the growth of the regional PHP conferences and would love the chance to contribute to PHP Benelux! I\'d be happy to do multiple talks to offset travel costs.','Josh Butts is the Director of Development at Offers.com, located in Austin, Texas. In addition to nearly a decade in the trenches of e-commerce at Offers.com, he is also the organizer of Austin PHP, one of the largest PHP user groups in the US. Josh has taught several classes in PHP and enjoys the opportunity to share his experiences with the PHP community.',1,1,'Josh.Butts542b30d94dc94.jpg',0),(99,'','David works at Heroku, a cloud platform as a service headquartered in San Francisco. He was already building applications for the Web when the dot-com bubble burst, and went on to co-own a software consultancy before exploring the e-commerce and Berlin startup scene. Based in Munich, Germany, he is a regular speaker at technology conferences around the world and an avid fan of all things fast or exciting.',0,0,'David.Zuelke542b32b0c56c3.jpg',0),(100,'','I believe that the best working place must be one where communication flows - from clients and company direction, to development layers - and where people feel free and involved enough to talk, share and experiment. As Lookatitude CEO I like to think Iâ€™m the one who firstly opens the door for such environment, and who ultimately drives change within the company.\n\nMy main functions include presiding all day-to-day operations, being close to clients and teams, helping everyone making the most appropriate decisions.\n\nIn 2012 I had the chance to bring Rocket Internet to Portugal and built its Tech Center in Porto. It was certainly a footprint in Portugal IT history that none can erase: in just a couple of months, me and a small founding team were able to provide the necessary recruitment, training, equipment, infrastructures and assets for more than 140 people. \nThe experience in Rocket Internet Tech Center as Managing Director and CTO sure gave me the opportunity to deal with all kind of international businesses at a large scale, different cultures and timezones. It also matured me to work between many bright, committed professionals who proved that things done fast could be also good.\n\nMy technical background and experience enables me to lead, motivate and support the development teams at any phase - from the initial tech decisions and design iteration, to the assurance of product and service quality. I recruit dedicated professionals and take them to follow the best practices of the industry, thus building surely efficient and reliable teams.\n\nIn parallel, I provide IT consulting - that is, if you need a hand in architecture design, development, team creation or project management, I can help.\n\nSpecialties: entrepreneurship, start-ups, business development, strategy, international business, web and mobile development, agile and lean methodologies, team management, system architecture design, e-commerce, productivity apps',1,1,'Miguel.Pinto542b37973025b.JPG',0),(101,'','Php Developer for 15 years. Currently working on modern rest api design. Big symfony fan and open source project supporter',0,1,'',0),(102,'Departure airport could also be MXP or LIN depending on which is cheaper :-)\nDon\'t need help with hotel if I find a place to crash','Software engineer, working with PHP since 2005 and now CTO at Ideato.\nI have broad interests in several aspects of software development like automation, quality and testing.\nI\'m co-author of \"PHP Best Practices\", published by FAG in 2012. Serial speaker @phpday, you can find some of my talks on https://joind.in/user/view/188',1,1,'Michele.Orselli542bb17a077f2.jpg',0),(103,'','A 15 year veteran of PHP development, from being a one mand band web developer, via focusing on PHP development in a team environment to being a technical analyst. \n\nI founded ZgPHP, PHP user group based in Zagreb and WebCamp, a language agnostic web development conference held in Zagreb and organized by multiple user groups. \n\nBesides speaking on local events (Zagreb,Belgrade &amp; Vienna) I\'we spoke in international conferences too (PHPDay Verona 2014 &amp; PHPCon Poland 2014).',1,1,'Miro.Svrtan542c517fa057e.jpg',1),(104,'','Beth Tucker Long is a PHP developer and advocate at Code Climate (http://www.codeclimate.com) and co-organizer of Madison PHP (http://www.madisonphp.com). You can find her on Twitter (@e3betht) or on her blog (http://www.alittleofboth.com). She runs Treeline Design (http://www.treelinedesign.com), a web development company, and Playlist Event Music - (http://www.playlisteventmusic.com), a DJ company, along with her husband, Chris.',0,0,'Beth.TuckerLong542ea7515aa1a.png',0),(105,'Spoken at MongoDB Belgium meetup, Laravel Brussels meetup (2x), LaraCon EU in Amsterdam, and maybe at the PHPBenelux meetup at Nucleus.','Master in Science by education, PHP developer at madewithlove, previously at Darwin Analytics. Experience with CodeIgniter, FuelPHP, Symfony and Laravel. Co-creator Ghendetta.be and organiser of MongoDB Belgium meetups and one-time organiser of Laravel Brussels meetup.',0,0,'Hannes.VanDeVreken542f15562769b.jpeg',0),(106,'Will be driving from the Netherlands, so no airport needed ;) Will add a picture later, don\'t seem to have one that is both a bit respectable and fits the requirements hahaha','PHP Enthousiast with a love for complex systems and project dynamics. Currently working as Team Lead for Ibuildings. Firm believer that software should focus on solving problems in a value adding way.  Feeling strangely comfortable out of the box. Always up for a chat, preferably with coffee or beer.',0,1,'',0),(107,'','I\'m a developer who turned to the dark Ops-side. Passionate about DevOps, collaboration, automation and scalability.',0,0,'Mattias.Geniar542fe9d663cbe.jpg',0),(108,'','I am a Jadu Engineer. I started working with PHP shortly after PHP 5 was released. Initially working with Joomla and over time starting playing with ZF1 and later with Symfony2. \nA few years later I started organising the PHP East Midlands User Group (@PHPem) in Leicester, UK.',0,1,'Antonis.Pavlakis543017e35068c.jpg',0),(109,'http://lanyrd.com/profile/raulfraile/','Software engineer at Acilia specialised in PHP and Symfony2. SensioLabs Symfony Certified Developer and PHP Zend Certified Engineer. I hold a BS degree in Computer Science and I am currently a MSc(Res) student in Computing Technologies, focused on data compression, cryptography and steganography. Created LadybugPHP, an extensible PHP dumper. Love reading and learning new stuff every day. Proud dad.',1,1,'Raul.Fraile54307de36390e.jpg',0),(110,'','With over 10 years of experience in PHP, I live in the sunny Barcelona. After a couple of years working as Development Trainer, helping other developers to increase their development skills, I currently work as Software Architect. More confortable with backend tasks, I\'m obsessed with best practices in general and testing in particular.',1,1,'Jose.Armesto5431182612d6c.JPG',0);
