INSERT INTO `talks` VALUES (2,10,'Test 123','This talk will test if entering talk submissions work.','tutorial','handson','continuousdelivery',1,'','This is a test. Additional info field',0,0,0,'2014-09-02 22:44:55','2014-09-02 22:45:39'),(3,18,'Random talk title','This is a talk abstract....','regular','overview','testing',1,'http://www.slideshare.net/rtuin/phpday-automated-acceptance-testing-with-behat-and-mink','',0,0,0,'2014-09-03 12:38:39','2014-09-03 12:39:27'),(4,19,'Asynchronous PHP','PHP has emerged from itâ€™s dark past; just in time to learn from the advances in event-based programming languages/platforms. As a result; there is vast, untapped potential in developing event-based, real-time applications. Utilising emerging open-source projects, like ReactPHP and Ratchet, PHP developers can join the party.','regular','handson','other',1,'https://speakerdeck.com/chrispitt/async-php-redux','I have given this talk at PHP South Africa (April 2014) and PHP New Zealand (August 2014).',0,0,0,'2014-09-03 16:19:49','2014-09-03 16:21:55'),(5,19,'Better Than MVC','MVC is a design pattern which first became popular in the 1970s, yet many popular frameworks still use it today. This talk describes a few alternatives which can be a better fit for the web.','regular','overview','other',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-03 16:20:37','2014-09-03 16:21:43'),(6,19,'Creating a Programming Language','Programming is hard. Making programming languages is harder. Or so people think. The truth is that making a programming language is just a series of small steps, using regular language constructs. It\'s so easy, we\'ll make one in this talk.','regular','handson','other',0,'','This could easily be a workshop. I am giving this talk (50 minutes) at PHP South Africa, in October. This could easily be expanded to a workshop.',0,0,0,'2014-09-03 16:21:21','2014-09-03 16:25:04'),(7,19,'Defensive Programming','Defensive programming may sound like something your granddad did after the war, but it\'s key to reducing the number of bugs and increasing maintainability. We\'re going to look at what defensive programming is and some steps to doing it in PHP.','regular','overview','other',0,'https://speakerdeck.com/chrispitt/defensive-programming-redux','I have given this talk at multiple user-groups in multiple countries.',0,0,0,'2014-09-03 16:22:42','2014-09-03 16:25:17'),(8,21,'Tips&amp;tricks on using the Linux command line','Linux is, and probably will be for a long time, the OS of choice to deploy most web applications. But even with all the control-panels, admin-interfaces and management-tools out there, nothing will beat doing your work from the command line. During this talk I will show you a range of tips&amp;tricks for both the beginner and more advanced command line users to do the things you need to do. From piping and redirecting your output to building your own menu-system in a very easy way, to simple bash-tricks to make your life easier.','regular','overview','devlife',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-03 16:23:13','2014-09-03 21:19:04'),(9,19,'Introduction To Laravel','Laravel is a young and popular framework, built on Symfony goodness. In this workshop we will be introduced to the concepts that underpin the framework, as well as how to use it. We also look at where to find help when you get stuck, and many of the tools you can use to make your time with Laravel pleasing.','tutorial','handson','other',0,'https://speakerdeck.com/chrispitt/laravel-4-workshop','I have given this talk at PHP South Africa (April 2014), Dutch PHP Conference (June 2014), PHP New Zealand (August 2014) and privately.',0,0,0,'2014-09-03 16:23:42','2014-09-03 16:24:01'),(10,19,'Typed PHP','Strings, arrays and numbers are just second-class citizens in PHP-land. This talk describes how they can be extended to look like objects, and how clean and consistent APIs can be introduced so that you can be proud of your PHP code again.','regular','handson','other',0,'','I am also writing a book about this: leanpub.com/typedphp.',0,0,0,'2014-09-03 16:24:40','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(11,21,'Don\'t reboot, debug!','Nothing is showing up in the logs, everythings works fine on your development and acceptance environment, your unit-tests are all green and yet you\'ve got major issues on your production server. What to do? Restart apache? Reboot the system? Maybe we even add more machines? Hell no! We debug it Chuck Norris style! I will show you how you can use advanced (linux) tools like strace, iostat, gdb and even dtrace to figure out the bottlenecks in your system. Is it even your code that is buggy or can we easily identify other things that can go wrong? A free tip for those who don\'t attend this talk: never ever reboot or restart your system without knowing what caused the issue in the first place!','regular','indepth','virtualization',0,'https://speakerdeck.com/jaytaph/dont-reboot-debug-ipc','https://joind.in/talk/view/6939',0,0,0,'2014-09-03 16:25:26','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(12,21,'10 tips to start your own business and get the best job ever','Starting your own business seems easy: do the jobs you like, charge an insane amount of money for it, and get rich. But everybody who has started a business knows that this could not be further from the truth. \n\nIn this presentation I will discuss 10 tips on starting your own business and what you need in order to succeed as an independent contractor.','regular','overview','other',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-03 16:26:27','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(13,21,'Writing custom annotations in Symfony2','The SensioFrameworkExtraBundle enables some of the annotations we all use and love, like @route, @security, @cache and @template. But how does these annotations work internally, what makes them trigger and how can we create our own annotations to help create better and more flexible code even faster? In this presentation I will open up the framework, dive deep into its core, show you how they work and how to write your own custom annotations.','regular','indepth','phpfuture',0,'https://speakerdeck.com/jaytaph/custom-annotations-in-symfony2','This is a highly symfony2 centric presentation.',0,0,0,'2014-09-03 16:29:25','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(14,21,'Out of memory, or plenty to spare?','One of the hardest question to ask on a linux platform: how much memory does my application use. This is mostly because Linux is amazingly efficient when it comes to memory usage. But it comes with a price.\n\nDuring this very advanced presentation, we will talk about virtual spaces, MMUs, mmap(), shared, resident and virtual memory and how it all fits together on your servers.\n\nAfterwards, you will be one of few who can read tools like \"top\".','regular','overview','virtualization',0,'','This is a highly advanced subject, however it will be understandable by everybody who at least knows a bit about linux. \n\nIt mostly will dive into how Linux manages its memory, and how a process (multiple processes actually) can share memory, and how ultimately, you be able to read tools like \"top\" and \"free\" much  better',0,0,0,'2014-09-03 16:30:03','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(15,22,'Releasing your first open source library','This talk discusses the development processes required to begin and release a new open source project into the wild. It covers a number of the step a good developer should consider implementing as well as providing practical examples of how to do so. It also links the audience with resources and authority figures to follow if they wish to learn more about a particular step.\n\nThis talk was previously presented at PHP South Africa 2014 Joburg and was recorded: http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PqDOwUtd_hg','regular','handson','devlife',1,'http://www.slideshare.net/xsist10/releasing-your-open-source-project','Composer and Packagist, PHPUnit, PHP Code Sniffer (and a variety of other QA tools)\n\nhttps://joind.in/talk/view/10405',0,0,0,'2014-09-03 16:46:31','2014-09-03 17:09:25'),(16,22,'The security weak-points in our systems','A discussion about the security implications of 3rd party dependencies. This talk came out of a continued auditing project where software versions used in various hosting environments are monitored and correlated with vulnerability reports. While this talk is not PHP specific, it predominately covers common PHP libraries and applications and discusses concerns around current security practices. More importantly it comes with really scary graphs. This talk was originally presented at PHP South Africa 2013 Cape Town.','regular','overview','security',0,'http://www.slideshare.net/xsist10/php-sa-php-south-africa-2013','This talk puts the fear of version control and semantic versioning into a developer... or at least that\'s the plan.\n\nhttps://joind.in/talk/view/9462',0,0,0,'2014-09-03 16:47:17','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(17,25,'Abstract Filesystems, with Flysystem','In almost all of the applications we create in our day to day lives we work with filesystems. These days it\'s not just our local filesystem anymore. It\'s AWS S3, Dropbox, (S)FTP, or any other cloud filesystem provider. They all have their pros and cons. In this talk weâ€™ll go into several aspects of choosing and working with filesystems and how Flysystem helps you out in this process. We\'ll go over: technical debt, separation of concerns, domain vs implementation and how using an abstract filesystem can help you be flexible.','regular','overview','crossingphp',1,'http://www.slideshare.net/ikbenfrankdejonge/abstract-filesystems-with-flysystem','The talk has been rated on joind.in: joind.in/talk/view/11681\nI\'ve done this talk at a Laravel Meetup in Ghent (Belgium): http://www.meetup.com/Laravel-Brussels/events/189623102/\n\nBoth times the talk was very well received and sparked up a number of interesting conversations. I\'m improving the talk after each time, the next iteration will focus on how abstract filesystems will help you to adhere to the SOLID principles.\nAlthough I\'ve done this talk at Laravel related events, it\'s not tied to any framework.',0,0,0,'2014-09-03 17:04:15','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(18,22,'Cobbling with other peoples\' blood, sweat and components','This tutorial covers the quick assembly of new applications by taking advantage of the myriad of well documented and freely available components in the wild. I\'ll discuss the importance of decoupled libraries, extending interfaces and using traits rather than hacking, dependency injection (IoC) and the golden standard of re-usability.\n\nThe outcome is developers will be exposed to a variety of design patterns and framework concepts as well the source of a flexible event driven framework to tinker with built with components from a number of popular frameworks.','tutorial','indepth','phpfuture',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-03 17:07:16','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(19,26,'Advanced templating for beginners','We talk a lot about writing highly decoupled, dependency injectable, single responsibility classes and methods. And this stuff is ALL GOOD. But, are we thinking enough about what defines quality templates? How seriously are you taking security when writing your templates? How tightly are these templates coupled to the objects they use? This talk will show you how to write awesome, modern-day PHP templates. We\'ll look at new features you should be using, how to decouple templates from your business logic, where to best place your presentation logic and more.','regular','overview','other',0,'','Templates are an area of focus and expertise for me. I wrote the Plates (http://platesphp.com) library and have contributed to PHP: The Right Way on the topic. Templates don\'t tend to get much attention when it comes to \"best practices\", and yet there is certainly a right and wrong way to do them. This talk will be very helpful for beginners while still tweaking the interest of more seasoned developers.',0,0,0,'2014-09-03 17:31:00','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(20,26,'PHP, it\'s time to take design seriously','Us back-end developers aren\'t known for our design skills. We like to think it\'s a job for a different department. You know, those hipster front-end folk. But, are we missing out on something? PHP is certainly maturing as a language, but is our visual identity as a community lagging behind? This talk is all about stepping it up a notch. Come learn some practical ways that design can help improve both the image of your project, and also PHP as a whole.','regular','handson','ux',0,'','This talk comes from the perspective of a back-end developer who\'s been working in a highly creative environment for over a decade. While I don\'t call myself a designer, I certainly have a strong appreciation for it, and I\'ve picked up a few things along the way.\n\nToo often back-end developers \"give up\" on design before even trying. In this talk I\'ll show how non-creative people can do design by simply following some basic rules. I\'ll share some common tools that I use that make it much easier. I\'ll also share my experiences having recently worked on the design of some popular open-source projects, including the Slim Framework, The PHP-FIG, and The PHP League.',0,0,0,'2014-09-03 17:32:24','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(21,26,'Zero to The PHP League: The story of how Plates became a thing','It\'s one thing to write a quick library that you and maybe a few coworkers will only ever use. It\'s an entirely different thing to put your work out there for the entire PHP community to analyze, test, poke, benchmark and critique. While there is potential for this process to be incredibly rewarding it can also be quite intimidating. Wouldn\'t it be nice to see what this looks like before you jump in? Come see how Plates (platesphp.com) became a thing last year and learn how to make your open-source PHP package a success.','regular','indepth','other',1,'','This talk comes from the perspective of a developer who has just gone through the process of releasing an open-source PHP project. As I share my personal story I plan to teach other developers what I learned along the way, and give practical advise on how they can successfully open-source their own PHP package. This talk includes a nice mix of soft skills and technical information, touching on many key areas of modern PHP development.\n\nThe main talking points are:\n\n1. Why one might want to open-source a package\n2. How to design an API that developers will actually WANT to use\n3. The modern PHP coding standards needed to be taken seriously by other developers\n4. How to market the package, including naming, documentation, design and getting the word out\n5. Challenges around maintaining an open-source project, including navigating pull requests, backwards compatibility and more',0,0,0,'2014-09-03 17:33:24','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(22,28,'Bringing Browscap Back To Life','The Browser Capabilities Project (a.k.a. â€œbrowscap.iniâ€ or the â€œget_browserâ€ function in PHP) has been around since 1998 and provides databases of browser information for user agents. In September 2012, founder Gary Keith left the project and it seemed like the project would be abandoned. In this talk, weâ€™ll look at how open sourcing the project brought it back to life, the challenges we overcame and the technical progress we made. If youâ€™ve been using Browscap for years or you want to find out more about it, this session will give you insights into the bright future of the Browser Capabilities Project.','regular','overview','other',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-03 18:23:48','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(23,28,'Dip Your Toes in the Sea of Security','Security is an enormous topic, and itâ€™s really, really complicated. If youâ€™re not careful, youâ€™ll find yourself vulnerable to any number of attacks which you definitely donâ€™t want to be on the receiving end of. This talk will give you just a taster of the vast array of things there is to know about security in modern web applications, such as writing secure PHP web applications and securing a Linux server. Whether you are writing anything beyond a basic brochure website, or even developing a complicated business web application, this talk will give you insights to some of the things you need to be aware of.','regular','overview','security',0,'http://www.slideshare.net/asgrim1/dip-your-toes-in-the-sea-of-security-php-dorset','I was asked to give a talk on security at the PHP Dorset user group meetup, at which I received really encouraging feedback on Joind.in (which you can see on https://joind.in/talk/view/11353). You can watch a video of this talk here: http://vimeo.com/97645043 .\n\nI have also since been asked to present this talk at PHP Cambridge meetup early next year too!',0,0,0,'2014-09-03 18:24:23','2014-09-26 14:44:36'),(24,28,'Low Latency Logging with RabbitMQ','When all hell breaks loose with your in-production application, what do you do? Panic? Enable xdebug in production? Throw some var_dumps on the live code? Sound familiar?\n\nThere is a smarter way of controlling these situations: An effective application log can tell you exactly what is going wrong, and possibly even how to fix it, keeping downtime to an absolute minimum.\n\nIn this talk youâ€™ll discover how to put your application logging into overdrive using a tried and tested method known as Low Latency Logging. Using the power of RabbitMQ, youâ€™ll discover that a great logging architecture is a low-cost investment in your application that will always pay off in the long run.','regular','overview','architectures',0,'http://www.slideshare.net/asgrim1/low-latency-logging-with-rabbitmq-brno-php-cz-20th-sep-2014','I gave this talk at BrightonPHP with great feedback (can be seen at https://joind.in/talk/view/9928)\n\nI also gave this talk at PHP London too :), and received some good feedback (sadly not on joind.in), for example:\nhttps://twitter.com/johannacherry/status/507871753096675328\nhttps://twitter.com/d3r/status/507857328230899712\nhttps://twitter.com/craigwillis85/status/507663637319000064\n\nMost recently, I presented this talk at the Brno PHP Conference 2014 in Czech Republic.',0,0,0,'2014-09-03 18:25:17','2014-09-26 14:44:46'),(25,28,'Adding 1.21 Gigawatts to Applications with RabbitMQ','As your application grows, you soon realise you need to break up your application into smaller chunks that talk to each other. You could just use web services to interact, or you could take a more robust approach and use the message broker RabbitMQ.\n\nIn this talk, we will take a look at the techniques you can use to vastly enhance inter-application communication, learn about the core concepts of RabbitMQ, cover how you can scale different parts of your application separately, and modernise your development using a message-oriented architecture.','regular','handson','architectures',0,'http://www.slideshare.net/asgrim1/practical-message-queuing-using-rabbitmq-phpem-3rd-july-2014','I\'ll be presenting this talk at the December Nomad PHP EU meetup! :)\nhttps://nomadphp.com/2014/09/19/nomadphp-2014-12-eu/',0,0,0,'2014-09-03 18:25:50','2014-09-26 14:43:37'),(26,28,'Writing Reusable Zend Framework 2 Components','This talk is a culmination of best practises, tips, tricks and general knowledge I have learnt about Zend Framework 2, and modern PHP in general. The talk will explore several commonly accepted conventions when it comes to writing Zend Framework 2 modules, important Object Orientated Programming practices, and shows how to save yourself and others time in the long run - for example by not re-inventing the wheel.','regular','handson','other',0,'','This talk assumes the audience has at least a basic understanding of ZF2. The talk is based on a short book I am writing on the same subject, which is a work in progress at https://leanpub.com/zf2-reusable',0,0,0,'2014-09-03 18:26:27','2014-09-26 14:43:54'),(27,30,'The why and the how of moving to 5.5/5.6','With PHP 5.6 out and many production environments still running 5.2 or 5.3, it\'s time to paint a clear picture on why everyone should move to 5.5 and 5.6 and how to get code ready for the latest version of PHP. In this talk, we\'ll look at some handy tools and techniques to ease the migration.','regular','indepth','phpfuture',0,'https://joind.in/talk/view/9068','Old version of the talk : https://joind.in/talk/view/9068 - now updated for 5.6',1,0,0,'2014-09-03 22:40:10','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(28,30,'Bringing bright ideas to life','Who would have thought putting 140 charachter messages about one\'s life online or having a virtual farm game could ever be popular ? Then again, many of us have those weird (but sometimes brilliant) ideas.\nBut no matter how incredible your ideas might be, getting them launched successfully takes more than writing lots of php code, smacking a sleek design on it and dropping it on a server.\nSo what does it take ? Where do most ideas crashland and how can you avoid making the same mistakes and transform your ideas into reality ? We\'ll look at what steps are needed to make a service successful and sustainable.','regular','overview','other',0,'','A business talk with lots of geeky content, or simply put : how can a geek with bright ideas build something that works and sells, not as in \"I wrote code, it should work, let\'s launch and crash\", but something that works in the long run as well.',1,0,0,'2014-09-03 22:41:19','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(29,30,'My app is secure... I think','With more and more sites falling victim to data theft, you\'ve probably read the list of things (not) to do to write secure code. But what else should you do to make sure your code and the rest of your web stack is secure ? In this tutorial we\'ll go through the basic and more advanced techniques of securing your web and database servers, securing your backend PHP code and your frontend javascript code. We\'ll also look at how you can build code that detects and blocks intrusion attempts and a bunch of other tips and tricks to make sure your customer data stays secure.','tutorial','handson','security',0,'','This is a topic that\'s often neglected at conferences, but one that\'s crucial in this age of data theft incidents. This is not a theoretical tutorial about OWASP, but a practical guide to securing the full stack from operating system to code.\nThis is a shorter version of a 2 day training we provide.',1,0,0,'2014-09-03 22:42:15','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(30,30,'From typing to test to testing the type','With unit testing being almost a given nowadays, most developers take the many pitfalls and testing gaps for granted. In this session, I\'ll go through the most critical pitfalls, discussing the dangers and solutions to each. Then we\'ll have a look at a new PHPUnit extension which adds another level of code consistency testing, while at the same automatically verifying the quality of your inline documentation, saving you some valuable time (and manual labour).','regular','indepth','testing',0,'','Not a \"what is unit testing ?\" session, but a session to point out the dangers of testing the wrong way, as well as some new fancy stuff that helps improving documentation (something most developers hate doing)',1,0,0,'2014-09-03 22:43:22','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(31,30,'Creating fast, dynamic ACLs in ZF2','Designing an ACL system in Zend Framework is easy enough, but when a small application grows, ACL rules become more complex and Zend\\Permissions\\ACL quickly becomes a pain. Moreover, designing an ACL system from scratch for every single project can\'t be considered best practice.\nThe alternative : a dynamic, reflection-based ACL system, with a caching bonus. Sounds complicated? Don\'t worry, it\'s easy to setup and a lot easier to manage!','regular','indepth','other',0,'http://static.zend.com/topics/dynamicacl-slideshare-110617093048-phpapp01.pdf','Presented as a Zend Webinar in 2011 for the ZF1 system, now redesigned for ZF2.\nRatings for the webinar : http://speakerrate.com/talks/7782-creating-fast-dynamic-acls-in-zend-framework',1,0,0,'2014-09-03 22:46:53','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(32,31,'Talmudic Maxims to Maximize Your Growth as a Software Developer','Youâ€™ve been programming for a while now.  Youâ€™re beginning to feel that youâ€™ve got a handle on things but at the same time canâ€™t escape the feeling that youâ€™ve somehow plateaued in your growth as a software developer.  In this talk Yitzchok, a rabbinic scholar and software developer, shares the â€œwisdom of the sagesâ€ as practical, actionable advice â€“ strategies and tactics â€“ that you can use to reinvigorate your growth as a software developer.','regular','overview','other',1,'','Alternate Title: \"Everything that I Really Needed to Know, I Learned in Rabbinical School\"\n\nObviously, â€˜Talmudic Maximsâ€™ plays a role in the presentation only as a metaphor and will be limited and simple â€“ no prior knowledge needed. \n\nOne example of a Talmudic maxim which offers practical advice for young software developers:\n\n\"I learned much from my teachers, but I learned even more from my colleagues, and from my students I learned most of all.\"\n		(Rabbi Chanina, Babylonian Talmud, Tractate Taâ€™anis 7A)\n\nThis maxim would be used to discuss sharing oneâ€™s knowledge â€“ blog posts, mentoring, teaching, presenting, etc. â€“ and the impact it has upon oneâ€™s own growth.\n\nOther topics covered will include:\nâ€¢	Rubber Ducking\nâ€¢	Pair Coding\nâ€¢	Apprenticeship Models\nâ€¢	Minimizing Context Switching\nâ€¢	Maintaining Context\nâ€¢	The Importance of Consistency\nâ€¢	Learning Heuristics\nâ€¢	Vacational vs Vocational Coding\nâ€¢	Generalism vs Specialism\nâ€¢	Embracing Community\nâ€¢	You Are Not Your Tools\nâ€¢	Learning by Doing\nâ€¢	Learning by Teaching\nâ€¢	Pragmatic vs Dogmatic Application\nâ€¢	Youâ€™re Never too Old\nâ€¢	Lack of CS Background is not Impediment to Greatness\nâ€¢	The Value of Small Beginnings',0,0,0,'2014-09-04 02:37:58','2014-09-17 04:36:50'),(33,32,'PHP 7: because elephants have to move forward','2014 was a big year for PHP. In addition to the annual 5.6 release, PHP now has a new major version number and a raft of intriguing features that have either been committed to Git or are being actively discussed.\n\nIn this talk, Iâ€™ll discuss PHP 7, the engine changes previously known as â€œphpngâ€, and where this is likely to lead in terms of a stable release. Iâ€™ll also talk about the likely tradeoffs in terms of backward compatibility and how it is likely to be handled, with reference to the lessons learned from other languages that have tried the same trick with varying degrees of success (from Perl to Python to Ruby).','regular','overview','phpfuture',1,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-04 04:58:36','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(34,32,'Welcome to the (home office) jungle','Iâ€™m on my third stint as a remote worker, and like Goldilocks, Iâ€™m finding the third time is the charm â€” not too hot, not too cold. Iâ€™ll dissect the good, the bad, and the ugly: the happy times, the tears, and the many things, both large and small, employers and employees alike can do to make remote work as smooth as working in an office.','regular','overview','devlife',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-04 04:59:04','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(35,34,'Using Zend Framework 2 as a Freelancer','Zend Framework 2 has the reputation as being the enterprise framework of choice. But is it right for the freelancer or small team? Is there too much overhead for a team of only a few people? Can a small team use it to rapidly build client applications? This talk shows that, whilst feature rich, Zend Framework 2 is as much suited to smaller development teams, even freelancers, as it is for large, more corporate, development teams, by looking at 5 key areas of the framework.','regular','handson','devlife',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-04 08:53:34','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(36,34,'Prototyping and Production Development in Zend Framework','Are you aware of how to rapidly prototype applications using Zend Framework 2? Are you aware that you can, but that there\'s also a clear path to refactor the prototype, to code which is production ready and maintainable? This talk looks at 5 areas of Zend Framework 2, working through this scenario, showing developers how to both rapidly prototype an application, and how to migrate the prototype code to a production ready application.','regular','handson','devlife',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-04 08:55:17','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(37,35,'Reasoned PHP','Logic programming combines ideas from computation and proof theory to create a programming paradigm that is very different from the mainstream. Imagine taking any existing program, and swapping its inputs and outputs. By constructing programs in a relational way, they become a relational database of sorts. The execution of the program corresponds to a proof search.\n\nReasoned PHP is an embedded logic programming system based on miniKanren. The core of the system is very small, but extremely powerful. Use logic to run your programs backwards!','regular','overview','other',0,'https://igor.io/2014/08/06/reasoned-php.html','The reasoned-php project on GitHub: https://github.com/igorw/reasoned-php',0,0,0,'2014-09-04 10:15:17','2014-09-28 21:56:29'),(38,37,'Urban Legends: What You Code Makes You Who You Are','If you were a carpenter, would your skills at building be more important than the tools you use to build? Skills, right?  Tools are just a means to an end.  So why do developers think the language they use defines the problems they solve?\n\nThis talk will take a look at misconceptions across the board, some experiences, both positive and negative, people have had crossing barriers to new languages, and show some of the benefits thinking of one\'s self as a coder and not a \"Ruby coder\" or a \"PHP dev\" can have on being a better problem solver.','regular','overview','crossingphp',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-04 16:38:39','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(39,37,'When You Aren\'t Sure If You Are Who You Thought You Were','For those unfamiliar with the concept, impostor syndrome is defined as feelings of inadequacy that persist even in the face of information indicating the opposite is true. This talk will take a look at what Impostor Syndrome is and some keys on how to combat it.','regular','overview','phpfuture',1,'','FULL DISCLOSURE: I am not a mental health professional. If you feel you need the advice of a professional, please seek such advice from a clinical physician. I\'m always willing to help, but I do not have a degree or license to dispense medical advice.',0,0,0,'2014-09-04 16:40:03','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(40,37,'Meetup Groups: Act Locally - Think Globally','There are thousands of local tech groups worldwide. Sadly, many suffer along, become stagnant, some even die off. How can you make your local tech group better and in so doing, improve the global Tech Community?\n\nThis talk focuses on the human side of getting a group together and making it successful so the members, as a group can contribute to the larger community. It is a universally useful guide to improving all parts of the tech community, starting on a local level.','regular','overview','other',1,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-04 16:41:09','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(41,38,'Secure PHP Development Bootcamp','The web is becoming a more and more dangerous place every day. You, as a PHP application developer, need to be armed with the tools and knowledge to make your applications as secure as possible. Come get hands-on training in applying secure design principles, testing code for vulnerabilities and fixing the problems we find together. Weâ€™ll be using a vulnerable application to illustrate some of the most common vulnerabilities like cross-site scripting, SQL injection and other notables from the OWASP Top 10 list. Youâ€™ll walk away with a grasp of good secure coding practices and a platform for future experimentation.','tutorial','handson','security',0,'','This talk could possibly go a full day depending on how much content is needed. I\'ll provide a vulnerable application that can be set up ahead of time by the user (or possibly on donated hosting?) where they can follow along and have something to take with them at the end.',0,0,0,'2014-09-04 17:31:15','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(42,38,'Auth All The Things','With so many potential threats lurking out on the web these days, keeping your application secure is more important than ever. One of the most important points to secure is your application\'s \"front door\": your authentication and authorization. Identifying your users can be a tricky process. Let me help guide you through some of the common mistakes and how to prevent making them, hardening your application even more. We\'ll talk about authentication and authorization types, libraries and some best practices you can use in your every day development.','regular','overview','security',0,'','While this talk is on a similar topic to the \"Auth*: Dispelling the Myths\" talk given before, it will include more practical examples than just the theory of the previous talk.',0,0,0,'2014-09-04 17:31:47','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(43,38,'Securing the (PHP) INI','In PHP development, securing your code, the pieces that your users interact with, is gaining more and more traction. There\'s another side to the same coin that needs to be considered, however: server configuration. Inside your php.ini file are keys to providing additional security for your application without much impact to your code. I\'ll walk through several of the most important settings and how they should be configured for optimum protection.','regular','overview','security',0,'','This talk will build on the work done with my iniscan library (https://github.com/psecio/iniscan) but will explain the details and implications behind each point, not just run through a quick list.',0,0,0,'2014-09-04 17:32:25','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(44,38,'The Beginner\'s Guide to Alternative Authorization','It\'s pretty common for developers to go with the same kinds of authentication handling when they\'re creating their applications with permissions and groups. Unfortunately, as applications grow in side an interact with other systems, this kind of system sags under the weight of its own technical debt. Follow along with me as I talk about some alternatives to the typical RBAC authorization including attribute-based, multifactor, pattern-based and federated identity providers.','regular','overview','security',0,'','This talk will go more in-depth than my other Auth talk proposal and is a bit less about the PHP-specific code examples.',0,0,0,'2014-09-04 17:32:54','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(45,35,'Lisp','What would it mean to build a programming language from the ground up? What if a language were so small, yet powerful enough to compute anything? How about a language capable of extending its own syntax with new features?\n\nLisp, a language that changes the way you think about programs and solving problems. It will bend your mind and take you down the rabbit hole!','regular','overview','other',0,'https://speakerdeck.com/igorw/lisp-laraconeu','I gave this talk at laraconeu: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FRaNUsiD_BA\n\nhttp://joind.in/talk/view/11697',0,0,0,'2014-09-05 09:28:05','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(46,39,'A lap around PHPOffice','The PHPOffice organization on GitHub has several great class libraries available for working with various file formats like Excel, ODF, Word, PowerPoint, HTML and so on. In this talk, weâ€™ll have a look at some common tasks we can perform with these libraries as well as give some hints to more advanced usage such as using PHPExcel as a calculation engine. Lots of demos! Promised!','regular','overview','other',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-05 17:31:58','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(47,40,'Refactoring 101','We hate to refactor. (The practice of altering code to make it cleaner, simpler, and sometimes faster, while not altering functionality.) Adam Culp will talk about how to do it better, and will discuss: When to refactor. How to refactor. Why refactor. How a refactor can help us write better code in the future. A common methodology and steps to follow while refactoring, and resources to help us all on our refactor journey.','regular','overview','other',1,'http://www.slideshare.net/adamculp/refactoring-23666462','https://joind.in/talk/view/9273#comments\nhttps://joind.in/talk/view/9344#comments\nhttps://joind.in/talk/view/10465#comments',0,0,0,'2014-09-05 21:38:33','2014-09-05 21:41:15'),(48,40,'Refactoring Legacy Code','Faced with legacy code many decided to rewrite, thinking it will be easier, for many reasons this can be wrong. Adam Culp will talks about the entire journey of refactoring a legacy code base. We will begin with assessment and why, cover planning how and when, discuss execution and testing, and provide step-by-step examples. Attendees will gain insight and tips on how to handle their own pile of code and refactor happy.','regular','overview','other',1,'http://www.slideshare.net/adamculp/refactoring-legacy-code','https://joind.in/talk/view/11658#comments\nhttps://joind.in/talk/view/11661#comments\nhttps://joind.in/talk/view/11467#comments',0,0,0,'2014-09-05 21:41:01','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(49,40,'Essential Git for Developers','With so many \"Git how-tos\" out there, where to start? This is not another one of those. Instead Adam Culp will give a practical walk through the development cycle and how to use Git as the source control. From initialization of a repository, adding, staging, cloning, and checkout, we will walk through a sample project and how most developers actually use Git to manage the workflow.','regular','overview','vcs',0,'http://www.slideshare.net/adamculp/essential-git-fordevelopers','https://joind.in/talk/view/9966#comments\nhttps://joind.in/talk/view/8688#comments\nhttps://joind.in/talk/view/10046#comments',0,0,0,'2014-09-05 21:42:25','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(50,40,'Clean Application Development','No matter what level of development we are at in our careers we all face a daily battle to write good code for ourselves and others, deliver finished applications fast to satisfy business, and ensure everything is properly tested to prevent end-user fails. In this talk Adam Culp will discuss what â€œclean application developmentâ€ is, and how it can help us win those battles. The talk will provide practical and usable examples to, integrate into your workflow, and continue to grow into good habits.','regular','overview','other',0,'http://www.slideshare.net/adamculp/clean-application-development','https://joind.in/talk/view/9831#comments\nhttps://joind.in/talk/view/9050#comments\nhttps://joind.in/talk/view/10439#comments',0,0,0,'2014-09-05 21:43:31','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(51,40,'Vagrant for Virtualized Development','Adam Culp introduces Vagrant to create and manage virtualized development environments, making it easier to mirror production servers and remove the \"works on my machine\" troubles. Then will lightly cover using advanced provisioning like Chef or Puppet to make adding multiple development environments and servers easier and faster. We will also introduce other tools to use with Vagrant making it even easier to use.','regular','overview','continuousdelivery',0,'http://www.slideshare.net/adamculp/vagrant-for-virtualizeddevelopment','https://joind.in/talk/view/9343#comments\nhttps://joind.in/talk/view/9149#comments\nhttps://joind.in/talk/view/10538#comments',0,0,0,'2014-09-05 21:44:56','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(52,40,'Practical PHP Deployment with Jenkins','When pushes to production fail the \"blame game\" starts between developers and devops, then everyone scurries to figure out what happened...fast! Adam Culp will show how a PHP application can be deployed flawlessly using Jenkins. Then see how \"Dev\" and \"Ops\" are supported by a system if the application breaks and the nightmare happens.','regular','overview','continuousdelivery',0,'','This is a new talk. Will be presenting it at Jenkins User Conference and ZendCon.',0,0,0,'2014-09-05 21:46:10','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(53,35,'End the war on tabs','If PHP is a double-clawed hammer, whitespace is an invisible spaceship from the future. Whitespace is a general purpose DSL that can be embedded into almost any existing programming language.\n\nHere is a basic example of a hello world program, running inside a whitespace interpreter (that is written in whitespace), running again in that same whitespace interpreter (that is still written in whitespace), running in this whitespace interpreter (that is written in PHP).\n\n$ (cat examples/wsinterws.ws; cat examples/hworld.ws; echo -ne \"\\n\\n\\nquit\\n\\n\\n\") | hhvm bin/interpreter examples/wsinterws.ws','regular','indepth','other',0,'','Most modern languages are interpreted. This means they run inside of a VM. Whitespace is a satirical esoteric programming language that is really just a simple VM. It has very similar instructions to the JVM or the zend engine, which in turn model the hardware. As such it\'s interesting to see the general concept of how such an engine works, as it tells us about how interpreters and computers work.\n\nI\'ve written a whitespace interpreter in PHP: https://github.com/igorw/whitespace-php\n\nAlso, VMs and stack machines are fun!',0,0,0,'2014-09-06 00:25:36','2014-09-28 16:01:33'),(54,42,'Symfony2: The journey from the request to the response','Let\'s get in an adventure! Basically, what happens when a request is done until the response is rendered? When I first asked this question to a teamate, it was a pretext to see how I can learn most of concepts applied in the Symfony2 framework. This talk is about discovering (or re-discovering) how Symfony2 performs things internally to render a response: by going through a winding road, we\'ll see how you can teach to your colleagues all of this.','regular','indepth','other',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-08 11:44:20','2014-09-08 11:45:43'),(55,42,'How I learnt to build a RESTfull API with Symfony','I\'ll talk about a project I had to work on where one of the key word was SOA.\n\nFrom FOSRestBundle to JMS serializer, through Guzzle, some HATEOAS and Oauth,  I\'ll cover all tricks I\'ve set on a Symfony 2 application.\n\nWe will first cover some basics about REST, then talk about the architecture I\'ve set for this project and to finish all the solutions I\'ve implemented to do this nice REST API.','regular','handson','other',1,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-08 11:49:50','2014-09-08 12:01:15'),(56,42,'Reverse engineering of the Symfony2 Form component','The Symfony2 form component is a complex and ingenious system offering to developers a simplified API to create awesome forms. This high level component coupled with the Twig template engine is actually the visible part of the iceberg.\n\nThis subject invite the public to discover the immersed part of that gigantic iceberg! It\'s about studying the internal architecture of the component.','regular','overview','phpfuture',0,'https://speakerdeck.com/saro0h/ingenierie-inversee-du-composant-form','Hi,\n\nI had the pleasure to talk about this subject at the last Symfony Live Paris 2014 with Hugo Hamon, which had great rates. I\'d be happy to present it again but in english this time if this subject seems appropriate for the event.\n\nRegards,',0,0,0,'2014-09-08 11:58:59','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(57,42,'Developers / Project managers : Be reconciled','Let\'s first understand each side to get to what I use everyday to manage my teams through nice  but complex projects. This talk is for project managers (preferably using Scrum methodology) and of course to developers.\nWe\'ll see how to find solution during tough moments, learn together and make happier days.','regular','overview','other',0,'https://joind.in/talk/view/11243','Hello,\n\nI had the joy of to do this talk at the last PHP forum in Lyon. I\'d be delighted if I could do this one more time, but in english this time.',0,0,0,'2014-09-08 12:01:05','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(58,43,'Who Framed Roger Rabbit(MQ)? Php of course','In this talk Iâ€™m going to show Rabbitmq, a highly reliable enterprise messaging system based on the emerging AMQP standard, and its integration with PHP and Symfony.\nAfter a  short overview on how Rabbitmq works and what it is capable of, I would like to share the experience gained in Namshi, an e-commerce retailer based in Dubai serving the UAE, and how we are using it to boost and scale our SOA architecture to serve milions of users every month. \n You will see how easy it is to implement a solution around messaging and that you donâ€™t need to have a complex architecture in order to take advantage of RabbitMQ and finally get rid of your cron scripts.','regular','overview','crossingphp',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-08 17:32:10','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(59,43,'Are you ready for redis?','Redis in a well know advanced key-value store that you can easily integrate and instantly improve your PHP application and architecture.\nAfter a short overview of this wonderful tool, I will show you why in many cases is a more suitable solution over the well known Memcache.\nI will also share the experience gained in Namshi, an e-commerce retailer based in Dubai serving the UAE, and how we are using it to boost and scale our SOA to serve millions of users every month.','regular','handson','architectures',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-08 17:32:48','2014-09-08 17:39:04'),(60,43,'Apt-get no more let Vagrant and Puppet take the stage','How frustrating is to configure your dev machine everytime to meet the production specs?\nHow frustrating is to be sure that all of your colleagues have the same setup?\nHow to avoid distributing a new 4 GB vm to your team devs everytime you change the specs?\nEnter Vagrant and Puppet, the easy way to distribute vm and integrate them in your project repo\nwith just few KB!','regular','overview','devlife',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-08 17:33:10','2014-09-08 17:35:43'),(61,43,'Oh my Git! whatâ€™s happening there?','Nowadays Git is no more the new kids on the block for versioning your awesome codebase, but, due to its flexible nature, sometimes its usage is still not well understood.\nHow often you use google to find answers on how to perform a specific operation with Git and How often you realize that you did the same search 3 weeks before?\nWhy sometimes I can do â€œgit checkoutâ€ or â€œgit resetâ€ to achieve the same results?\nWhy should I rebase and not perform  Git merge?\nIn this talk I will explain how Git works behind the scenes and some tips and tricks, in order to avoid you freaking out at next Git rebase.','regular','handson','vcs',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-08 17:36:12','2014-09-08 17:36:38'),(62,43,'All the roads lead to (GIT) push','We all use Git, we know that itâ€™s a great tool, but, due to its flexibility, sometimes is difficult to find the right flow in our daily usage.\nDo you still remember when you discover Git-flow? â€œAwesome, finally, thatâ€™s the way you use Git!â€\nWRONG! \nGit-flow is one of the possible way to fit your daily Git usage but it could be not the right fit for your internal workflow organisation.\nIn this talk I will show different flow that I used in my career, and how Git can easily adapt to your flow, and not viceversa.','regular','overview','vcs',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-08 17:37:11','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(63,43,'PHP is the king, nodejs is the prince and Python is the fool','In Namshi, an e-commerce retailer based in Dubai serving the UAE, we are using different technologies to boost our architecture.\nWe started with a common architecture based on PHP (Yii and Zend framework), Nginx, Mysql and Memcache: the usual suspects. \nDuring last year the architecture changed a lot, using an SOA paradigm to meet expectations and the huge increase of traffic from several millions users throughout the year and PHP is still dispatching and serving the huge number of responses. But thereâ€™s moreâ€¦\nIn this talk we will show how funny, easy and rewarding is to integrate different technologies in your stack, with PHP always being the king of the whole system.','regular','overview','architectures',1,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-08 17:38:00','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(64,43,'A PHP developerâ€™s toolbox','Other than our favourite IDE, there are several great tools, tips and tricks that can help us to monitor and troubleshoot the development of our PHP application.\nIn this talk I will show you what should be inside every PHP dev toolbox, introducing small tips and tricks that the language itself gives us, curl, xdebug, xhprof, wireshark and many more.','regular','overview','devlife',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-08 17:38:48','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(65,44,'Facebook PHP SDK v4 and the new Graph API and why you\'re gonna have to rewrite all the things','On April 30, 2015 Facebook is going to break their API. Are you prepared?\n\nWith the announcement of Graph v2.0 on April 30, 2014, Facebook updated the way they version their API. But they also announced that they are going kill the existing Graph version 1.0 on April 30, 2015. And that\'s not all that will break. There is a brand new Facebook login that all websites and Facebook apps are required to upgrade to. And if you\'re using the old PHP SDK v3, that is now officially deprecated and you\'ll need to upgrade to the brand new PHP SDK v4 which uses the latest version of Graph by default.\n\nIf you have any web apps that use Facebook login, the Graph API or the old PHP SDK v3, you cannot miss this talk. I will outline what Facebook is changing, how you can upgrade your legacy Facebook app and what to expect from Facebook going forward.','regular','overview','other',1,'https://speakerdeck.com/sammyk/facebook-php-sdk-v4-and-the-new-graph-api','By the time PHPBenelux kicks off, developers will have a little over 3 months before the Facebook apps they created before April 30, 2014 will break. So this is an important \"heads up!\" talk to anyone who has implemented Facebook login or has ever used the Graph API. It should also ease the pain of trying to catch up on all the changes that Facebook as made with very practical tips on how to upgrade.\n\nThe link to the slides above is from my OpenSpaces talk at php[tek] this past year right after Facebook\'s F8 Graph v2.0 announcement. There have been lots of changes to the Facebook SDK and the Graph API since then so I\'ll be updating the slides to be relevant and also including more in-depth slides on the PHP SDK v4.',0,0,0,'2014-09-09 07:09:27','2014-09-22 03:54:40'),(66,44,'Facebook app development from start to finish','During this tutorial we will go through all the necessary steps to create your very first fully-functional Facebook app. We\'ll cover creating the app in Facebook and properly configuring it, creating test apps and test users, setting up the proper development environment for your app, how to use the latest PHP SDK v4 &amp; Javascript SDK, the new Facebook login, getting data from the Graph API, running your app from an app canvas, installing your app as a Facebook page tab, and submitting your final app for app review. \n\nAnd if there is time, we\'ll dive deeper into how you can get the most out of your app including nested and batch requests to the Graph API and real-time updates.\n\nA local development environment is highly recommended for this tutorial.','tutorial','handson','other',0,'','The zeitgeist of Facebook development changes all the time. And sometimes it hard to learn a technology when the target is constantly moving. This tutorial will help alleviate the pain of getting started with Facebook app development.',0,0,0,'2014-09-09 07:53:32','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(67,35,'Abstract Machines','As developers, we compute. But what is computation exactly? And why is it so difficult to write correct software? Alan Turing and Alonzo Church discovered some remarkable answers to these questions in 1936. They envisioned abstract machines before real computers even existed. Those abstract machines would model all of the computable things.\n\nIn this talk, we will discover the possibilities and limitations of computation. Along the way we will encounter a bunch of virtual machines and interpreters, see similarities between them, and how they relate to things that we use every day, such as regular expressions, parsers, the PHP interpreter itself. You will gain a deeper understanding of what computation is, and what programming is all about.','regular','overview','other',0,'https://speakerdeck.com/igorw/abstract-machines-dpc14','I gave this talk at dpc and at laracon.\n\nThere\'s a video from laracon https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zu_iFwD8MfI',0,0,0,'2014-09-09 09:59:59','2014-09-20 18:32:42'),(68,35,'Concrete Machines','Computers!!! How do they work?\n\nProgramming is not really about computers. Most theories of computation take place at a higher level of abstraction, than the physical. However, low-level implementation of physical computers can teach us a lot about abstraction.\n\nStarting with the fundamental theories of quantum physics, discovering NAND gates along the way, and ending up with a universal computer.','regular','overview','other',0,'https://speakerdeck.com/igorw/concrete-machines-bephpug','This is a talk about quantum physics, abstraction, and how hardware actually operates. I originally did it as a short fun april 1 talk at the Berlin PHP usergroup. But I\'d love to flesh it out more and actually present it at a conference.\n\nMost software developers do not know much about electronics and what computers do in terms of hardware.',0,0,0,'2014-09-09 10:13:29','2014-09-20 18:31:52'),(69,46,'50 tips in 50 minutes','In this sessions Jan-Willem Eshuis takes you into a fast journey along 50 valuable tips for developers using real world practical examples. In his talk Jan-Willem covers topics like clean code, testing, deploying, hosting, infrastructure and service and support. After the 50 minutes of passion, humor and speed you\'ll remember at least a couple of tips to apply them in practice.','regular','overview','other',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-09 11:20:41','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(70,45,'Naming things','For us developers it is a constant struggle to find the right words to describe things. Naming classes, functions and variables correctly and giving them context helps to create a meaning, and to convey that meaning to other developers.\n\nIn this talk we will discuss guidelines to find good names for the buildings blocks we use, to aid in our daily challenge to transport our knowledge by leveraging well worded sourcecode.','regular','overview','devlife',1,'https://speakerdeck.com/dazz/nomen-est-omen-naming-things-considered-hard','I gave this talk at our local PHP Usergroup in Berlin and people came to me afterwards and told me they loved it.\nThey said, the slides are awesome, my english is very good, every slide made them to want to contribute, I have a good pace through the slides and I should give this talk in front of 2000 people.\nThe slidedeck has now around 1390 views and there was quite a fuzz on twitter about it.\n\nFor me, I am very passionate about how to write huge applications in a style that I still love after a year working in it. I have seen a lot of bad code. Often I was just angry as how respectless one can be to leave it to the coder after him to figure out how things are connected. I collected what I found out works best communicating with others through code and wrapped a story around it to give this talk.',0,0,0,'2014-09-09 14:15:48','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(71,47,'Asynchronous PHP and Real-time Messaging','With every major browser now supporting HTML 5 and WebSockets the demand for real time client and server messaging continues to increase.  A common misconception is that PHP is not capable of handling this type of functionality. This has caused PHP developers to look to other languages and frameworks such as Node.js and Twisted for Python. In this session we\'ll explore libraries and extensions we can use to write efficient real-time HTML5 messaging applications','regular','overview','phpfuture',1,'http://www.slideshare.net/SteveRhoades2/asynchronous-php-and-realtime-messaging','I recently gave this talk at the PHP Minicamp / Drupal LA conference at UCI.',0,0,0,'2014-09-09 17:47:10','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(72,48,'Vagrant Provisioning with Ansible','Vagrant is getting more and more popular every day, reaching the status of de-facto tool for virtualized environments created for development purposes - you can finally forget about setting the right environment and focus on what you do best: code. However, many developers still step back from this great tool after having a bad experience with tools like Puppet and Chef.\n\nThis talk will present you Ansible, a clean and straightforward automation tool that can be used along with Vagrant to spin up development vms. You you will learn how to get started with Ansible and write your first playbooks to provision a Vagrant environment.','regular','overview','virtualization',0,'https://speakerdeck.com/erikaheidi/portable-development-environments-with-vagrant-and-ansible','The description is slightly different, but this is intended to be the same talk I presented at DayCamp4devs: https://joind.in/talk/view/11663 .',1,0,0,'2014-09-09 23:47:56','2014-09-26 20:37:43'),(73,49,'Software architecture in an agile age','Properly designing the architecture of software seems to have become a lost art. Even when using agile development methods, designing (parts of) your application can still be very rewarding and insightful. This presentation is not about slow and in-detail design cycles, but about quickly and pragmatically sketching the outlines of your system in order to keep a birds-eye view on the architecture and the application as a whole.','regular','overview','other',1,'','A subject that I\'m very passionate about and very eager to present. The talk is ***NOT*** about in-detail designs of applications, it\'s about model storming and quickly sketching designs to keep a birds eye view on your application\'s architecture.',0,0,0,'2014-09-10 10:50:30','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(74,49,'Recognizing smelly code','The way the code of an application is organized greatly influences its maintainability, extendability and testability. Finding flaws in your object-oriented design as early as possible can therefore make the difference between an awesome application and a not so good one. Luckily there are a lot of indicators to look out for while you are coding, telling you that you should probably consider refactoring - often without even looking at your actual code! This session is an introduction to the most common code smells and some of the related anti-patterns in OO PHP projects. You will learn how to recognize indicators of deeper underlying problems in your application, and how to prevent these problems from happening in the first place.','regular','overview','other',0,'','Evolved version of the codesmell-talk. Presented this talk on several occasions where it was well received:\n\nhttps://joind.in/talk/view/7000\nhttps://joind.in/talk/view/4975',0,0,0,'2014-09-10 10:52:21','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(75,49,'A hands-on introduction to writing unit tests using PHPUnit','In this hands-on introduction to unit testing we will be writing some actual tests for code that you could come across in real-life applications. We will start with a simple schoolbook example and gradually go into subjects like mock objects, dealing with dependencies, writing testable code and test driven development. The \'live coding\' setup should make it easy to understand how all of this can applied to your own projects, starting tomorrow!','tutorial','handson','testing',0,'','I think it\'s really important to learn unit testing by actually doing it. This is the only way attendees will know how to apply their knowledge to their own projects tomorrow.\n\nPresented on several occasions, both as a \'regular\' session and a workshop:\nhttps://joind.in/talk/view/9317\nhttps://joind.in/talk/view/8941\nhttps://joind.in/talk/view/8979\nhttps://joind.in/talk/view/8190\nhttps://joind.in/talk/view/8057',0,0,0,'2014-09-10 10:54:28','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(76,23,'Composer the right way','Composer has triggered a renaissance in the PHP community, it has changed the way we deal with other peopleâ€™s code and it has changed the way we share our code. We are all slowly moving to using Composer, from Wordpress to Joomla and Drupal and frameworks in between. But many of us mistreat composer, follow outdated practices or simply lack a few tricks. In this session iâ€™ll get you the low down on how to use composer the right way.','regular','indepth','devlife',0,'','New talk, follows my previous composer talk into the realm of more advanced and usual things that people get wrong with composer.',0,0,0,'2014-09-10 20:36:03','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(77,23,'Writing code that lasts','As developers we write code everyday, only to frown at it a week after that. Why do we have such a hard time with code written by others and ourselves, this raging desire to rewrite everything we see? Writing code that survives the test of time and self judgment is a matter of clarity and simplicity. Let\'s talk about growing, learning and improving our code with calisthenics, readability and good design.','regular','overview','devlife',1,'http://www.slideshare.net/rdohms/writing-code-you-wont-hate-tomorrow','This is an inspirational talk, it does not go into deep technical details, but stays more in a keynote-y inspirational talk. It draws on my other talks and paints a clear picture of why you hate your code tomorrow and how you can avoid that by hardwaring your brain to write code better. Its one of my favorite talks. It has a second title which is \"Writing code, you won\'t hate tomorrow\".\n\nIt has been delivered and well received at JandBeyond and CakeFest: https://joind.in/talk/view/11594',0,0,0,'2014-09-10 20:39:56','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(78,35,'Cute little interpreters','Cute little interpreters is a workshop where you can learn how to build your own little programming language!\n\nHave you ever wondered how programming languages work on the inside? What is bytecode? How does a virtual machine work? Learn how to create your own stack machine, extend it with control flow to make it turing complete. Then create your own language that can be compiled to instructions and run on your very own interpreter.\n\nAttend this workshop if you always wanted to know what is happening a few layers deeper.','tutorial','handson','other',0,'','I did this workshop as an informal session at the DPC14 hackathon, and it was a lot of fun.',0,0,0,'2014-09-11 10:40:33','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(79,51,'Codeception your passport to acceptance testing','Todays Applications are vast because we have left the playground. Applications need to have\na ton of features to compete with competitors. All this requires tons of code. For years now\nwe as developers have tried to maintain code quality by introducing Unit testing. Today\nthat isn\'t enough. We need integration tests as well. And besides integration tests full acceptance\ntesting through different browsers. I give you the wonderful world of Codeception.','regular','overview','testing',1,'','Codeception (http://codeception.com/) is a mature product and valuable tool. In several partner projects it has\nserved to maintain quality and assure stability where mere Unit testing didn\'t suffice. Myself\nwouldn\'t feel comfortable anymore with an application which doesn\'t have a good acceptance suite\nbehind it. Codeception ensures that the suite is easily written and maintained.',0,0,0,'2014-09-11 21:27:16','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(80,51,'Vagrant move over, here is Docker','Developers need to be able to run an application on an environment as closely\nmatched to production as possible. We can already do this through Vagrant.\nThe problem with Vagrant is that it is slow and takes a lot of resources both\nin cpu and space. Docker doesn\'t have this problem and gives you a tool to\ncreate hundreds of different application environments on the same machine and\ndistribute them through a registry. \nAs Git replaced SVN, so has Docker replaced vagrant for application environment setups.\nLeave the future behind, own today (like a boss).','regular','overview','virtualization',0,'http://blog.nickbelhomme.com/php/moving-from-vagrant-to-docker-in-an-easy-way_447','Talk will give a quick overview on how we work today with Vagrant 10 mins and then move over to Docker. Giving the when and how to use what. For application environments Docker clearly wins. This talk will give an overview on what it is, how to install and potential pitfalls such as running it on OSX and Windows, networking issues, etc.\nAfter the talk the audience has enough feedback to start its own docker image + containers and push it to the registry. All this with a clear understanding of what is going on, thus moving the abstract concept of Docker into something comfortable.',0,0,0,'2014-09-11 21:49:11','2014-09-26 15:19:38'),(81,52,'Handling Highly Connected Data with the Neo4j Graph Database','Traditional relational databases â€” ironically â€” are not that good at the complex relationships some modern applications need.\n\nMultiple joins and complex sub-queries can gradually take a toll on performance.\n\nGraph Databases, on the other hand, are all about relationships. In this talk we will look at using the popular Neo4j graph database with PHP to build efficient relational data for OmNomHub: not your average recipe site.','regular','overview','architectures',1,'https://speakerdeck.com/michellesanver/graph-databases-with-php-and-neo4j','I have given this talk before at laracon, webtuesday and at amsterdamPHP with great feedback! Can\'t wait to give it again even better than before, it\'s a hot topic that people love.\n\nhttps://joind.in/talk/view/11566',0,0,0,'2014-09-11 22:51:01','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(82,52,'Starting Open Source: How To Make Your First Contribution','So, you want to join the Open Source party, but you\'re not used to every man and his dog looking at your code. You keep putting it off, you don\'t know anyone involved in the project, you might be a burden...\n\nIf you want to get involved but keep talking yourself out of it, let me show you how to take that first step. I\'ll cover the mechanics and the fear of contributing, from saying hello and installing the project to selecting a bug and surviving the fear of your first pull request and code review using git and GitHub.','regular','overview','other',0,'','I have given this talk before, several times, and every time I got several people contacting me afterwards telling me they contributed to their first open source project, I love empowering the community! :)\n\nhttps://joind.in/talk/view/8950',0,0,0,'2014-09-11 22:52:16','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(83,52,'Automating and optimizing the frontend workflow using Bower and Gulp','Do you use external JavaScript files, is it really tedious everytime you want to update them?\n\nDo you do a lot of frontend tasks manually such as minimising JavaScript and compiling your SASS or LESS files? As developers we want as much as possible done for us.\n\nEnter the world of Gulp and Bower - the composer of frontend development. With these tools we will automate and optimise our frontend workflow','regular','overview','other',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-11 22:52:45','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(84,52,'Life After Assetic: State of the Art Symfony 2 Frontend Dev','Assetic is a great tool. It helps us build our SASS and LESS files and minimises our JavaScript. But with Assetic we still have to do a lot of manual work. There are better ways to automate our frontend workflow.\n\nWith Gulp and Bower, we can ditch Assetic and get to grips with the latest and greatest. We will go through how to automate and optimise our Symfony2 frontend workflow in a more efficient manner than we have ever done before.â€œ','regular','overview','other',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-11 22:53:38','2014-09-11 22:53:50'),(85,54,'Principles of PHP Package Design','With many great tools available for sharing packages of PHP code, it is now up to you as a developer to design these packages well. You have to decide what to put in a package, when to split a package and on what other packages you can safely depend.\n\nYou will learn how to make good decisions about your package design and release reliable, highly usable and therefore highly esteemed packages of PHP code.','regular','overview','other',1,'http://www.slideshare.net/matthiasnoback/principles-of-php-package-design-laracon-europe-amsterdam-2014','I did this talk on several occassions before:\n\n- 3/6/2013 Dutch Symfony Usergroup Meetup (http://www.meetup.com/Symfony-User-Group-NL/events/162773962/)\n- 9/19/2013 AmsterdamPHP (http://www.meetup.com/AmsterdamPHP/events/98709922/, https://joind.in/talk/view/10883)\n- 6/28/2014 Dutch PHP Conference (http://www.phpconference.nl/schedule)\n- 7/29/2014 DomCode Utrecht (http://www.meetup.com/DomCode/events/192964782/, https://joind.in/talk/view/11580)\n- 8/28/2014 Laracon EU Amsterdam (http://laracon.eu/2014/, https://joind.in/11685)',0,0,0,'2014-09-12 21:26:20','2014-09-12 21:42:06'),(86,54,'The Naked Bundle','The Bundle system is \"one of the greatest and most powerful features of Symfony2\". Bundles contain all the files related to a single feature of your application: controllers, entities, event listeners, form types, Twig templates, etc. But how much of that actually *needs* to be inside a bundle?\n\nIn this talk I take a bundle, containing all those different types of classes, configuration files and templates, and strip it down to the bare necessities. And I promise that after moving many files out of the bundle, at the end everything still works.\n\nWhile looking for ways to move things out of the bundle, I will discuss some of the more advanced features of bundle design, like prepending configuration, compiler passes and Doctrine mapping drivers. We will end with a very thin bundle, surrounded by a few highly reusable, maximally decoupled libraries.','regular','indepth','other',0,'https://www.slideshare.net/secret/DFRSxW4n0hTewW','This can also be a 3 hour interactive tutorial. I\'m doing this tutorial at the Dutch PHP Conference (www.phpconference.nl).\n\nI did the workshop at the following occasions:\n\n- 6/26/2014 Dutch PHP Conference (https://joind.in/talk/view/10849, includes the slides)\n\nI did the talk at the following occasions:\n\n- 9/17/2014 e-Active Zwolle (NL), try-out (https://www.slideshare.net/secret/DFRSxW4n0hTewW)\n- 9/26/2014 SymfonyLive London (https://joind.in/talk/view/11553, will include the slides)',0,0,0,'2014-09-12 21:37:59','2014-09-22 20:46:15'),(87,54,'A Series of Fortunate Events','What is an event really? How can you best describe an event in your code? What types of events are there, and how do you decide whether or not to implement something as an event?\n\nIn this talk we start with a straightforward command-only piece of code. We extract events from it and start moving the event handling code out, trying different design patterns on the way. First we try Observer. Then we introduce event data, event handlers and a Mediator between our code and the event handlers. Finally we pick a well-known event dispatcher implementation (the Symfony EventDispatcher) and see how it uses the Chain of Responsibility design pattern to control the entire flow of a web application request.\n\nIn the end I will answer some burning questions like: is it safe to use events all over the place and rely on event handlers to do some really important stuff? How do I overcome the indirection in my event-driven code? And how can I quickly find out what happens where?','regular','overview','other',0,'https://www.slideshare.net/secret/Kc97Tpi84K70wt','I have done/will do this talk on several occasions:\n\n- 9/18/2014 Drupal CafÃ© Utrecht (http://www.meetup.com/drupalnetherlands/events/202500432/)\n- 10/2/2014 DrupalCon EU Amsterdam (https://amsterdam2014.drupal.org/session/series-fortunate-events)',0,0,0,'2014-09-12 21:41:52','2014-09-22 20:42:58'),(88,55,'Dockerize your (existing) PHP application','Docker has been a buzzword over the past couple of years. But how does it actually help developers, particularly those with existing PHP applications in production?\n\nIn this presentation we\'ll take an existing sample PHP application and Dockerize it. We\'ll start by mentally breaking down our application in terms of Docker containers. We\'ll explore how to create and run these containers in a development environment on a laptop. Then we\'ll learn how to deploy the same containers into a production environment, onto Cloud Servers running CoreOS.\n\nAlong the way we\'ll learn new concepts, terminology and idioms related to Docker. More importantly, we\'ll discover how Docker can make your life as a developer so much easier.','regular','handson','virtualization',1,'','I am going to try and do this as a live demo so WiFi would be appreciated. I will, however, have a screencast as a backup.',1,0,0,'2014-09-12 22:45:59','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(89,55,'Working Remotely: The Good, The Bad, and The Ugly','Remote collaboration is on the rise, particularly in the software industry. A majority of employees at companies like Automattic (makers of WordPress) and GitHub work remotely.\n\nEarly on in my career, I was sent to Mumbai, India to setup a remote office for my US-based employer. Many years later, I was a manager at a startup in Silicon Valley and had the opportunity to manage a full-time remote employee.  Today, I myself work remotely as a part of a distributed team of 20+ people at Rackspace.\n\nMy presentation will explore some of the benefits and downsides of remote work, drawing on my as well as others\' experiences.\n\nIf you are looking to become a remote employee or are an employer with remote employees on your team, this talk is for you!','regular','overview','devlife',0,'www.slideshare.net/shaunakkashyap/working-remotely-the-good-the-bad-and-the-ugly','I gave this talk at New Zealand PHP Conference 2014 and it was well received: https://joind.in/talk/view/11437.',1,0,0,'2014-09-12 22:47:13','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(90,56,'The Modern Developer Toolbox','In recent years there has been a tremendous amount of progress and innovation around tools and applications available to web developers that improve the quality, efficiency and speed of our applications, and it is hard to keep up with all of it.\n\nIn this talk we will introduce and showcase tools that make a difference in the following areas:\n- Developing, testing and debugging with Vagrant, Ansible, and Docker\n- Monitoring and logging with Logstash, Kibana, Redis, and Elasticsearch\n- Deployment with Capistrano, Capifony and friends\n\nAll these tools, plus tips and tricks collected over years of experience will make this talk quite valuable for developers of different skills levels.','regular','overview','devlife',1,'','This talk was accepted in PHPNW UK in Manchester.',0,0,0,'2014-09-12 23:19:48','2014-09-12 23:31:54'),(91,56,'Building web apps from a new angle','We have been developing Web Applications, generating HTML in the server with bits of JavaScript and jQuery, for many years now. But a new breed of JavaScript frameworks and the maturity of the browser now allow us to create really powerful apps that were not possible before.\n\nAngularJS is one of these new-breed JavaScript framework, backed by Google, it allows building powerful, complex and rich client-side web applications. We will go over the features and basics of building a web application with AngularJS and we will demonstrate how to communicate with a REST server built with Symfony and offer tips that will help make the transition in this new era.\n\nWarning: Once you see what you can do with these new methodologies and technologies, you will not go back to the way you build web apps.','regular','overview','crossingphp',0,'http://www.slideshare.net/pgodel/lone-starphp-2013-building-web-apps-from-a-new-angle','I have worked a lot more with AngularJS since giving this talk at Lone Star PHP and Tek\'13, so I can update it quite a bit adding new and more advanced information.',0,0,0,'2014-09-12 23:24:13','2014-09-12 23:32:29'),(92,56,'Declare Independence from your IT department: sysadmin skills for PHP developers','A PHP/web developer is not complete without knowing server administration. When looking for a job, it is quite likely that you will be required to know about installing and configuring a LAMP (Linux, Apache, MySQL and PHP). Your prospects of getting that job are much higher when you know these. In this session we will cover: - Introduction to LAMP servers - Frequently used Unix commands - Linux distro Differences - Prepare your LAMP server before going live - Overall LAMP Security - Performance tips to improve your website speed - Compiling PHP from source. Adding PHP extensions. - Basic description of web hosting options for PHP.','regular','overview','virtualization',0,'http://www.slideshare.net/pgodel/lone-star-php-2013-sysadmin-skills-for-php-developers','',0,0,0,'2014-09-12 23:25:50','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(93,56,'Rock Solid Deployment of PHP Apps','Web applications are becoming increasingly more complex, so deployment is not just transferring files with FTP anymore. We will go over the different challenges that are present when dealing with deploying PHP applications effectively, safely and consistently with the latest tools and techniques. We will also look at tools that complement deployment with virtualization, management, configuration and monitoring.','regular','overview','devlife',1,'http://www.slideshare.net/pgodel/phparchitect-devops-summit-2013-rock-solid-deployment-of-php-apps','I have given this talk at:\n- PHP Architect DevOps Summit\n- PHP Conference Argentina\n- PFCongres\n\nI will also give a variation of this talk at Symfony Live NYC.',0,0,0,'2014-09-12 23:31:39','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(94,56,'APIfy your app!','APIs are becoming an essential part of web applications and websites. Not having one will put obstacles to your users and will mean losing customers and users. They are as important as your app or website.\n\nIn this talk we will go over why it is important to have an API, from the first day but also for existing apps. And we will explore ways to add an API to an existing or legacy application.\n\nThen we will get dirty with code and go over a series of demos with tools (such as Apigility, Symfony, Silex, etc) to create powerful APIs easily.','regular','overview','other',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-12 23:33:37','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(95,36,'Getting a grip on your content with Symfony CMF','An introduction to Symfony CMF. I will cover the underlying ideas and its components and bundles.\nSome of the topics I will cover:\n- PHPCR + Decoupled Content Management\n- Routing + RoutingAuto\n- PublishWorkflow\n- CreateBundle\n- MediaBundle\n- BlockBundle\n- Versioning\n\nThe goal is to explain the subjects while using fictive examples for an online learning application like Coursera.','regular','overview','other',0,'','I gave a talk about Symfony CMF at 010PHP in december 2013. I noticed that only explaining what you can do with CMF is a bit to abstract for some people. So I want to adjust the talk with an example application throughout the talk.\nSlides foe the talk at 010PHP: https://speakerdeck.com/wjzijderveld/symfony-cmf-a-decoupled-content-management-framework',0,0,0,'2014-09-13 16:44:28','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(96,36,'Decouple your content with PHPCR','An overview about the ideas of PHPCR and the most interesting parts of the specifications.\nTopics I want to cover:\n- What is a content repository\n- Creating and accessing content\n- Structure (with nodetypes and mixins)\n- SQL2\n- Referencing content\n- Versioning\n- Import/Export','regular','overview','other',0,'','I gave a 15 minute introduction on PFCongres 2013 (Unconference), but 15 minutes is not nearly enough time to explain PHPCR. I also gave a PHPCR workshop at PHPSummercamp 2014 in Croatia (sadly they didn\'t use joind.in).',0,0,0,'2014-09-13 17:02:08','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(97,36,'Creating a basic CMS from scratch with PHPCR','The goal of this workshop/tutorial is to let people experience PHPCR first-hand. They will create a very basic CMS from scratch. without the help of a framework. The only tool we will use is PHPCR-Shell.\n\nThere are a few goals people should achieve:\n- Creating and browsing content in PHPCR-Shell\n- Retrieving content in PHP based on the url\n- Create and use mixins to structure content\n- Using referencing to create a custom route to existing content\n- Looping over nodes and his children to create a menu\n- Using versioning\n- Using SQL2 to retrieve content','tutorial','overview','other',0,'','I gave this workshop at PHPSummercamp 2014, sadly they didn\'t use joind.in. \nIn that workshop I learned I need to have more fixture data ready, so people can get to the PHP part faster.',0,0,0,'2014-09-13 20:29:08','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(98,57,'\"Orcs \'n\' All\": A Journey to Mount Doom (via Facebook)','The story of how a tiny team in South Wales that somehow acquired a license to write a Facebook game for one of the world\'s biggest brands. Making money with the \"Lord of the Rings\" story should be easy, right? Wrong. You\'ll hear what we learned about the web and Facebook on the epic (and futile) journey. A \"warts \'n\' all\" story about how we tried to conquer Facebook, what we learned, where we succeeded, and ultimately why we failed.','regular','overview','other',0,'https://joind.in/talk/view/10862','This is a story rather than any kind of technical talk.',1,0,0,'2014-09-14 11:53:47','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(99,57,'Build Your Own Dependency Injection Container','Dependency Injection is a hot topic in PHP at the moment, and more and more of the popular frameworks are using a dependency injection container to manager the creation and storage of objects. A DIC can be a great way of managing the various complex dependencies, but the internals can seem complicated and scary.\n\nIn this session we will build our own DIC from scratch as a way of fully understanding both the patterns and code involved in creating a container for managing your class instances. We\'ll get to understand why the Dependency Injection pattern is a Good Thing, and learn about the challenges in defining dependencies and creating services with factories. Building your own container will help you understand how the DIC in the current crop of frameworks are put together.\n\nBy the end of the session we\'ll have a fully working DIC that you should never use in your own projects!','tutorial','handson','other',0,'','',1,0,0,'2014-09-14 11:55:19','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(100,57,'Understanding the OWASP Top 10','Every year the OWASP community releases a Top 10 List of what it considers are the most critical web application security flaws. Join us as we step through the current OWASP Top 10 vulnerabilities, explaining what they are and how they can affect your PHP application. We\'ll take a quickfire look at all 10 security concerns complete with examples and best practices. You\'ll leave the talk with a basic understanding of each flaw giving you a great grounding to audit your own applications and an impetus to learn more about website security.','regular','overview','security',0,'','Giving at PHP NW 2014',1,0,0,'2014-09-14 11:56:45','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(101,57,'Writing Workers for Scalable Applications','At some point in any successful web application\'s life, you\'re going to need to remove things from the request and response cycle in order to improve the performance. From sending out emails to publishing information to social media channels, we\'re finding ourselves trying to shoehorn more and more processes into the traditional HTTP request/response. This talk will help explain how you can use command line PHP to control workers that take and process jobs from a queue helping to make sure each and every one of your responses is lightening fast. Using popular technologies like Redis and Beanstalkd to manage and monitor worker processes is a skill that every developer will benefit from sooner rather than later.','regular','handson','crossingphp',0,'','Currently this talk has never been given before. I\'m really excited about this talk as it seems to have a very good narrative and should be useful to most levels of developer.',1,0,0,'2014-09-14 11:57:36','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(102,48,'PHP in the underground','Itâ€™s a well-known fact that PHP is the most popular server-side programming language in the world. But what happens in the â€œundergroundâ€, while we are carefully crafting our PHP applications?\n\nThis talk will walk you through the universe of BotNets and Command &amp; Controllers, showing how they use PHP in the backend to manage infected machines all over the world. Youâ€™ll see some of the PHP code they use to collect data from the bots, like credentials and banking information.\n\nThis is not a technical talk, itâ€™s an informative talk about why and how PHP is being used in the underground by the â€œbad guysâ€.','regular','overview','other',0,'','This is a new talk I\'ve started to work on. It\'s an overview of botnet control panels, since PHP is the favorite choice for these malicious networks. The idea is to show another side of PHP usage out there. I have some interesting source codes to show, but I don\'t consider this talk technical because it\'s more about showing information, there are no \"how tos\" or guides.',1,0,0,'2014-09-16 00:26:00','2014-09-26 20:37:57'),(103,58,'Queues and the Giant beanstalkd','In the modern world of scaling web applications, queues have become a go-to for increasing performance by parallelizing and backgrounding heavy duty tasks. Learn practical usages of queues through beanstalkd.','regular','overview','architectures',0,'https://speakerdeck.com/dcousineau/queues-and-the-giant-beanstalkd','Given at Confoo 2013\n\nhttp://joind.in/talk/view/7873',0,0,0,'2014-09-16 00:32:21','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(104,58,'Reframing the Problem: How to Think Like a Computer Scientist','Often times we hit a wall and get stuck on a problem, only to realize much later and after lengthy and unnecessary pain the solution was simple if we just reframed the problem as something else. Thinking like a Computer Scientist involves being able to take a step back, abstracting what we know about a problem space, and realizing relations to other, solved, problems that were not immediately apparent. Together we\'ll tackle a problem, learn how to think, and come away with that \"aha!\" moment that we all know and love as developers.','regular','overview','other',1,'https://speakerdeck.com/dcousineau/reframing-the-problem-madisonphp-2014','Video of the talk at MadisonPHP: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YDfYHS34D-4\n\nJoind.in: http://joind.in/talk/view/11753',0,0,0,'2014-09-16 00:33:50','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(105,58,'Pulling the Strings: Backbone.Marionette for Single Page Apps','Single Page Apps are fast becoming the go-to of responsive front end user experiences now that modern JavaScript engines are lightning fast. However building a SPA brings in new hurdles and stress points in regards to how you organize your code, how you deliver templates, and how your application can live for long periods of time and maintain state without going crazy. Learn practical tips using Backbone.Marionette and how to shape your PHP application to better support this new style of UX.','regular','indepth','ux',0,'https://speakerdeck.com/dcousineau/pulling-the-strings-backbone-dot-marionette-and-require-dot-js-for-single-page-apps','Video of my presentation at empireJS: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4K4JKtAGPu4',0,0,0,'2014-09-16 00:35:39','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(106,58,'JavaScript for PHP Developers','JavaScript is definitely now a requirement for web developers, especially PHP developers, to really know and truly understand. Come learn JavaScript indepth, from finally figuring out exactly what \"this\" is to the modern libraries, frameworks, and toolchains that some of the best and most advanced sites are using today.','tutorial','overview','other',0,'https://speakerdeck.com/dcousineau/html5-and-javascript-part-deux-javascript','This will be a redux and update of the JS for PHP Devs tutorial session I gave at Tek 12 (the slides linked). I will most of the jQuery section (except for events, ajax, and selectors), spend time on Grunt and other toolchains, etc.',0,0,0,'2014-09-16 00:36:32','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(107,58,'How Not Using PHP Can Make You Better At PHP','The concept seems weird initially, but it\'s true: learning another programming language (instead of spending more time in PHP) will make you a better PHP programmer. Different programming languages, through variations in their grammar, encourage idioms that others don\'t and can actually influence how you approach a problem. Together we\'ll explore several non-PHP programming languages, see the problems they tackle cleanly, and learn how becoming more Pythonic, becoming a bigger LISPer, and more of a Rubyist can make you a better PHP developer.','regular','overview','devlife',0,'','New talk I\'m still preparing',0,0,0,'2014-09-16 00:40:34','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(108,60,'Building SPA with Symfony2 and AngularJS','Forget about classic website where UX is not so important. We are living in time where usability is one of the important thing if you are building some business client oriented web service. In locastic we are working on CRM that is based on Symfony2 as backend and AngularJS as frontend solution.\n\nHow to connect this two frameworks? What are best practices? What are disadvantageous? How to take best from both worlds? These are topics I will cover in my talk with real examples.','tutorial','handson','phpfuture',1,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-17 14:06:53','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(109,59,'The Golden Rule of Coding','\"Do unto others as you would have done unto you.\" It isnâ€™t just about being a great friend; it also applies to building great software. In this talk, we will look at how you should be approaching coding so that your application plays nicely with others, communicates effectively and is generally a good citizen.','regular','overview','devlife',1,'','https://joind.in/user/view/2660',0,0,0,'2014-09-17 20:25:38','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(110,59,'Building Engineering Teams','Just as software powers experiences, teams power businesses. Building a great team is just like writing great software; it doesnâ€™t happen by accident. As a leader in an organization, it is your responsibility to make sure your team is being continuously nurtured and challenged. In this talk we will discuss what it takes to build and grow an effective software development team.','regular','overview','other',0,'','https://joind.in/user/view/2660',0,0,0,'2014-09-17 20:26:16','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(111,59,'Make Your Code Your Friend','Friends are great. They share, they listen, they talk and they help you when you need them. Friends make life better. Code doesnâ€™t always act like a friend. Fortunately, as a developer you get to tell your code what to do. You can make the code your friend and give yourself the tools you need to be happier. In this talk, we will discuss ways to make your code share, listen, talk and help you when you need it.','regular','overview','devlife',0,'','https://joind.in/user/view/2660',0,0,0,'2014-09-17 20:26:49','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(112,38,'The Hardened Application: Testing Principles from OWASP','Secure development has become a necessary part of any development process, thereâ€™s no way around that. Protecting the various parts of your application (and users) is also becoming more and more complex. Writing the code is only half the battle - it still needs to be tested. What tests do you need to worry about, though? Thereâ€™s just not enough time to test all the things - a more targeted approach is necessary. Join me as I walk you through the most recent version of the OWASP Testing Guide, pointing out interesting points along the way and recommend some effective testing techniques.','regular','overview','security',0,'','This talk will be based on the information provided in the OWASP Testing Guide (v4.0). There\'ll be some PHP in the examples, but they\'re largely language-agnostic. Attendees should be familiar with the OWASP Top 10 guide and the basic terms involved in web application security.\n\nThis *could* potentially be expanded out to a tutorial session pretty easily - there\'s definitely enough content.',0,0,0,'2014-09-17 23:22:52','2014-09-18 16:31:36'),(113,61,'The road to Continuous Deployment','Deploying code changes continuously to your production environment has many benefits. New features get to your users much faster which enables very short and quick iterations on them. And due to the small change sets you tend to encounter less bugs and regressions. In this talk Iâ€™ll present what Continuous Deployment means, and what you have to do, step-by-step, to make it work successfully for your project. We will cover topics like trunk based development, feature flags, partial roll outs, continuous integration, deployment automation and application monitoring.','regular','overview','continuousdelivery',0,'','Previous slides: https://speakerdeck.com/bastianhofmann/\nPrevious talk ratings: https://joind.in/user/view/11182\nFull speaking history: http://lanyrd.com/profile/bastianhofmann/',0,0,0,'2014-09-18 01:58:28','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(114,61,'Bring your PHP application to the next level with React.JS','React.JS is a very powerful library for building user interfaces and the new, cool kid in the JavaScript world. But it is also very interesting for creating a fast, maintainable and interactive PHP application. In this talk I\'ll show what React is all about and how you can combine itâ€™s power with your PHP application, even if you have to render out HTML on the server side. The result will be a flexible, component based architecture that enables developers to take page elements, like a single \"follow\" button, and place it everywhere on the site without having to duplicate any PHP, JS, HTML, CSS or AJAX endpoints in the process.','regular','overview','crossingphp',0,'','This is an heavily updated evolution of my talk \"Marrying front with back end\" with a more detailed focus on how you can create such an architecture with React.\n\nPrevious slides: https://speakerdeck.com/bastianhofmann/\nPrevious talk ratings: https://joind.in/user/view/11182\nFull speaking history: http://lanyrd.com/profile/bastianhofmann/',0,0,0,'2014-09-18 01:59:07','2014-09-18 02:00:30'),(115,61,'My site is slow, what can I do? - Profiling PHP applications','It\'s nothing new that speed is important for the success of any web application. Only a few hundred milliseconds may lie between a user leaving your site or staying. Unfortunately performance problems are oftentimes hard to fix and even harder to pinpoint.\nIn this talk I will show you how we at ResearchGate measure web application performance, which means not only timing how long the PHP backend took to deliver a page, but also tracking the speed the users actually perceives in the browser. After that you will see how you can track down and analyze any problems you found through measuring with the help of tools like Xdebug, XHProf and the Symfony Debug Toolbar. And if you still need to get faster after optimizing and fixing all these issues, I\'ll introduce you to some tricks, techniques and patterns to even further decrease load times.','regular','overview','other',0,'','This talk will be heavily updated\nPrevious slides: https://speakerdeck.com/bastianhofmann/\nPrevious talk ratings: https://joind.in/user/view/11182\nFull speaking history: http://lanyrd.com/profile/bastianhofmann/',0,0,0,'2014-09-18 02:00:13','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(116,33,'Data Structures Workshop','This 3 hours workshop aims to arm you with the practical knowledge of when to use Data Structures, what benefits they could bring to your code.\nWe will explore the standard data structures in the SPL practically: the Linked List, the Heap, Fixed Array and Object Storage and some other variants of them.\n\nWe will profile those data structures to assess memory and time complexities to better understand the implication of using each of them.','tutorial','handson','devlife',1,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-18 13:21:39','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(117,33,'Watering the trees: An introduction to data structures','Did you know that your can store your data in something better than an array? Ever heard of B-trees? Wondering what a big O notation is all about? This talk is not got to make you a computer scientist, but it will help you get a better idea of all that stuff. We will explore some of the SPL classes and how you could utilize them in your PHP projects.','regular','overview','devlife',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-18 13:22:44','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(118,33,'Let\'s start Hacking!','Facebook introduced Hack lang for HHVM in March, 25 2014. So what\'s Hack? It\'s an almost interoperable language with PHP that tries to introduce new features to PHP. You get static typing, enforced typing hinting, generics among other features.\nWe will go through a few example to see what can Hack offer for a PHP developer.','regular','overview','phpfuture',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-18 13:23:13','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(119,62,'Working on legacy PHP application without losing your mind','While everyone likes to work on a greenfield project there is a point in developers career when one is confronted with a legacy application. This application is alive for a reason - it provides a business value. However the code is so messy and there are no automated tests whatsoever. No one likes to work with such a system and over time the ball of mud just becomes bigger and bigger. The team morale is at itâ€™s lowest.\n\nThis talk is a story of how we turned one such a system around. How to start small and work your way up to the point where you reach a confident state. It will show you how to optimize for team happiness. The topics it will cover are technical and practical: refactoring, unit and acceptance tests, static code analysis, continuous integration, architecture for testability, monitoring. The talk is inspired by real life experience, working on three legacy systems in the span of more than four years.','regular','overview','other',1,'','This is original talk, never presented before.',0,0,0,'2014-09-19 11:27:13','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(122,64,'Writing Faster PHP with HHVM and Hack','HHVM is the new hotness, a super-fast alternative PHP runtime from Facebook it can take your existing PHP code base and run it at blazing fast speeds... but is there more?\n\nHHVM also brings Hack to the table which some say is a better PHP. Hack adds numerous features to the PHP language we all know and love that help speed up both development time and runtime performance.\n\nGet the most out of your human and technical resources by using HHVM and Hack today!','regular','overview','phpfuture',0,'https://speakerdeck.com/dshafik/writing-faster-php-with-hhvm-and-hack','',1,0,0,'2014-09-19 18:33:05','2014-09-19 18:33:39'),(123,64,'PHP 5.NEW: The Best Bits','Are you still stuck on PHP 5.2? Looking to migrate from 5.3 to the latest and greatest?\n\nThis talk will cover all the best new features and tooling since PHP 5.3, all the way up to PHP 5.6 and beyond.\n\nNamespaces, Closures, Traits, Generators, Variadics/Argument unpacking, Composer, PSR-0 &amp; PSR-4 autoloading and more!','regular','overview','phpfuture',0,'https://speakerdeck.com/dshafik/php-5-dot-new-the-best-bits','This could be a full tutorial I think. If you\'re interested, let me know.\n\nJoind.in from NEPHP: http://joind.in/talk/view/11473',1,0,0,'2014-09-19 18:34:45','2014-09-19 18:35:47'),(124,41,'Put Rabbit(MQ) into the game and let Symfony be the pivot of your architecture','Are you still using crons? really? It is high time to make your Symfony based system react instantly to changes. Placing Rabbit(MQ) into the mix will also make your application scalable and reliable.\n \nAt Namshi, Rocket Internet e-commerce venture in Dubai, we use various technologies in our software stack including NodeJs, PHP and AngularJs. We went through lots of changes in our software stack in the past year. Now, our backend APIs are powered by Symfony. In this session, I will uncover some real life use cases of Rabbit MQ with a back-end that serves millions of users.\n \nWe use Rabbit MQ to communicate between multiple systems as well. The talk will also include some best practices for using Message Queue (MQ) software with Rabbit MQ in particular.','regular','overview','phpfuture',1,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-20 08:31:27','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(125,65,'OrientDB, the fastest document-based graphdb','OrientDB is a NoSQL graph database which also includes a document layer (like MongoDB or CouchDB): since his first stable released it gained a lot of attention, enough to push big companies like Sky and UltraDNS to use it in production: it\'s written in Java and it\'s amazingly fast, since it can store up to 150,000 records per second on common hardware; moreover, thanks to being a graphdb, it can manage relationship so fast that, compared to traditional RDBMS, it can be more than 1000% faster than them.\n\nIn this talk we will see a bit of the graph theory, how OrientDB functions as both a document db and graphdb and how to work with it from its HTTP interface.','regular','overview','other',0,'http://www.slideshare.net/odino/orientdb-the-fastest-documentbased-graph-database-confoo-2014-in-montreal-ca','',0,0,0,'2014-09-20 21:29:43','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(126,65,'SOA with Symfony2','Symfony2 is one of the de-facto standards for developing enterprise-ready applications in PHP: being a very structured and decoupled framework, it becomes very handy and suitable for building Service Oriented architectures, which require loose coupling and a clean and tested structure.\n\nIn this talk we will see how we could create a Service Oriented Architecture in Symfony2 taking advantage of messaging systems like RabbitMQ, HTTP APIs and Symfony2â€™s internals, having a closer look at the problems weâ€™ll have to face while switching from the context of a monolithic application to a set of services.','regular','overview','phpfuture',0,'http://www.slideshare.net/odino/soa-with-symfony2-confoo-2014-in-montreal-ca','',0,0,0,'2014-09-20 21:30:25','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(127,65,'Tricks and tips for your Service Oriented Architecture','While building Service Oriented Architectures, which require loose coupling and a clean and tested structure, you need to keep in mind that you should rely on very structured and decoupled frameworks, letting the door open for new integration and paradigms, like messaging queues or hypermedia-based webservices. But apart from this, are there any other things that we should keep in mind while going SOA? For example, how can you deploy your architecture if each service requires a few minutes to be deployed and your deployment mechanism can only deploy one service a time? How do you handle cross-service features in git, when you would need to create, review and integrate N pull requests that involve different services?\n\nIn this talk we will see how to avoid common hassles and mistakes while developing your own SOA.','regular','overview','architectures',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-20 21:30:52','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(128,65,'HTTP colon slash slash: the end of the road?','For years we\'ve been used to the HTTP protocol, one of the reasons behind the web\'s success, a protocol able to scale up to billions of requests and beyond.\nBut there\'s more we can achieve, taking advantage of HTTP/1.1 hidden features, having a look at HTTP/2.0 and SPDY, the Google-proposed new protocol which is already making web faster.\n\nBack to the basics: what empowers and will empower the web?','regular','overview','architectures',0,'http://www.slideshare.net/odino/http-colon-slash-slash-the-end-of-the-road','',0,0,0,'2014-09-20 21:31:20','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(129,65,'Practice is king: write an Open Source library for fun and profit','In this talk we will focus on the practical aspects of open source: how to write a public library and what do we need to make it successful.\n\nFrom coding guidelines to packaging it, there are are a few points that people usually do not keep in mind while releasing their code to the public: time to sit on our laptop, get the live coding session rolling and see how to publish beautiful code.','regular','overview','devlife',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-20 21:31:45','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(130,65,'Dockerize it: stop living in the past and embrace the future','Docker is a groundbreaking technology that will heavily influence how we will write software in the years to come: let\'s then have a look at\n\n* where it comes from (Linux Containers)\n* how it works\n* how to dockerize simple apps to easily deploy them on production\n* how you can use Docker in local environments to simplify your development workflow\n\nDo you like Vagrant, auto-scaling or 12-factor apps? Then get ready to be mindblown.','regular','overview','virtualization',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-20 21:32:12','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(131,65,'Run a product? Then do crazy things like Google Docs as a backend','At Namshi we run a product that needs to quickly evolve and be ready to change: new features, integrations technologies are integrated every week to be able to keep up to date with the market and the technology around us -- we don\'t want to be obsolete in 6 months.\n\nBut how can we deliver things fast? From abusing of expression languages to using Google Docs as a backend, learn how we tackled complexity and kept things as lean as possible.','regular','overview','devlife',1,'','A very practical talk in which Im gonna show the 10 things that made our development team so fast and pleased all the other 20 departments of the company\n\nI feel this talk, more than anything else I submitted, has the most insights for the audience',0,0,0,'2014-09-20 21:33:11','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(132,67,'Coding the Semantic Web with HTML5 and JSON-LD','How can you help the realize Tim Berners-Lee\'s vision of the semantic web? Examples will demonstrate techniques for coding web page content with semantic meaning using HTML5 elements, the microdata format, and schema.org definitions. The recently released JSON-LD specification for defining linked data will be described in depth.\n\nImplementing the semantic web â€“ conveying the meaning of content in a machine readable format â€“ is an elusive goal that has been worked on since the World Wide Web was first introduced. While complex technology stacks have been successfully implemented for specialized knowledge based industries, there are simple techniques for defining the meaning of content that anyone who tags web page content can learn. The concept of the semantic web and the following three examples will be discussed in this technology presentation.\n\nâ€¢	HTML5 elements are defined with more specific semantic meaning than before. Tagging content with the correct element requires good language skills and a clear understanding of the HTML5 specification.\n\nâ€¢	Microdata combined with schema.org definitions has been the traditional format used by search engine companies to generate and deliver rich snippets, which offers the immediate benefit of delivering improved search engine click though rates for website owners.\n\nâ€¢	The JSON-LD specification, a newer format used to describe linked data, has achieved rapid adoption. Adding JSON-LD scripts to web pages help companies like Google build their knowledge graphs, and other companies develop more sophisticated web applications using techniques like schema.org actions.','regular','overview','other',1,'http://www.slideshare.net/DaveKelleher/semantic-html-5-v2','David is an organizer for the annual Northeast PHP Conference\n\nPrior experience for you to consider:\n\nSemantic Web Joind.in Ratings\nhttp://joind.in/talk/view/8913\n\nSemantic Web Talk\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SOnWncxJX6k&amp;t=1m57s\n\nStage Performance Experience\nhttp://panelpicker.sxsw.com/vote/42672\n\nCollege Lecturer Biography\nhttp://www.emerson.edu/academics/faculty-guide/profile/david-kelleher/239',0,0,0,'2014-09-21 06:13:32','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(133,67,'Inside Cinematic UX Design','Modern website design has expanded beyond the traditional page model. â€œThe moviesâ€ are a source of inspiration for a new generation of websites such as interactive music videos. Websites that tell stories or associate emotions with a companyâ€™s brand are good candidates for cinematic styled interfaces. Implementation can include large hero units, and full screen background images or videos.\n\nFilm clips will illustrate the cinematic language used by filmmakers to deliver emotional experiences. Principals that will be discussed include:\n* Framing\n* Contrast\n* Movement\n* Time\n* Depth\n\nJavaScript and JQuery code examples will show how web sites can implement video cuts, dissolves, and virtual camera movements. Code that can create a sense of continuity in UX design will also be included in the talk.','regular','overview','ux',0,'http://www.slideshare.net/DaveKelleher/cinematic-ux-design','David is an organizer at the annual Northeast PHP conference.\n\nPrior experience for you to consider:\n\nCinematic UX Joind.in Ratings\nhttp://joind.in/talk/view/11482\n\nCinematic UX Interview\nhttp://2014.northeastphp.org/uploads/audio/kelleher-interview.mp3\n\nStage Performance Experience\nhttp://panelpicker.sxsw.com/vote/42672\n\nCollege Lecturer Biography\nhttp://www.emerson.edu/academics/faculty-guide/profile/david-kelleher/239',0,0,0,'2014-09-21 06:14:54','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(134,67,'Cryptocurrency Cookbook for PHP Developers','Bitcoin and other distributed virtual currencies are revolutionizing how monetary value is stored and exchanged on the Internet. Key opportunities and risks will be described. The two main objectives of this talk will be to explain the underlying blockchain and cryptology technologies that make them work, and to demonstrate PHP recipes for using the web services that enable payment processing, identity validation, and smart contract execution.','regular','overview','other',0,'','David is an organizer of the annual Northeast PHP conference\n\nPrior experience for you to consider:\n\nJoind.in Ratings\nhttp://joind.in/user/view/21749\n\nStage Performance Experience\nhttp://panelpicker.sxsw.com/vote/42672\n\nCollege Lecturer Biography\nhttp://www.emerson.edu/academics/faculty-guide/profile/david-kelleher/239',0,0,0,'2014-09-21 06:16:58','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(135,28,'Youâ€™ll Never Believe How Easy Deployments Can Really Be...','The deadline is looming: one week until we release the new version. Some features aren\'t going to make the cut, but the boss really wants to make sure these critical bugs are fixed. You canâ€™t wait for the release cycle to be over so you can relax.\n\nBut what if I told you it didn\'t have to be that way? What if I could show you how to create a world where there is no release cycle? A world where weekend deployments are a rarity, not the norm?! In this talk we will cover the steps we took to achieve the coding utopia of releasing a feature as soon as itâ€™s ready - many times per day. Youâ€™ll find out that by implementing a continuous deployment flow, you can empower your developers to take ownership and become more productive.','regular','overview','continuousdelivery',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-21 08:49:33','2014-09-26 14:45:03'),(136,68,'Debugging: past, present and future','In this talk I will go over all the past, present and future debugging\ntechniques. The talk start by giving an overview on PHP\'s (ancient) standard\nfeatures for debugging, additional (userland) libraries and functionality in\nframeworks.\n\nAfter the introductions we move on to the meatier stuff and I will talk about\nlive-action debuggers, such as Xdebug and Zend\'s debugger. They both provide\ninformation while a script is being executed, in combination with IDEs.\n\nIn the future, there is PHP 5.6\'s phpdbg which allows for some debugging and\nother analysis. I am also unveiling a project that allows you to \"step back\"\nwhile debugging as well; introspect what your script\'s or application\'s\nexact execution paths was; and trace variable modifications.','regular','indepth','phpfuture',1,'','http://derickrethans.nl/talks.html',0,0,0,'2014-09-21 23:24:04','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(137,68,'From SQL to noSQL','In this talk I will explain the differences between different types of noSQL\ndatabases as well as the CAP theorem. I will then progress to illustrate\nwhich paradigm shifts are necessary to successfully implement noSQL, using\nMongoDB as an example.\n\nThe approaches to schema design, fault tolerance, the network breaking and\nlatency are all things that are inherent to scalability with noSQL solutions\nand with this talk you will learn how to use MongoDB effectively considering\nall the above mentioned situations.\n\nCovered subjects will be: CAP theorem, schema design, dealing with error\nsituations and architecture of multi-node set-ups.','regular','overview','architectures',1,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-21 23:24:49','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(138,68,'One extension, two engines','In this talk, I am explaining how we went from supporting a legacy driver for\none language engine (PHP) to an architecture where multiple language engines\nare supported. \n\nThis is the tale of the new MongoDB driver for PHP and HHVM. We started off\nwith one massively complex (and legacy) driver. The goal was an easy to\nmaintain extension. In our case that became a joint venture between core\ndrivers (in C/C++), and a user-land supporting library in PHP. \n\nBecause there are now other engines that run PHP, such as HHVM and Hippy, the\nonly real work that needs to be done for porting to a new engine is the basic\ncore driver.\n\nThis talk explains the choices, considerations and issues that we ran into\nwhile developing the driver to work with multiple engines; and our first\nsteps supporting Facebook\'s HHVM.','regular','indepth','devlife',0,'','Quite an internals talk, this is not about a specific database.',0,0,0,'2014-09-21 23:25:45','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(139,68,'Find all the things','In this talk you will learn how to effectively store, retrieve and display\ngeospatial data, such as roads, points of interests and more. \n\nFirst we will be importing an OpenStreetMap dataset covering London into\nMongoDB. This is not trivial due to the amount of data.\n\nAfter importing, we will look at which types of queries we can \nrun to find things. Either by predicates, or with geospatial queries.\n\nAnd last we will have a look at how to display the data that we\'ve requested,\nthrough a website using the Leaflet mapping library.','regular','overview','architectures',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-21 23:26:20','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(140,68,'Text wrangling and word smithing','This talk covers multiple methods of querying text with MongoDB. From\nsimple string and regexp matching, to full text search indexes. The talk will\ncover stemming, tokenization and issues while sorting multiple languages.\n\nWe will look at techniques for search queries that deal with multiple locales\nfollowing Unicode specifications.\n\nLastly, we will also look at how to get our data into Elastic Search as a\ndedicated engine for doing full text search with automatic replication.','regular','overview','ux',0,'','I put it in the usability, as correct language searching and sorting belongs there. It\'s also a bit language-geeky.',0,0,0,'2014-09-21 23:27:04','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(141,68,'From SQL to noSQL','In this tutorial I will explain the differences between different types of\nnoSQL databases as well as the CAP theorem. I will then progress to illustrate\nwhich paradigm shifts are necessary to successfully implement noSQL, using\nMongoDB as an example.\n\nThe approaches to schema design, fault tolerance, the network breaking and\nlatency are all things that are inherent to scalability with noSQL solutions\nand with this talk you will learn how to use MongoDB effectively considering\nall the above mentioned situations. \n\nCovered subjects will be: CAP theorem, schema design, dealing with error\nsituations and architecture of multi-node set-ups.','tutorial','handson','architectures',1,'','This is a tutorial version of the talk with the same title, but now we\'re letting the audience actually build things. It\'s going to be very similar (albeit a bit shorter) than http://derickrethans.nl/talks/mongo-tut-summercamp14.pdf',0,0,0,'2014-09-21 23:28:27','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(142,66,'The power of the soft skill','Every day developers ask themselves what they can do to improve their technical expertise. Which comes to no surprise seeing the nature of this industry.\nHowever it is important to focus some of your time on training and learning to use your soft skills. This will help you be a better developer. It will also give you an edge when trying to get into a certain company or when trying to obtain that contract you always wanted.\nDuring this talk you will be shown some of the most vital skills needed for developers to reach that goal. Besides the overview we will also dive into methods by which you can actively work on improving said skills.','regular','overview','devlife',1,'','This talk will be held at King Foo before it will be presented at a conference. If possible it will also be tested and fine-tuned at a meet-up.\nThe slides will be available online and feedback can be given through Joind.in by the time the conference will start.\nThere will be interaction with the audience to some extend.',1,0,0,'2014-09-22 12:53:56','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(143,71,'Treating Javascriptophpobia','Javascriptophpobia: \"A persistent, abnormal, and irrational fear of Javascript that compels PHP developers to avoid it, despite the awareness and reassurance that it is not dangerous.\" In this session, I will show you why that fear is irrational, and with any luck you will be cured from it. Starting from what we all know best, PHP, we\'ll have a look at how certain concepts we already know, translate back to Javascript. During this session, we will not concentrate on the syntax of the building blocks that constitute the great Javascript language, but rather on the concepts and semantics of certain techniques. Once we know and understand these concepts, we\'ll end with some best practices for writing neat and structured Javascript. This treatment is highly recommended for anyone who exhibits symptoms of severe Javascript dislike and aversion.','regular','overview','crossingphp',0,'','My previous experience was a Javascript Unit Testing talk on PHPBenelux 2012. I noticed that the turnout was not that great, partly because a lot of developers don\'t really like Javascript. So I figured I should first try to explain to my fellow developers how Javascript works, what the concepts are, why certain things work the way they do. Once we know and understand that, Javascript is not that annoying anymore. You can do beautiful things with it. In some case it\'s more limiting than PHP, but this may also help you to be more creative in finding solutions to a problem. The goal of this talk is to share my passion for Javascript, teach the concepts, and bring some understanding of the language.',1,0,0,'2014-09-23 09:27:07','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(144,70,'Creating your own Entity/Object Manager','Most of us are used to working with an Entity or Object manager. In ORMs like Doctrine, they are the central point to talk to to keep track of our objects (and safely load/store them into a DB or document store). We can use this approach to not only manage objects in our database, but to manage third party sources, like webservices, etcâ€¦ This talk will explain the place of the Entity Manager in our projects and how to write your own version of it.','regular','handson','phpfuture',0,'','This talk will be a practical approach/follow-up of the \"The Database Access rEvolution\" talk (https://speakerdeck.com/coudenysj/the-database-access-revolution-with-at-miljar), using all the terms in practice.\n\nI recently build such an object manager to talk to a Navision SOAP service, so the talk will contain lots of real life (and working) examples.',1,0,0,'2014-09-23 09:39:15','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(145,70,'Database Access: There and Back Again','In PHP, we have different tools at our disposition to talk to a database. There are also different ways of working with the data coming from that database. Many people take working with a database abstraction layer or ORM for granted. But how do these modern tools work? Why are we doing things the way we are doing them now? By taking back a step and looking at each iteration in the evolution of working with databases in PHP applications, we will try to explain the principles on which our current tools are built.','regular','overview','phpfuture',0,'https://speakerdeck.com/coudenysj/the-database-access-revolution-with-at-miljar','This is a duo talk with Tom Van Herreweghe. The bottom line of the talk presented during the user group will stay the same, but we\'re fine-tuning the content and adding a \"what\'s next\" chapter where we look at the future.',1,0,0,'2014-09-23 12:52:50','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(146,31,'From London to Chicago: A Conceptual Map for Learning Unit Testing','All aboard as we travel from London to Chicago! These two historical methodologies approach unit testing from divergent perspectives. Unfortunately, few learning resources explicitly identify with one or the other, creating a confused and frustrating learning landscape for the novice and journeyman alike. During our voyage, we\'ll explore each school\'s philosophical underpinnings; not only how they test, but how they view testing, what they test and why. We\'ll discuss the relative merits of the two approaches, as well as how to implement each style. Finally, we\'ll develop a conceptual model for unit testing which can serve as a foundation upon which to evaluate and integrate other resources you may encounter along your testing journey.','regular','indepth','testing',0,'','I am constantly surprised by the fact that the overwhelming majority of talks, articles, blog posts, tutorials, etc. on Unit Testing jump right into the â€œhowâ€ before making the case for the â€œwhyâ€. Even when the case for â€œwhyâ€ is sufficiently made, little to no time is spent laying a theoretical foundation which would allow the learner to integrate what they learn into a consistent conceptual framework and to be able compare and contrast it with other resources they might encounter going forward. This hampered my growth as I was learning the testing discipline and Iâ€™ve spoken to many young developers who have had similar experiences â€“ thereâ€™s simply no good primer for how it all fits together. This talks seeks to fill that void and covers the following:\n\n-	Why Test?\n--	Business Case\n-	Why Unit Testing\n--	Case from Development Methodology\n-	What Unit Testing Isnâ€™t\n--	Unit Testing vs Functional Testing\n--	Unit Testing vs Acceptance Testing\n--	Unit Testing vs Integration Testing\n-	TDD vs BDD\n-	London School vs Chicago Schools of Unit Testing\n-	Making Sense of Test Doubles\n--	Dummies\n--	Stubs\n--	Spies\n--	Mocks\n--	Fakes\n-	The Role of Isolation\n-	How Big is a Unit?\n-	Overview Testing Tools\n--	xUnit Frameworks\n--     Mocking Frameworks\n\nSuitable for beginner and intermediate level.',0,0,0,'2014-09-23 15:37:26','2014-09-28 15:39:16'),(147,31,'Inside Laravel 5.0','One of PHP\'s most popular frameworks has undergone a major version upgrade! Join us to explore what\'s new in Laravel 5.0. We\'ll explore  putting your Controllers on a crash diet with Custom Request Objects and Method Level Dependency Injection, managing 3rd party authentication with Socialite, understanding the new Directory Structure and Service Provider Architecture, leveraging FlySystem Integration, improving performance with Route Caching and increasing decoupling using Contracts. Special attention will be given to contributing to the framework using the exciting new contribution tool, Liferaft.','regular','handson','other',0,'','Laravel 5.0 is scheduled for release in mod-November, so the content will be highly relevant. Suitable for beginner and intermediate audiences. Includes code samples.',0,0,0,'2014-09-23 15:38:10','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(148,31,'The Human Side of Software: Managing Cognitive Bias','We\'d never knowingly rely upon a programming tool prone to seemingly inexplicable error, yet we often do just that by ignoring the limitations of the human minds which make up our teams. Join us as we explore three areas where cognitive biases manifest; perception, behavior and motivation, and their impact upon the development process. We\'ll learn why they occur, how to recognize them, and tactics to mitigate the impact of these human \"bugs\" on our projects.','regular','indepth','other',0,'','Biases covered will include:\nï‚§	Anchor Bias\nï‚§	Clustering Illusion\nï‚§	Knowledge Bias\nï‚§	Availability Cascade\nï‚§	Zero-Risk Bias\nï‚§	Bandwagon Effect\nï‚§	Intergroup Bias\nï‚§	Illusion of Control\nï‚§	Social Desirability Bias\nï‚§	Comparison Bias\nï‚§	Illusion of Transparency\nï‚§	Halo Effect\nï‚§	Fundamental Attribution Error\n\nSuitable for beginner or intermediate levels.',0,0,0,'2014-09-23 15:38:51','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(149,31,'Getting Off the Freelance Roller Coaster','You love the idea of freelancing, but in practice, you\'ve found it to be stressful, unreliable, at times even terrifying. It doesn\'t have to be this way. Learn from a seasoned freelancer the strategies and tactics he\'s used to avoid the freelance feast/famine cycle and log billable hours every work day for nearly four years. Join us to receive actionable tips you can begin using immediately to stay booked and get off the freelance roller coaster.','regular','overview','other',0,'','This talk is an exposition of the tips and tricks that I use to stay fully booked as a freelance developer/consultant and to avoid the feast/famine cycle that plagues many freelancers. Using these strategies, Iâ€™ve managed to not miss having billable hours on a work day for over three years! The talk originated with a series of tweets that I was encouraged to share by other freelancers. That series can be found in a Storify summary here: https://storify.com/coderabbi/staybooked. The tweets were very well received and the Storify summary received over 1,000 hits within the first 48 hours. I later encapsulated those tips in a blog post which has received an additional 2,500 hits. As a result of those tweets, Iâ€™ve been approached to guest blog on several freelance sites and write an article for PHP Architect magazine. This talk includes the strategies which were the focus of those tweets as well as many others.\n\nSuitable for beginner and intermediate audiences.',0,0,0,'2014-09-23 15:39:26','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(150,73,'Dashboards for devops and other web folks','It would be nice if devops could sit down with web applications and discuss their feelings over cup of coffee. Instead, they have to jump through hoops and figure out what is going on by using tools such as StatsD/Graphite, Nagios, Cacti, New relic and many others. Successful data collection is only half of the solution. Presenting real time data in a way that it intuitively shows you that something is different and aiding you in pinpointing problem makes up other half. \n\nTalk will focus on importance of monitoring web applications and give advice on how to organize your dashboard for quick reactions. Find out tips and tricks as well as what impact had running a dashboard monitor on overall project performance.','regular','overview','other',0,'','Talk will be held at WebCamp Zagreb 2014 conference.',0,0,0,'2014-09-23 20:11:48','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(151,74,'What\'s new in Magento 2?','Magento 2 was first announced way back when in 2010, but a lot can change in IT over four years.\nThere was not a lot of noise from the Magento camp until October 2013. Now there is a public repository with updates published weekly.\nIn this talk we\'ll have a look at the current technical status, make a comparison to the first version of Magento and review the road ahead.','regular','overview','phpfuture',0,'http://de.slideshare.net/TobiasZander/magento-2-meet-magento-2014-de','',0,0,0,'2014-09-24 08:39:44','2014-09-24 08:42:50'),(152,74,'The myth of the 10x programmers','Recently on the net there was a lot of chatter surrounding the myth of the 10x programmer.\nIt claims that some individuals are 10x more efficiently than some of their colleagues.\nIn this talk we\'ll look into this species of superproductives!\nHow can we measure efficiency of a programmer at all? Is it the lines of code, amount of fixed bugs or number of empty Red Bull cans per hour?\nAfter that we\'ll have a look if it\'s actually possible to achieve 10x productivity and if so what\'s needed to get there.','regular','overview','other',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-24 08:41:00','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(153,74,'XSS and SQL injections - The tip of the web security iceberg','You might know about XSS and usual SQL injection, but time has changed and we have to keep up-to-date with the latest attack scenarios.\nDo you also know what clickjacking is? If not I\'ll show you how to protect against it.\nI\'ll also present techniques like Perfect Pixel Timing and a combination of xss/time-based-sql-injection to access intranet sites, which are not even compromised.','regular','overview','security',1,'http://cdn.oreillystatic.com/en/assets/1/event/115/XSS%20and%20SQL%20Injections_%20The%20Tip%20of%20the%20Web%20Security%20Iceberg%20%20Presentation.pdf','',0,0,0,'2014-09-24 08:42:42','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(154,75,'Buzzwords 101','With software development there are a lot of technical terms, technologies that are used day in, day out. For new comers to software development all these words can be rather confusing and intimidating. This would be a quick intro what these terms mean and point people to resources to learn more in depth.','regular','overview','other',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-24 16:28:48','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(155,66,'Manage yourself to a clear mind','We all went through it at least once. You try to pick up work where you left it only to find out you have absolutely no idea what you were doing, what needed to be done and how you were going to do it.\nThrow in sickness, holidays, (long) weekends, context switching and distractions and itâ€™s even harder to pick up where you left off. This will lead to a lot of unnecessary stress and a troubled mind.\nWith all the different projects and side projects going on at the same time who can blame you?\nWell, Iâ€™m here to face you with the ugly truth, you have only yourself to blame.\nBut no worries, the main problem here is management. Management of yourself and of your projects, tasks, events and so on.\n\nIn this talk I will show you different techniques in combination with different tools to help you manage all your projects, tasks, ideas, meetings and more. Every technique will be explained and with the help of an example you can see just how this works in your advantage.\nBy finding out what technique matches your workflow and mindset best you will be able to manage yourself and boost productivity. Your mind will once again be clear and stress levels will be at a minimum.','regular','overview','devlife',0,'','This talk will be held at King Foo before it will be presented at a conference. If possible it will also be tested and fine-tuned at a meet-up.\nThe slides will be available online and feedback can be given through Joind.in by the time the conference will start.\nThere will be interaction with the audience to some extend.',1,0,0,'2014-09-24 21:43:13','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(156,76,'Performance Testing Crash Course','The performance of your application affects your business more than you might think. Top engineering organizations think of performance not as a nice-to-have, but as a crucial feature of their product. Those organizations understand that performance has a direct impact on user experience and, ultimately, their bottom line. Unfortunately, most engineering teams do not regularly test the performance and scalability of their infrastructure. Dustin Whittle shares the latest performance testing tools and insights into why your team should add performance testing to the development process. Learn how to evaluate performance and scalability on the server-side and the client-side with tools like Siege, Bees with Machine Guns, Google PageSpeed, WBench, and more. Take back an understanding of how to automate performance and load testing and evaluate the impact it has on performance and your business.','regular','handson','testing',1,'https://speakerdeck.com/dustinwhittle','',1,0,0,'2014-09-25 00:20:46','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(157,76,'Scaling PHP in the real world!','PHP is used by the likes of Facebook, Yahoo, Zynga, Tumblr, Etsy, and Wikipedia. How do the largest internet companies scale PHP to meet their demand? Join this session and find out how to use the latest tools in PHP for developing high performance applications. Weâ€™ll take a look at common techniques for scaling PHP applications and best practices for profiling and optimizing performance. After this session, youâ€™ll leave prepared to tackle your next enterprise PHP project.','regular','handson','architectures',0,'https://speakerdeck.com/dustinwhittle','',1,0,0,'2014-09-25 00:21:35','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(158,77,'Decorating Applications with Stack','Stack is a convention for composing HttpKernelInterface middlewares. By following Stack\'s conventions one can add behavior and functionality to any application based on Symfony\'s HttpKernelInterface. This means Stack middlewares can be applied to Silex, Laravel 4, and Drupal 8 applications in addition to any other HttpKernelInterface based application. Learn the conventions, see community middlewares, and find to how to get started with Stack.','regular','overview','phpfuture',0,'https://beau.io/talks/2014/09/09/decorating-applications-with-stack-milwaukee-php-user-group/','This talk will focus on practical use cases and examples of composing HttpKernelInterface middlewares. Each of the core Stack tools will be shown and discussed along with a number of community middlewares.\n\nI\'d love to get a chance to really talk about Stack! It is a great concept and I hope that it takes off in 2014.\n\nhttp://stackphp.com/\n\nFull disclosure: I am one of Stack\'s creators and would LOVE to have a chance to talk about the power of Stack and composable interfaces.',0,0,0,'2014-09-25 00:59:12','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(159,77,'Laziness Is King: Writing Providers for Silex and Pimple','So you\'ve gotten to the point in your Silex application that you want to start breaking it out into modular pieces. Silex bootable providers and controller providers and Pimple service providers to the rescue! These interfaces appear to be really simple but do you know which things can safely be done in each?\n\nFind out the intended purpose and which operations should be done (or avoided) in each interface. Get a tour of Silex and Pimple and learn about why laziness is so important when writing code for Silex. By following some best practices you can avoid headaches for both you and your users.','regular','indepth','devlife',0,'https://speakerdeck.com/simensen/writing-silex-service-providers-and-controller-providers-madison-php','This talk is based on a lot of discussion and helping people in #silex-php debug their applications. Laziness and abuse of what should and should not be done in service providers is usually the core of what people are having problems with.\n\nThis talk was given at Madison PHP Conference at the end of 2013.\n\nhttps://speakerdeck.com/simensen/writing-silex-service-providers-and-controller-providers-madison-php\n\nBlog posts this talk is based on:\n\nhttp://srcmvn.com/blog/2013/02/22/writing-silex-service-providers/\nhttp://srcmvn.com/blog/2013/03/08/silex-service-providers-and-controller-providers-what-is-safe-to-do-where/\n\nThis talk needs to be updated for Pimple 2 as there have been some major changes since then! I\'m super excited about the changes. In particular, Pimple now has its own Service Provider interface! Very cool stuff there.',0,0,0,'2014-09-25 01:00:23','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(160,77,'Embedded Composer: CLI and Phar Applications','Composer is a wonderful way to manage a project. But what happens when you need your CLI or phar distributed application to be extensible at runtime? Enter Embedded Composer.\n\nEmbedding Composer into your CLI or phar packaged application will ensure that the dependencies already included by your application are taken into account when adding additional dependencies at runtime.','regular','indepth','phpfuture',0,'https://beau.io/talks/2013/05/23/embedded-composer-sflive-portland-2013/','This talk will focus on CLI based applications or applications that are distributed as a phar. This is going to be similar to the talk I gave at Symfony Live in Portland with a few important changes. More time on use cases upfront.\n\nThis is a walkthrough of embedding Composer into a CLI application. It works well but the concepts are pretty experimental and a lot of theory and Composer internals are explored in this talk. It does work and Sculpin uses it quite effectively.\n\nThis talk is a lot of fun for me and is very exciting. It is the reason I got involved in Composer development and sort of launched the idea of building Sculpin to begin with.\n\nhttps://beau.io/talks/2013/05/23/embedded-composer-sflive-portland-2013/\nhttps://speakerdeck.com/simensen/embedded-composer-sflive-portland-2013\nhttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9CSovVvRwXk\nhttps://joind.in/talk/view/8667',0,0,0,'2014-09-25 01:01:47','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(161,77,'Namespaces and Autoloading','Want to make sure that your class names don\'t overwrite the class names for any other projects on the server? Hate having long class names like [insert ridiculously long classname here]? Namespaces were introduced in PHP 5.3 to help address these common issues. Learn how to namespace classes and see how namespaces and class autoloading can make your coding experience much nicer!','regular','indepth','phpfuture',0,'https://beau.io/talks/2014/02/08/namespaces-and-autoloading-sunshine-php-2014/','This is a super basic walkthrough of namespaces and autoloading targeting users who are either very new to PHP or have never moved beyond PHP 5.2 or have only had an opportunity to work with legacy systems.\n\nBasic, but a lot of fun. :) It has been pretty well received the few times I\'ve given it (once for Madison PHP and once as an uncon talk for Sunshine PHP) even for seasoned developers.\n\nIn my various talks on Composer, a lot of time is spent showing how to configure autoloaders. Most of that deals with namespaces. Randomly asking the audience about their knowledge on namespaces has yielded results that are pretty surprising (at least to me): a healthy chunk of people are not using namespaces.\n\nSomewhat relevant, this popped up on Reddit recently: \nhttp://www.reddit.com/r/PHP/comments/1u1ztr/attempting_to_understand_namespacing_and_its/\n\nhttps://beau.io/talks/2014/02/08/namespaces-and-autoloading-sunshine-php-2014/',0,0,0,'2014-09-25 01:04:05','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(162,77,'Decomposing Packages','Using Composer and Packagist makes integrating third-party code a lot easier but sometimes relying on other people\'s code can be more trouble than it is worth. Projects are abandoned. Maintainers may not be super responsive to pull requests, pull requests may be rejected outright due to maintainers not liking the changes you\'ve made, and pull requests may not even make sense if the changes are too specific to your project. Especially for trivial packages it may not make sense to take on this technical debt. Fortunately, Composer provides tools to help make these situations a little easier to manage.\n\nLearn how you can leverage Composer features like \"replace\" and Composer tools like Satis to help manage forks of third-party packages. See some of the pros and cons of different ways to handle these issues so that you can feel more confident in how you decide to move forward with decomposing other people\'s packages.','regular','overview','devlife',0,'','This talk will be based on recent experiences in dealing with a new third-party vendor I\'ve been working with and trying to use code before it is actually ready to be used. I\'ve tried a few different techniques including creating a fork of the project as well as just copying the code directly into my project so I could work on it directly. I\'ve also been playing a bit with satis to help speed up performance of dealing with these packages so I do not need to do inline VCS repositories while I\'m working on them in early development phases. This is particularly useful when packages are not even on Packagist yet.\n\nThere are also a subset of packages where it doesn\'t always make sense to actually bring a project in as a dependency. A package that contains a single class that isn\'t likely to change often, for example, might be bettered handled as just a local utility class in my own namespace so that I can manage it directly. If it works now, chances are it will continue to work forever and I don\'t want to run the risk of someone else messing that up for me for such a trivial bit of code.',0,0,0,'2014-09-25 01:04:50','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(163,77,'Say What? Ubiquitous Language and You!','When you discuss a project with other people involved with a project in any capacity are you ever absolutely certain that they understand exactly what you\'ve said? If you haven\'t paid super close attention to naming chances are you can\'t be certain! What if you could all speak the same language?\n\nOne of the core Domain-Driven Design (DDD) tools is the Ubiquitous Language. By paying close attention to how domain experts (people intimately familiar with how a specific part of a business actually runs) you will start learning critical information that you can use to help ensure that your code more accurately models the business processes it represents. While this is an important part of practicing DDD the idea behind the Ubiquitous Language can be applied to almost any project to help keep everyone involved on the same page!','regular','overview','other',0,'','I am super interested in Ubiquitous Language. It is something that I know is super important in the DDD world but I\'m convinced that at least parts of it can be applied to any project, even if it is not fully embracing DDD.',0,0,0,'2014-09-25 01:05:33','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(164,77,'Bringing Sculpin to Life','Are you curious about the process of creating an open-source application from scratch? Are you asking questions like, \"should I contribute to an existing project instead?\" or \"does the world really need yet another [insert your idea here]?\" Maybe you are wrestling with, \"am I good enough?\" or \"what if nobody wants to use it?\" Once you decide to go for it, a whole new round of decisions need to be made like \"which framework should I use?\" , \"should I roll everything from scratch?\" or \"should I use some standalone libraries to help me?\" And this is before you\'ve even written any code!\n\nCome see how this scenario played out for Sculpin (sculpin.io). Learn about the motivations for creating yet another static site generator for PHP. Find out about the questions and barriers that almost kept Sculpin from ever being created. Discover the technology decisions that needed to be made and how those have changed over time. Walk away knowing more about what it was like for one open-source application to grow from idea to a full-fledged application with actual users.','regular','overview','phpfuture',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-25 01:07:30','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(165,77,'Managing Dependencies with Composer','Traditionally, managing third-party code in PHP projects has not been a trivial task. Fortunately, the PHP community now has Composer, a top-notch dependency manager. Learn what Composer is and how you can put it to work for fun and profit. You will see how to set up a new project, find packages, as well as how to create and distribute your own packages.','tutorial','handson','phpfuture',0,'','I\'d like to give this talk as a workshop and do a real deep dive on Composer. I\'ve found that there are a lot of topics people are interested in that just cannot be covered in a 1 hour talk.\n\nExamples include custom repositories, private repositories, self-hosted Packagist, and Satis repositories.\n\nI have a bunch of existing material to work from. My very first high-level generic Composer talk actually ran about an hour and a half at user groups despite testing out closer to 50 minutes. This was mostly due to the huge amount of questions I generally receive will giving Composer related talks.\n\nhttps://beau.io/talks/2014/04/25/managing-dependencies-with-composer-lone-star-php-2014/\nhttps://beau.io/talks/2014/05/22/composer-stability-and-semantic-versioning-demystified-php-tek-2014/\nhttps://beau.io/talks/2013/05/23/embedded-composer-sflive-portland-2013/',0,0,0,'2014-09-25 01:08:40','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(166,77,'Managing Dependencies with Composer','Traditionally, managing third-party code in PHP projects has not been a trivial task. Fortunately, the PHP community now has Composer, a top-notch dependency manager. Learn what Composer is and how you can put it to work for fun and profit. You will see how to set up a new project, find packages, as well as how to create and distribute your own packages.','regular','overview','phpfuture',0,'https://beau.io/talks/2014/04/25/managing-dependencies-with-composer-lone-star-php-2014/','Basic introduction to Composer usage along with a healthy dose of autoloading (PSR-0 and PSR-4) and semantic versioning.\n\nThis is a more broad look at Composer as opposed to the \"Stability and Semantic Versioning Demystified\" talk which is more advanced.\n\nI\'ve presented variations on this topic a few times at local user groups and several conferences over the last year. It has evolved quite a bit over that time. Most recently it was presented at Lone Star PHP in Dallas.\n\nhttps://beau.io/talks/2014/04/25/managing-dependencies-with-composer-lone-star-php-2014/\n\nI am also submitting this talk as a workshop.',0,0,0,'2014-09-25 01:09:23','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(167,78,'Programmer\'s introduction to CoreOS','CoreOS is a new Linux distribution for Massive Server Deployments. Essentially it gives you three tools: service discovery (etcd), container management (Docker) and process management (fleet). This tutorial is an introduction to CoreOS from programmer\'s perspective: it will help you decide whether CoreOS is the right platform for your next project.\n\nDistributed systems are a lot of fun to build, but they are challenging to build too. And they become even more demanding when it comes to cluster management (adding/removing nodes, running configuration on some or all nodes etc).\n\nIn CoreOS, we finally have a linux distribution that is, from the very beginning, architected with massive deployments in mind. It doesn\'t provide many tools, it is limited by design. But it provides just enough tools to build highly scalable distributed systems that are also easy to manage and maintain.\n\nMassive deployments wouldn\'t be that easy if not for the OS-level virtualization, in form of isolated containers. And with an amazing Docker tool, container management is almost trivial (and lots of examples will be provided to support this argument).\n\nIn any distributed system, node communication is essential and quite cumbersome to implement. CoreOS team comes up with their own implementation of a highly-available key/value store - etcd. Again, this tutorial session will provide lots of examples on how to use it.\n\nFinally, to manage the lifecycle of Docker containers, another tool was introduced - fleet. While this tool is relatively low-level, it is still very handy for your cluster management and you will see why.\n\nTo sum up, this talk will provide enough examples to make an informed decision whether CoreOS (as a platform) is good choice for your next software project. Additionally, expect a hands-on approach which should be quite engaging and geared towards practical understanding of all concepts covered.','tutorial','handson','virtualization',0,'','Outline:\n\n- Introduction to CoreOS\n    - Goals\n    - Architecture\n    - Problems Solved\n- OS-Level virtualization\n    - Brief overview of the Linux containers\n    - Introduction to Docker\n- Shared Configuration and Service Discovery\n    - Goals and Requirements\n    - Introduction to etcd\n    - Alternatives?\n- Distributed init system\n    - Goals and Requirements\n    - Introduction to fleet\n- Putting it all together',0,0,0,'2014-09-25 11:27:26','2014-09-25 11:28:42'),(168,78,'Low-ceremony introduction to OS-level Virtualization','Docker makes OS-level virtualization easy, almost trivial. However, almost all new adopters fall into the very same traps, not grasping Docker containers correctly. The reason is that developers are generally not aware of what\'s going on under the hood.\n\nInvestigating the internals of the Linux Containers is not only of academic interest. With a tool such as Docker, understanding the internals means better comprehension of where and how this tool can be applied, and where it does not suit well.\n\nThis talk will not re-iterate over the Docker manual (Docker team have done fantastic job already). Instead, we will try to grasp the lower level abstractions and mechanisms used.','regular','indepth','virtualization',0,'','**Outline:**\n- Introduction to Linux Containers\n    - namespaces\n    - cgroups\n- Introduction to Docker\n    - Architecture\n    - Images\n    - Containers\n- Summary \n\n**Notes:**\nVirtualization, being one of my primary research interests, is often only vaguely understood by software engineering practitioners. And while experienced architects will find nothing novel in this talk, I believe for the beginners it might serve a good starting point (to virtualization, message based distributed systems etc).',0,0,0,'2014-09-25 11:32:50','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(169,78,'How to build your own Distributed CI System','Things to expect from the talk:\nâ€¢ light-weight (I mean it!) introduction to OS-level virtualization\nâ€¢ short review of the conventional toolbox for building distributed systems (CoreOS, Docker, etcd, ansible)\nâ€¢ practical notes on how to build highly scalable distributed CI system\nâ€¢ case study (PHP and Python projects unit testing)\nâ€¢ working source code of everything we will cover (for those who want to dive deeper after the talk)','regular','overview','virtualization',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-25 11:35:19','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(170,78,'RESTful API using Symfony2','REST is a solid style with enormous success in recent years. This talk will not introduce you to the RESTful design principles (assuming you know them pretty well, which you should, unless you\'ve been absent from web-dev for the last 10 years).\n\n What this talk will provide you though is the following:\n- complete guide dealing with all the necessary bundles/components that one needs to build/test/document/deliver an API\n- working sandbox endpoint for experiments from the client side\n- fully working code samples to get you started with backend part\n- this is a tutorial session, if you come - expect to produce some code! Don\'t worry, boilerplate code will be provided.\n\nExpected outcome:\n- solid understanding of the capabilities that Symfony2 provides you with, when it comes to RESTful APIs\n- good comprehension of framework-agnostic principles that should guide you throughout API development process','tutorial','handson','other',0,'','I\'ve presented similar tutorial on Dutch PHP Conference this year (http://goo.gl/sIZPYl). In this tutorial, however, I want to concentrate on server side particulars, providing sample AngularJS frontend for the illustration purposes only.',0,0,0,'2014-09-25 11:50:44','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(171,36,'Using feature toggles with Qandidate\\Toggle','In an agile development environment, there is often the need to release quick and often. With feature toggles you can release features that arenâ€™t yet ready, but toggled off for regular users. Using Qandidate\\Toggle Iâ€™ll show how feature toggles can be used, how you can create toggles that are conditionally active and how we update toggles during runtime.\n\nQandidate\\Toggle: https://github.com/qandidate-labs/qandidate-toggle','regular','overview','continuousdelivery',0,'','It\'s a new talk, but we noticed on our blog [1] that a lot of people are interested in the subject. So it seemed appropriate to introduce more people to the subject and help them get started.\n\n[1]: http://labs.qandidate.com/blog/2014/08/18/a-new-feature-toggling-library-for-php/',0,0,0,'2014-09-25 19:42:49','2014-09-25 20:04:06'),(172,79,'mysqlnd, an unknown powerful extension','Some of you may have heard about mysqlnd. I personnally gave it a try and stepped deep into its heart. Here, I\'ll show you what mysqlnd can do for you, mainly how it can powerfuly decrease memory consumption when retrieving datasets, how it can hint you about wrong but working queries from PHP side, and how you can plug in additionnal code to turn this extension to an even more useful tool.','regular','handson','crossingphp',0,'','',1,0,0,'2014-09-26 10:29:52','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(173,79,'Hands on PHP objects','This talk will show you how PHP manages objects internally.\nObjects have been designed in PHP5 in a very flexible manner.\nYou will understand how the engine tracks your objects, creates them as you ask, keeps them in memory and destroys them.\nHow memory heavy are your objects? What are the best practices when it comes to objects management in PHP?\nWhat is the garbage collector, how does it work and what does it do for me?\nMaster PHP objects!','regular','indepth','crossingphp',0,'','',1,0,0,'2014-09-26 10:30:41','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(174,79,'Woops, I found a bug in PHP !','You think you found a bug in PHP? This talk is for you. We will here detail how to make a useful report of PHP bug.\nFirst of all, confirm this is really a bug and how to look for bugs to check if it\'s not already reported or fixed.\nThen, we are now sure we got one, how to get useful info for developers to fix it,\nthis will need you to compile PHP, add debug flags, isolate the bug, generate a stack trace and perhaps more.\nAll those points will then be treated in the talk, no more excuse when dealing with PHP bugs !','regular','handson','phpfuture',0,'','',1,0,0,'2014-09-26 10:31:09','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(175,79,'PHP 5.6, Wow !','Heyy, PHP 5.6 is released !\nWhat about taking a tour of what\'s new in this release and why you should upgrade ?\nThis talk will show you the new features in the language and the internal changes which can lead to little compatibility breaks and performance improvements.\nWe\'ll remind you as well with the PHP release process and try to foresee the future, and PHP7.','regular','overview','phpfuture',0,'','',1,0,0,'2014-09-26 10:35:27','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(176,79,'Let\'s have a look at PHP\'s engine','PHP is a complex C-written machine that has to run fast, efficiently, with no bug, safely, and across many platforms. These are so big challenges when put together. Here, I suggest we dive into PHP source code to show you how things works. How does the engine start, load extensions, load INI files, deals with OS it runs on... to how it understands some developer\'s script and sends an HTTP response.','regular','indepth','crossingphp',0,'','',1,0,0,'2014-09-26 10:36:05','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(177,80,'Mistake Driven Development','Most developers make mistakes, but when we do we tend to hide from them. At the time mistakes can be tough to take, can cause real worry and most of the time embarrassing.\nSadly for us making mistakes is part of being human, but the key is not making the mistake but admitting it and using it to learn and improve.\n\nAs developers we should be more open to admitting our mistakes. We should be looking to learn from them rather than hide them.\n\nSo to start the ball rolling I would like to share with you some mistakes I have made while developing with Magento.\nThe aim of this session is to highlight some general development best practices that will help make you an even better developer.\nBut while we do this we can look back and laugh at some mistakes I have made while learning to work with Magento.','regular','overview','devlife',0,'https://github.com/dmanners/Mistake_Driven_Development','I have performed this talk at Meet Magento Romania and Switzerland as well as the PHP Unconference and local user groups',0,0,0,'2014-09-26 11:02:47','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(178,80,'I don\'t want to work, I just want to live!','A developer can lead a stressful and lonely life sometimes or at least that is how it feels.\nOver the past years I have worked on improving my quality of life, avoid burnout but still making great software.\nI would like to present my story as an example to highlight the differences between stress and burnout and some ideas on how to avoid it.\n\nMy aim is to inspire developers to a better quality of life and code.','regular','overview','devlife',1,'https://github.com/dmanners/avoiding-burnout','This is a small talk for around 20/30 mins that gives an overview of my experience with stress and burnout. It then progresses into an open discussion that at the php unconference has to be cut off and moved to an external room so that the other talk could start. It is a very open and personal talk.',0,0,0,'2014-09-26 11:06:24','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(179,81,'Going crazy with Symfony2 and Varnish','You know how HTTP caching works but need more? In this talk we look into ways to cache personalized content. We will look at Edge Side Includes (ESI) to tailor caching rules of fragments, and at the user context concept to differentiate caches not by individual user but by groups.','regular','indepth','phpfuture',0,'http://davidbu.ch/slides/20140913-madison-varnish.html#45','This is the \"other half\" of my varnish talks that i never get time to present when doing all the basic things first. This is assuming basic knowledge of Varnish and Symfony.',0,0,0,'2014-09-26 16:05:21','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(180,81,'HTTP caching with Varnish','For some scenarios, Varnish is the silver bullet to fix performance issues and go from slow site to lightning fast site. More often though, you will need to put some effort into your application to get good results. Ideally, you design your application to play well with caching from the outset. If you don\'t know what you are doing, Varnish can also be the bullet to shoot yourself in the foot.\nVarnish is a server component that runs independent from your web server, making it useful whether your application is written in PHP, node.js, Java or any other language.\nIn this workshop, you will learn how to use HTTP headers to control caching and how to configure Varnish itself. Running your own vagrantbox with Varnish and PHP, you get to try out the effects of the caching headers and of Varnish configuration directives. We will discuss things that go well with Varnish and situations to avoid. After mastering the basics, we look at advanced concepts like edge side includes (ESI).\nWith this knowledge, you will be able to set up and configure Varnish. You know how to build applications with caching in mind, and can assess whether an application is ready for Varnish or what needs to be fixed.','tutorial','handson','crossingphp',0,'','I did a presentation about Varnish at user groups and then at Madison PHP in september 2014: https://joind.in/talk/view/11751\nI did this workshop internally at Liip, with success but learning a couple of things that I would improve for Miami.\n\nI could alternatively do this as a regular presentation if you prefer. Or even both, but that will be overlapping for those at the workshop.',0,0,0,'2014-09-26 16:08:14','2014-09-26 16:08:25'),(181,81,'Independent components instead of monolithic framework','Symfony2 is not only a full stack framework, but also a collection of components. Thanks to dependency injection and careful design, you can use single components in your non-symfony projects to solve specific tasks.\nI will discuss the basic design concepts and  then look more specifically at the Symfony2 console component for a real world example.','regular','indepth','phpfuture',0,'','I did this presentation at an internal event at Liip, but have no public slides available. This talk is about dependency injection and software design, on the example of the symfony console component.',0,0,0,'2014-09-26 16:09:11','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(182,81,'Introduction to the Symfony2 ecosystem','Symfony2 is a powerful and very flexible framework to build web applications. Symfony2 is also a collection of base components that you can use in any project. This modular nature allowed many frameworks to build on top of it, most notable Drupal 8 and Laravel. In this talk, I will give an overview of the fundamental Symfony2 components and show how to use the full stack framework.','regular','overview','phpfuture',1,'http://davidbu.ch/slides/20140827-dcphp-symfony-intro.html','I did other Symfony introductions, one at sunshine 2013. In this current form, i gave the talk at a Washington php usergroup meeting: \nhttp://davidbu.ch/mann/blog/2014-08-27/dcphp-washington-introduction-symfony2-ecosystem.html\n\nThis talk is very interesting for all that care about Drupal 8 which introduces Symfony components into Drupal, as well as Laravel developers that want to see some input about the Symfony base of their framework.',0,0,0,'2014-09-26 16:10:27','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(183,81,'PHP Content Repository: Porting a Java standard to PHP','PHPCR is an API for hierarchical data, handling both structured and unstructured content. It provides APIs for permission management, versioning, locking, search with an SQL-like syntax. Several major frameworks and CMS (Typo3, Drupal, Symfony2, Nooku und eZ publish) discuss whether to use it as common standard for storing their data.\nPHPCR is a port of the Java standard JCR. One PHPCR implementation allows you to talk to the Java CMSes Adobe Experience Manager and Magnolia.\nAfter this talk, you will know what PHPCR can be used for, understand the model and have seen some concrete examples.','regular','overview','crossingphp',0,'http://davidbu.ch/slides/20131018-codemotion-phpcr.html','https://joind.in/talk/view/8522 (comments in french, sorry. the slides are english though)\n\nI am active contributor to both the PHPCR standard and the Jackalope implementation.',0,0,0,'2014-09-26 16:12:57','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(184,81,'Open source projects with git','This talk is all about git and Open Source: Working with git, how to contribute to projects and how to handle your own open source projects. We will talk about git branching concepts, pull requests, release management and free (for open source projects) automated integration testing. I will explain best practices we developped in the Symfony CMF and the PHPCR projects and for our company\'s customer projects.','regular','overview','vcs',0,'','I accumulated quite some knowledge and experience about this topic over the last years. Rather than explaining \"git commit\" and \"git push\", i want to take one step back and look at workflows and how to make things work. There will still be interesting git examples in the talk like the squashing commits before merging.\nThis would be a new talk i did not present at other conferences, hence no slides. However, I promise to test-run the talk at Liip or with a user group before the phpbenelux conference.',0,0,0,'2014-09-26 16:16:54','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(185,83,'Container Coding','Do you have to spend hours wrapping your head around your entire application before you can make simple changes to one part? Is each layer too reliant on other layers so each change is a major revision? You need container coding. Learn to segregate each layer of your code so you can deal with each individually. Your code will be flexible, easy to maintain, and ready for new features.','regular','overview','phpfuture',0,'','This talk was well-received at Lake / Kenosha PHP, previously titled \"Get your Domain Logic Out of Storage!\" See http://www.lakekenoshaphp.com/events/58010282/ and http://joind.in/talk/view/6364 for feedback.',0,0,0,'2014-09-26 23:45:44','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(186,83,'Code Reviews: The \"Secret\" to Building Quality Software','Even the best of us can overlook things and make the occasional mistake, but a mistake that makes it to production means no sleep, unhappy customers, and lost revenue. Code reviews minimize this risk and keep you sleeping soundly.  Having QA review your code helps, but your developers know the code best. You also avoid having a single point of failure by ensuring that there are always two developers who thoroughly understand each update. Learn how to incorporate peer reviews and testing into your workflow, making big improvements in code quality without derailing your team\'s velocity.','regular','overview','phpfuture',0,'https://github.com/PSchwisow/Miscellaneous/blob/master/CodeReviews-MidwestPHP.pdf?raw=true','I gave this talk at Lake / Kenosha PHP in January 2013 (http://www.meetup.com/Lake-Kenosha-PHP-Users-Group/events/97472012/), php[tek] 2013 (https://joind.in/talk/view/8160), Madison PHP in July 2013 (http://www.meetup.com/madisonphp/events/125686792/), and MidwestPHP in March 2014 (http://joind.in/talk/view/10546). I am planning a major revamp of the presentation, but the content will be much the same.',0,0,0,'2014-09-26 23:47:23','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(187,83,'DO ALL THE THINGS!!!','Once you\'ve been around for a while, people (hopefully) start to look up to you, and you may find yourself bestowed with the coveted title of \"Senior\". All is well with the world, until your team leader takes a position elsewhere, and you\'re asked to cover some of his duties. Before you realize it, you\'re planning projects, running the day-to-day operations of the team, answering all the questions, and still trying to produce quality code at the same pace as before. It\'s tough enough to transition from developer to manager in an ideal situation, but being stuck somewhere in the middle has a whole additional set of challenges. I\'ll discuss these challenges and how to successfully handle them until everything settles out (whether that means you move to management or go back to the code).','regular','overview','devlife',0,'https://github.com/PSchwisow/Miscellaneous/blob/master/DoAllTheThings-tek13.pdf?raw=true','The topic was inspired by a short blog post \"Lead Scrumveloper\" by Chris Cornutt (on the now defunct \"The Accidental Scrummaster\" blog), but focuses more on my own experiences. I asked Chris before co-opting his idea, and he OK\'ed it. I gave this talk at php[tek] 2013 (https://joind.in/talk/view/8161).',0,0,0,'2014-09-26 23:51:19','2014-09-26 23:52:44'),(188,83,'Managing Developers','Taking on managerial responsibilities is more than just a title change, it\'s a change in mindset. Your job is no longer focused on what *you* can do, but rather what *your team* can do. Being an effective manager is about giving your team the tools and information needed to succeed; helping them find the right path, and clearing obstacles out of their way. Discover the fundamental tools and essential resources that will help you lead your team down the path to success.','regular','overview','devlife',0,'','The talk is for managers, those who aspire to become managers, and anyone who just want to better understand how management works. It aims to continue where \"DO ALL THE THINGS!!!\" (see https://joind.in/talk/view/8161) leaves off, but works just as well as a standalone talk.',0,0,0,'2014-09-26 23:52:25','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(189,83,'Migrating from Developer to Manager','We are developers, yet many of us have management on our plates as well (or would like to). Being an effective leader isnâ€™t something that happens overnight. Learn the tricks to make the road to leadership a smooth one, like project management, estimation, communication, one-on-ones, feedback, and empowering your developers.','tutorial','overview','devlife',0,'','This is a tutorial version of \"DO ALL THE THINGS!!!\" and \"Managing Developers\".',0,0,0,'2014-09-26 23:53:45','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(190,83,'Git Yourself Off Subversion','Creating a Git repository for your new project is really simple. Migrating an existing project while its under active development is something else entirely. There are many things to consider: How much history do you want to keep? How will you keep continuous integration / continuous deployment working? How will you deal with features that do not work the same in Git (e.g. SVN externals)? Do you want to make changes to your workflow / branching model during the transition? I\'ll discuss these questions and offer solutions for many different scenarios, so you\'re ready to take the plunge and free yourself from Subversion once and for all.','regular','overview','vcs',0,'','This not an intro to git. It is about migrating an existing project.',0,0,0,'2014-09-26 23:56:31','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(191,83,'Achieving High-Quality Code Standards','We all want want high-quality code. Standards keep things consistent and make it easier to identify potential problems, but if you want high-quality code, you need high-quality standards. Learn what standards are available and how you can enforce them from coding practices through documentation. We\'ll dive into PHP-FIG\'s PSRs as well as other popular coding standards and investigate how PHP_CodeSniffer can easily automate enforcement to make standards compliance easy to achieve. We\'ll even cover docblocks so you can create functional documentation of classes and methods using phpDocumentor. This talk will prepare you to write clean, consistent code so you can easily navigate and share between developers.','regular','overview','phpfuture',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-26 23:57:52','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(192,83,'Achieving High-Quality Code Standards','We all want want high-quality code. Standards keep things consistent and make it easier to identify potential problems, but if you want high-quality code, you need high-quality standards. Learn what standards are available and how you can enforce them from coding practices through documentation. We\'ll dive into PHP-FIG\'s PSRs as well as other popular coding standards and cover the use of docblocks to document individual classes and methods. Hands-on examples will include automating standards checking / enforcement with PHP_CodeSniffer and generating documentation with phpDocumentor. This talk will teach how you to write clean, consistent code and automate checking and enforcement of standards.','tutorial','handson','phpfuture',0,'','This is a tutorial version of the talk of the same title.',0,0,0,'2014-09-26 23:58:52','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(193,84,'Machine Learning : Or how to build SkyNet on your lunch break.','In this talk we\'ll learn about the wonderful world of Machine Learning and how we can bend it to our will to tackle common problems that we face in our applications.\n\nWe\'ll start with a quick primer on what even is Machine Learning. We\'ll learn about its different types, and the situations that suit them. We\'ll cover some history, and be introduced to the Grandfather of all Hipsters, Carl Friedrich Gauss.\n\nOnce we know what it is, and where it came from, we can look at the kinds of problems that it can be used to solve and the tools available to help us use machine learning to conquer the world.','regular','overview','architectures',1,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-27 04:44:48','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(194,84,'The Code Manifesto: Empowering Our Community','The Code Manifesto is a set of values, created in hopes of guiding our community towards a place that is welcoming, safe, and empowering to all.\n\nCurrently, our communities are greatly lacking in diversity, and sometimes outright hostile towards the minority members that we do have. In this talk I try to illustrate that problem, and also cover WHY it matters, and finally what we can do to help fix it.\n\nI talk about what the Code Manifesto is, why it came to be, and why each of the values were selected.','regular','overview','devlife',0,'https://speakerdeck.com/kayladnls/the-code-manifesto-empowering-our-community','Joind.in: https://joind.in/talk/view/11695\n\nvideo: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mS0dW2ux3qo',0,0,0,'2014-09-27 04:46:46','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(195,64,'PHP Performance Tuning: Prepare for Ludicrous Speed!','There\'s a saying \"hardware is cheaper than developers\", but this only holds true if you treat your hardware with the respect it deserves. \n\nLearn how to diagnose, confirm and fix bottlenecks in your application using XHProf and Xhgui. \n\nAfter an in-depth look at how to use these tools, we\'ll take a practical look at actually using them to achieve measurable (~20%) performance improvements in a popular open source project.','regular','indepth','other',0,'','This is a successor of a talk I gave in 2012, which rated very well:\n\n- DPC: http://joind.in/talk/view/6243\n- Lonestar: http://joind.in/talk/view/6349\n\nYou can see the slides here: https://speakerdeck.com/dshafik/dpc-fast-not-furious-how-to-identify-and-fix-slow-code\n\nChanges include updating to use the entirely re-written xhgui, which will be covered in-depth and will be completed by walking people through a practical example of actual performance tuning (~20% performance increase in Wordpress, which will be included in WP 4.1).       \n\nThis time I have cut out the additional memcache/apc stuff (everything from slide 29 \"Caching\" on), and it\'s now a much more focused talk.',0,0,0,'2014-09-27 06:10:21','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(196,64,'Building for the Cloud','While a lot of people canâ€™t even tell us what the cloud is, most of us are already using it in some way â€” but are we using it effectively?\n\nTo get the most benefit from the cloud, cost-savings, durability and performance, we must write for the cloud. The cloud is not just a cheap drop-in replacement for physical hardware â€” itâ€™s a whole different set of tools we can â€” and should â€” use more effectively.\n\nThis talk will look at a number of different scenarios and how we should re-think them for the cloud. Auto-scaling. Geographic Distribution. Disaster Recovery. Learn how the cloud can make all of these easy.','regular','overview','other',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-27 06:13:52','2014-09-27 06:14:35'),(197,85,'Zephir: A Wind of Change for writing PHP extensions','The last year or so has seen a lot of buzz about some major changes in the PHP world, with new runtimes like Facebook\'s HHVM and the new Hack language, JPHP, PH7 or HippyVM, and Zend\'s own response to these \"challenges\" with PHPng; or tools like PHPQB for improved performance and memory when working with images. But few of us have the opportunity to use any of these when our hosting gives up access to a basic LAMP stack.\n\nOne alternative that we might be able to implement on our stack is to write our own PHP extensions, which can help improve performance and/or reduce the memory overheads of our scripts. But there\'s little documentation available to help us if we choose to take this approach, and it\'s easy to consider this option impractical when looking at the C code for the existing PHP extensions... it just looks so damned scarey.\n\nYet there are tools to help simplify this task: tools like Zephir (from the developers of the Phalcon framework) that make it easier to write our own PHP extensions based on our own PHP classes while keeping the complexity of that C code at arms length. So how can we use Zephir to convert our existing PHP classes to a PHP extension? And what benefits can we expect to see if we do so?','regular','overview','phpfuture',0,'','Talks on building Extensions for PHP are always popular at conferences, but few developers ever actually take the plunge and write their own extensions: for many, looking at the underlying C code of existing extensions is a powerful deterrent. Yet it isn\'t as complicated as that initial view might suggest, especially when there are helpers available to simplify the task.\n\nZephir is a relatively new Open Source project from the developers of the Phalcon CMS, that makes the task of writing your own extensions based on existing PHP classes easy. It provides a hybrid domain-specific language partway between PHP and C that hides the obscure intricacies and structure of the extension code itself, while retaining much of the original PHP code.\n\nThis talk provides a short overview of Zephir, together with a demonstration of how to take an existing PHP library and convert it to a PHP extension using Zephir; and demonstrates the performance and memory benefits of doing so.',0,0,0,'2014-09-27 13:25:07','2014-09-28 23:30:00'),(198,85,'You don\'t need to be a Ninja Rockstar to contribute to Open Source','Many developers assume that you need to be a great code ninja to contribute to open source projects, but that isn\'t the case. The people who develop those open source tools, libraries and frameworks that we use for our own work aren\'t all uberhackers; but are often simply individuals or small groups of volunteers, working on the projects in their own time, and who need all the help they can get.\n\nAnd many companies believe that contributing to open source has no benefits, or even that it\'s giving away their trade secrets; but there are benefits for companies that do make contributions to Open Source projects, and it doesn\'t result in giving away a competitive edge, but may even result in improving their business where it matters to them - on the bottom line.\n \nSo why should you or your company bother to participate in an open source project? How do you contribute your code if you want to do so? And even if you don\'t believe that you can contribute code, there are plenty of other ways that you can help a community to improve their project that are just as valuable.','regular','overview','other',0,'http://www.slideshare.net/MarkBakerUK/open-source-contributions','So many developers claim to support the ideals of Open Source, but so few ever actually take the final steps to actually contributing to Open Source projects. This talk is an attempt to persuade more developers to become active participants in the open source community; and (even if they don\'t contribute code) to show how they can help projects in other ways that are just as important.',0,0,0,'2014-09-27 13:26:53','2014-10-01 23:06:57'),(199,85,'SPL: PHP\'s Forgotten Library','The Standard PHP Library (SPL) has been an option in PHP since version 5.0.0 and always available since 5.3.0, yet few developers seem aware of the powerful features that it offers. From a comprehensive set of iterators and powerful classes, interfaces and abstracts that seem complicated, but are surprisingly easy to use; through a hierarchy of exceptions; and datastructures like heaps, stacks, queues and linked lists; to file handling classes; to the Observer design pattern: the SPL has something to offer that can simplify your code, improve its performance and reduce its memory usage. Despite its wide and varied uses, SPL has been largely forgotten: but now it\'s time that developers learned the powerful toolset that\'s available to simplify their work.','regular','overview','other',0,'http://www.slideshare.net/MarkBakerUK/spl-datastructures-24333471','The SPL provides a powerful and flexible toolset: yet few developers even seem aware of its existence, or of how they can use it to simplify their work and improve the quality of their code. It\'s time that changed; and SPL should take its place among the standard features of PHP that we use on a daily basis. This talk is aimed at reminding people that SPL provides real solutions to daily problems, and that it isn\'t simply an esoteric collection of tools that only belong in a Computer Science theory classroom.',0,0,0,'2014-09-27 13:28:41','2014-09-28 23:30:14'),(200,73,'Introduction to search servers with Sphinx','Developers fear the day when database will grow to the point that full text search brings server to its knees. Their life would be happier if there was no search field in application. But management insists on it, clients depend on it and search is here to stay. Upgrading the server is a quick fix and it will buy you just enough time to bring your laptop to a workshop and learn how to build a search that works and performs.\n\nSphinx search server packs a lot of features so letâ€™s learn how to install it, configure it and use it in our projects. Iâ€™ll try to keep it as framework independent as possible so you will be able to go home and start implementing it in your project right away. Also, you will learn some search lingo so if youâ€™ll ever need to change to different search technology you will feel right at home.','tutorial','handson','architectures',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-27 17:18:16','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(201,35,'Debugging: The Art of WHY?! WHY DOES MY CODE WORK?WHY?! WHY DOES MY CODE WORK?','A debugger\'s lament: Dear computer, do as I want, not as I say. It turns out that computers do not care about what you want, they will do precisely as instructed. And that allows bugs to creep into our programs.\n\nAs a result, a lot of our time is spent on debugging. Usually this means finding out why something does not work, sometimes it means finding out why something works when it should not! I want to share some strategies, tools and a mindset necessary to effectively debug problems. In particular, you will learn how systems tools like strace, nc, ping, dig and tail can help understand what your code is doing.','regular','indepth','devlife',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-28 16:54:07','2014-09-30 10:08:11'),(202,86,'From Vagrant to Production','You heard all these great stories of people using tools like Vagrant, Puppet, Composer and Phing. Each of these tools can massively improve your development workflow. But how to combine them to get the best out of it? This session will guide you through the process of setting up the toolchain to build the \"perfect development stack\"(tm).','regular','indepth','continuousdelivery',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-28 19:36:10','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(203,86,'Composer for corporate use','It may seem that Composer only makes sense if you open-source your packages. But Composer and it`s ecosystem can be easily set-up in your corporation for internal use. Let me give you some ideas how to set-up and use Composer, Satis and Jenkins to run your own internal package repository.','regular','overview','devlife',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-28 19:36:22','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(204,86,'Microservices: Packs small, plays BIG!','Microservices based architectures look very promising. But what exactly are microservices? Is it just SOA as it was intended to be or maybe something completely different? With this session I`d like to discuss the benefits and trade-offs of an microservices based architecture and give you some insights on why it can make sense to create simple, isolated and collaborating services.','regular','overview','architectures',1,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-28 19:36:32','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(205,88,'PHP Challenges on PaaS','PaaS is the next big cloud revolution and a lot of companies (Pivotal, IBM, AT&amp;T, etc.) are heavily investing in solutions to bring these automated and scalable environments to the public.\nWhile PaaS removes a lot of the headaches a developer has, it brings a lot of new challenges to the way we develop our applications.\n\nI would like to use my experience with different cloud solutions and vendors, from the last 5 years and my active involvement with integrating Zend\'s products for different cloud providers, including several PaaS providers, and show the challenges and solutions for common issues developers will run into while developing for PaaS.','regular','overview','virtualization',1,'https://dl.dropboxusercontent.com/u/11893433/PHP%20Challenge%20on%20PaaS.pdf','- Slides are only initial version that was used in an IBM event and for reference only. *This is not the final deck for this conference*.\n- The session will include some live demos on IBM Bluemix (or other PaaS) running Wordpress to present some hands on examples for some of the suggest solutions.',0,0,0,'2014-09-29 14:02:59','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(206,72,'Asynchronous processing in PHP applications','In this talk I want to show the basics of synchronous and asynchronous communication using a job queue like beanstalkd.\nI will show you how to offload time consuming tasks and how to spread heavy work onto multiple workers.\nThis will result in better scalability for your application and better user experience for you customers.','regular','overview','architectures',1,'http://pub.benjamin-cremer.de/scd2014/','',1,0,0,'2014-09-29 15:52:56','2014-09-29 16:12:19'),(207,89,'Writing testable code. A functional programming point of view','We\'ve been told many times that we should write unit tests for our code. We have read the theory and we have applied automatic testing to our projects, sometimes successfully but often times not so.\n\nWhy it seems to be so hard to test our code? However we look at it, automatic testing doesn\'t work like a \"plug &amp; play\" peripheral. It just doesn\'t seem to fit with our project. A dependency is missing here; we have a hard to mock object there; and so on. \n\nWhat is _that_ thing we might be doing wrong but we fail to notice?\n\nIn this talk we will argue that the problem lays in our code, in its structure, in the way we pass data around and even how we write for loops!\n\nThis won\'t be your everyday \"code quality\" tech talk, since we are going to attack the problem of code quality from different points of view and paradigms like Functional Programming and the Unix philosophy of simplicity and reuse.','regular','overview','testing',0,'http://www.slideshare.net/old_sound/writing-testable-code2014','',0,0,0,'2014-09-29 16:15:56','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(208,89,'Scaling Applications with RabbitMQ','Do you need to process thousands of images in the background for your web app? \n\nDo you need to share data across multiple applications, probably written in different languages and sitting at different servers? \n\nYour real time data feed is becoming slow because you are polling the database constantly for new data updates? \n\nDo you need to scale information processing during peek times? \n\nWhat about deploying new features with zero downtime? If any of these problems sound familiar then you probably need to use messaging in your application.\n\nIn this talk I will introduce RabbitMQ, a messaging and queue server that can help us tackle those problems. We will learn the benefits of a Queue Server and see how to integrate messaging into our applications. With this talk we hope that the term \'decoupling\' gets a new, broader, meaning.','regular','overview','architectures',0,'http://www.slideshare.net/old_sound/scaling-applications-with-rabbitmq-at-sunshinephp','',0,0,0,'2014-09-29 16:18:42','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(209,89,'Building a Distributed Data Ingestion System with RabbitMQ','Your company has servers distributed around the world and you need to process data in a centralised location. The data is produced by applications using different technology stacks and comes from various sources, from web servers to sensors. How could you solve this problem? Enter RabbitMQ.\n\nIn this talk we are going to show how to build a system that can ingest data produced at separate geo located areas (think AWS and it\'s many regions) and replicate it to a central cluster where it can be further processed and analysed.\n\nWe will present an example of how to build a system like this one by using RabbitMQ Federation to replicate data across AWS Regions and RabbitMQ support for many protocols to produce/consume data.\n\nTo help with scalability we are going to show an interesting way to implement sharded queues with RabbitMQ by using the Consistent Hash Exchange.\n\nIf you want to learn what else has RabbitMQ to offer beyond simple messaging and queueing, then this is the talk for you.','regular','overview','phpfuture',0,'http://www.slideshare.net/old_sound/rabbitmq-data-ingestion-at-craft-conf','',0,0,0,'2014-09-29 16:19:37','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(210,52,'Inclusiveness: Empowering the PHP people','The PHP community is awesome, we are a group of people who all have fun and learn together. We share a passion and a common ground. But letâ€™s face it, we are not very diverse. I want to make this better. In this talk I will share my beliefs in how we as a community can empower everyone. Whether youâ€™re white, black or green, woman man or in between.','regular','overview','other',0,'','As a president of PHPWomen this is a topic very hot to me, I have been avoiding it thus far but I think it\'s important for everyone to know that inclusiveness makes us awesome &lt;3',0,0,0,'2014-09-29 23:17:13','2014-09-29 23:27:08'),(211,52,'Behat+Mink+PhantomJS = Test ALL THE THINGS!','Sometimes simple unit testing is not enough. There is more to it than that when you want to test JavaScript and the rendering of your page. In this talk I will show you how you can use Behat+Mink+PhantomJS to accomplish screenshot comparison, test your JavaScript implementations and your PHP code using the same human-readable language: Behatâ€™s Gherkin.','regular','overview','testing',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-29 23:28:41','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(212,52,'Pretty search results with schema.org','Ever googled a movie and saw super cool results from IMDB? Or wondered why people make their search results look so cool while yours look so boring. You don\'t have to wonder no more, let me show you the world of schema.org and make your search results pretty too.','regular','overview','other',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-29 23:51:40','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(213,52,'Accessibility done right','Unfortunately accessibility is often an afterthought. Some users canâ€™t use a mouse, others are visually impaired. In this talk I will show you how to test accessibility and how to browse your site blindfolded or with only a keyboard and still get around using things like headers and aria labels.','regular','overview','other',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-30 00:06:25','2014-09-30 00:07:05'),(214,57,'Build Your Own Dependency Injection Container','Dependency Injection is a hot topic in PHP at the moment, and more and more of the popular frameworks are using a dependency injection container to manager the creation and storage of objects. A DIC can be a great way of managing the various complex dependencies, but the internals can seem complicated and scary.\n\nIn this session we will build our own DIC from scratch as a way of fully understanding both the patterns and code involved in creating a container for managing your class instances. We\'ll get to understand why the Dependency Injection pattern is a Good Thing, and learn about the challenges in defining dependencies and creating services with factories. Building your own container will help you understand how the DIC in the current crop of frameworks are put together.\n\nBy the end of the session we\'ll have a fully working DIC that you should never use in your own projects!','tutorial','handson','other',1,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-30 09:14:03','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(215,92,'Public Speaking for Developers','You know that to advance your career, getting into the world of conference and user group speaking is important. Yet, most people will rate their fear of speaking to groups higher than their fear of death. How can you break into the speaking world, overcome your fears, and learn how to deliver an effective presentation? Come find out the strategies for crafting, creating and delivering an effective talk on a technical topic, followed by an opportunity to practice those skills in front of your tutorial class! Put your fears of public speaking to rest, and learn how the pros do it well each and every time.','tutorial','handson','other',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-30 15:40:13','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(216,92,'Free Agent: Creating A Profitable Business For Yourself','The dream of tossing the boss and going out on your own has always been with you. But where do you start? How do you build that audience, that product, that class or freelance enterprise that will give you freedom from your boring day job? Come learn the not-so-secret tools you\'ll need to strike out on your own and become a true free agent.','regular','indepth','devlife',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-30 15:40:55','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(217,92,'Five Ways To Ensure Your Development Project Fails','Nobody wants a development project to fail. And yet, many do fail. Miserably. How can this be? It turns out there are characteristics that every failed project has in common, characteristics that if prevented, would have avoided the failure. Come learn what the top five predictors of failure are, and how you can ensure (or avoid) complete and total failure of your next development project.','regular','overview','devlife',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-30 15:41:23','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(218,92,'Making Code Reviews Successful','Most developers recognize the value of code reviews, but making a code review process effective can be really difficult. Maybe you have a nitpicker on your team, or perhaps time constraints kill the review process early on in the cycle. Whatever the reason you\'re struggling, learn how you can make your code review process work better, improve the quality of your applications, and even improve the morale of your team!','regular','overview','phpfuture',0,'','I did and experienced hundreds of code reviews at Mozilla.',0,0,0,'2014-09-30 15:42:05','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(219,92,'The Seven Deadly Sins of Object Orientation','From tight coupling to inheritance errors, even the most experienced developers can commit one of the seven deadly sins of object oriented development. What are the sins? How can you avoid falling victim to them? What should you do if they\'re already in your code? Come and find out!','regular','overview','phpfuture',0,'','I\'ve given this talk a half a dozen times.',0,0,0,'2014-09-30 15:42:25','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(220,93,'Web Security Essentials','Join me for a 3hr long tutorial exposing you to a broad range of Web Security vulnerabilities and their solutions.  Come here knowing nothing and leave with a toolkit of knowledge to ensure that you are thinking properly about security before you write your first line of code.  This tutorial will cover the basics such as XSS, CSRF, SQL Injection, and clickjacking.  But will also go into depth on issues of PHP session management, password security, two factor authentication and much much more!','tutorial','indepth','security',1,'','This is a new tutorial, based upon an extended version of my typical 1hr Security talk.  1hr just often is only enough to blaze through the basics, requiring you to skip so many topics and gloss over others.  I did a 2hr extended version of it once, and it was much better.  3 hours will allow a true in-depth coverage.\n\nMy joind.in profile: https://joind.in/user/view/225',0,0,0,'2014-09-30 16:00:58','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(221,93,'Web Security and You','This talk will focus on XSS, CSRF, Session Hijacking, SQL Injection, and other security vulnerabilities that need addressed in Website Development.  This talk will cover a gambit of these issues, giving specific code examples showing what the vulnerabilities look like and how to identify them.  It will then present solutions to close them down and protect yourself.','regular','overview','security',0,'https://joind.in/talk/view/10556','I have given this talk many times, to very good reviews.  It involves jamming as much security as possible into a 1 hour slot.\n\nMy joind.in profile: https://joind.in/user/view/225',0,0,0,'2014-09-30 16:02:20','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(222,93,'Scaling in the Cloud with Amazon Web Services','Making your web application scale is always tough. This talk is a discussion &amp; overview of the typical ways to scale LAMP apps in the past, and how you can now do this more easily on the cloud, specifically using Amazon Web Services such as EC2, RDS, S3 and more. AWS has a rich feature set that makes having a scalable app easier than ever before.','regular','overview','virtualization',0,'https://joind.in/talk/view/9095','One of my standard talks, yet to be given outside of North America - It always gets very good reviews.\n\nMy joind.in profile: https://joind.in/user/view/225',0,0,0,'2014-09-30 16:04:39','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(223,93,'Responsive Design - When, Where, Why, or Why not?','Most people have heard of Responsive Design by now. Simply the idea of a website adjusting its display to the size/shape/capacities of the browser viewing it. But there is a lingering question:  Should you do responsive design?  Why?  Why not? What are the other options?  When should you consider it in your product life-cycle?  These and more questions will be addressed.','regular','overview','responsive',0,'http://eliw.com/presentations/','I\'ve given this talk a few times before, but always at conferences that don\'t use Joind.in -- It has gotten some great feedback though.\n\nMy joind.in profile: https://joind.in/user/view/225',0,0,0,'2014-09-30 17:12:49','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(224,93,'Iterators, ArrayAccess &amp; Countable â€“ Oh My!','Learn how to empower your objects in PHP with SPL! The SPL (Standard PHP Library) has existed for many years but is still one of the less understood parts of the language. We will cover some of the most useful core aspects of the SPL, features that are easy to add to your own objects, making them more powerful and flexible!','regular','indepth','phpfuture',0,'https://joind.in/talk/view/10433','Always a good topic, as it\'s great to see people\'s eyes open as they grok the idea of an Iterator the first time.\n\nMy joind.in profile: https://joind.in/user/view/225',0,0,0,'2014-09-30 17:14:17','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(225,93,'SVN is Not a Four Letter Word','While the world has moved on to Git (thanks in no small part due to GitHub), Subversion has been chugging away at releasing new versions that answer many peopleâ€™s original concerns about SVN.  This talk wonâ€™t at all try to convince you to switch back to SVN from Git.  But aims to expose you to the enhancements that have been coming and contrast them to Git.  It will leave you with a new appreciation of what SVN can now do, and what kinds of projects it may still be a good choice for.','regular','indepth','vcs',0,'','A brand new talk, designed to re-expose people to Subversion, and show all the advances that it\'s made since people abandoned it for Git in droves years ago.\n\nMy joind.in profile: https://joind.in/user/view/225',0,0,0,'2014-09-30 17:16:13','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(226,93,'PHP OOP: An Object Oriented Programming Primer','Whether you are a brand new developer or an experienced coder - the PHP object model can hold some mysteries that are worth exploring.  This session will briefly cover the basics of working with Objects in PHP, then dive quickly through inheritance, abstracts, interfaces, traits, late static binding, magic methods, namespaces and maybe even reflection.  Itâ€™s a lot to cover to make sure to show up with your eyes open and ready to move quickly!','regular','indepth','phpfuture',0,'','A brand new talk for you - To make sure that the more beginner types can really understand all that PHP Objects can do!\n\nMy joind.in profile: https://joind.in/user/view/225',0,0,0,'2014-09-30 17:17:32','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(227,93,'Refactor, Don\'t Rebuild','To paraphrase a popular 1970\'s TV series: \"We can rebuild it...we have the technology\". Everyone has heard the phrase uttered: \"This codebase sucks, we need to rewrite it from scratch!\". In fact you\'ve probably said that exact phrase before. But is it ever really a good idea?  Via real world examples, we will explore the topic in this session and iterate the reasons why it\'s almost always better to maintain and slowly refactor existing codebases as you go, rather than throw them away and start again from scratch.','regular','overview','devlife',0,'https://joind.in/talk/view/10815','An \'inspirational\' style presentation that has gotten very good reviews.\n\nMy joind.in profile: https://joind.in/user/view/225',0,0,0,'2014-09-30 17:19:13','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(228,93,'Hacking Wordpress - A Primer for PHP Programmers','I spent most of my career writing large custom in-house solutions. To me, WordPress was the software I used to run my blog, nothing more. Suddenly I found myself doing WordPress consulting as well as inheriting a codebase which is completely built on top of it!  I was then amazed as I dove in, at just how easy it is in WordPress to build any custom functionality you want with even just a basic knowledge of PHP.  You too can use WordPress as a full blown application development framework.','regular','overview','other',0,'','WordPress gets a very bad rep in the PHP community - When it\'s a system designed for a purpose, and it does that purpose well.  Once you break your mindset that \"It\'s just a blog\", it\'s amazing what you can do with it very easily.\n\nMy joind.in profile: https://joind.in/user/view/225',0,0,0,'2014-09-30 17:25:18','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(229,95,'Strange strings','String handling in PHP is still a bit of a mystery to many but it doesn\'t have to be. Do not be misled by rumors that PHP doesn\'t support unicode properly. PHP as of version 5.3 has all the support you need to correctly handle unicode strings, as long as you know a few tricks. In this session we\'ll go over the history of string support in PHP, the pitfalls, how to step around them, and finally we\'ll send you home with specific advice on how to handle unicode throughout all levels of your PHP sites. If you never want to see \"Ã‚Â£\" again, come listen to this talk.','regular','indepth','other',0,'http://sebrechts.net/slides/strings/','I will be giving this talk at the regular PHP BNL event at MCS (november 20th).\n\nThe slides need some pacing adjustments, but the content is pretty much there.',0,0,0,'2014-09-30 21:25:24','2014-09-30 22:04:54'),(230,95,'Strange numbers','IEEE-754. If that fills you with a vague sense of dread, don\'t worry, you are not alone. We\'ll lift the covers on floating point numbers, detail their behavior bit by bit (pun intended), and go over the best practices for doing numerical computation. You will walk out with enough knowledge that the next time someone much smarter than you tells you your floating point calculation is sensitive to catastrophic cancellation, you\'ll know exactly how to tell them off, or how to fix your code.','regular','indepth','other',0,'','No slides yet, just a collection of ideas, but I\'m confident that I can shape it into a talk prior to the deadline. The talk would be like the strings talk, going in-depth in how the floating point numbers work and how to work with them in PHP, except that it will contain much more examples of bit-wise representation (I will probably end up doing long division at the bit level during the talk).',0,0,0,'2014-09-30 21:34:39','2014-09-30 22:04:44'),(231,95,'ASVS, the road to better security','Ever wanted to know what you have to do to ship a PHP application to a bank and pass an audit on the first try? OWASPâ€™s ASVS guidelines cover a wide range of security requirements that help you get there, and applying them judiciously is a great way of improving the security of your PHP application. We\'ll go over the key points of ASVS, and regale you with war stories of trying to build secure enterprise-level PHP software in the real world.','regular','overview','security',0,'https://speakerdeck.com/jsebrech/getting-to-asvs-2-balancing-practicality-with-security','I gave this talk before at a PHP BNL event: http://joind.in/talk/view/8570\n\nI plan to adjust the slides to contain more \"from the trenches\" experiences and more code based on my experience of building PHP software used by banks and telecom companies (Barclays bank, Nordea bank, Telenor, Belgacom, HP, ....)',0,0,0,'2014-09-30 21:46:19','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(232,96,'The hunt for dead code','Code dies naturally in any project, just like trees grows branches but kill them later. Dead code grows with the age of the project, the size of the team and the size of the code. But how do you spot dead functions, forgotten classes, impossible conditions, unreachable positions ? We\'ll review what is dead code, how to track it and how to remove it. We\'ll feel a lot cleaner after this.','regular','handson','devlife',1,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-30 21:48:46','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(233,96,'Migrating to newer PHP versions','While many systems are still supporting PHP 5.3, we are rushing PHP 5.6. To ensure a good migration, one must go beyond checking for compilationÂ : the code must be reviewed to avoid pitfalls like obsoletes functions, change in default parameters or behavior. It must also start taking advantage of new features and drop old habits. We\'ll review a checklist of such traps, and help your code be modern.','regular','handson','phpfuture',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-30 21:49:04','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(234,96,'Automating code quality','Even nowadays, PHP code is mostly manually audited. Expert pore over actual code, in search for bugs or code smells. Actually, it is possible to have PHP do this work itself ! Strengthened with the internal Tokenizer, bolstered by the manual, it is able to scan thousands of lines of code, without getting bored, and bringing pragmatic pieces of wisdom: official manual recommendations, version migration, code pruning and security. In the end, it deliver a global overview of the code, without reading it.','regular','overview','testing',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-30 21:49:27','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(235,96,'Of the usage of randomness','Â«Â God doesn\'t play dice with the worldÂ Â» famously said A. Einstein. But we can rely on randomness to help us in many aspects of our code. It may be to secure data, to speed up testing, to generate unforeseen situations or even inspire us to write better code. When problems get too complex or too coupled, it is worth trying some random sampling and hit the target without too much hassle. We\'ll see solutions to generate data, mutate code or apply Monte-Carlo. When you don\'t know where to start, random is always a solution.','regular','overview','devlife',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-30 22:01:30','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(236,95,'Work faster, write fewer bugs','It is often said that there is a trade-off between productivity and quality. The faster you work, the more bugs you write, and vice versa. We\'re here to dispel this myth and explain how you can have your cake and eat it too. You\'ll get productivity tips distilled from the best practices of industry leaders and the real world experience of building PHP software with a team of dozens of developers.','regular','overview','devlife',1,'http://sebrechts.net/slides/Quality%20and%20Productivity.pptx','This is an in-house talk I\'ve given to several groups of incoming developers. I gave the talk as an uncon at last year\'s conference: http://joind.in/talk/view/10475\n\nThe attendance was not high, but it was well received anyway.\n\nIf selected I will remake the slides to be more attractively styled and work in some more experiences we had at MCS trying to master the mythical two-headed beast of quality and productivity.',0,0,0,'2014-09-30 22:02:06','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(237,82,'Modernizing a Stagnant Toolbox','On the day WordPress turned 10 years old, the main repository didn\'t contain a single tool to make it easier for developers to work with and contribute code. Over the last year, we have worked to improve itâ€™s toolbox and build process that would be considered antique at best.  Our tooling and testing are now first class citizens. Many of the pieces were taken off the shelf, a few where custom built, and some required large coordinated efforts to be successfully implemented. Weâ€™ve learned some valuable lessons along the way that may help you improve your projects build and test process.','regular','indepth','other',0,'','This is based on a talk that I gave to the Portland WordPress user group and at Open Source Bridge in 2014. Those talks were shorter in length, so this will give me the opportunity to really dive into what we went through and the challenges we overcame.',0,0,0,'2014-09-30 23:18:05','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(238,97,'Push like it\'s not 1999','With all the browsers supporting the new Push technologies we can upgrade pushing to the 2014. We will create an overview of all the technologies there are  - including Websockets - and see whatâ€™s best in certain situations. With ofcourse some real world examples including fallbacks for the few using the browsers of the old age.','regular','overview','architectures',0,'http://crazyawesomecompany.com/talk/push-1999/push-like-its-not-1999.pdf','',0,0,0,'2014-09-30 23:38:26','2014-09-30 23:41:59'),(239,97,'Apify your webapp','All is Api nowadays because Apiâ€™s are awesome. Building a new Api is sometime a real pain in the ass, but what should you do when you already have a full working web application and now need an Api? You need to take care of a lot of variables and the worst thing, itâ€™s already running (in production).\n\nLets (re)structure your existing application and Apify it so your (old) application will be awesome again.','regular','handson','architectures',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-30 23:40:16','2014-09-30 23:41:43'),(240,97,'Your team is a train','Coding can be hard, but working in a team can be even harder. You need your team members just as your team members need you. Your projects will fail if you don\'t work with the person next to you. Lets connect with each other and ramp up your development speed by improving and working together.','regular','handson','devlife',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-09-30 23:41:29','2014-09-30 23:41:53'),(241,82,'The Users We Forget About','We create applications for our users. If there are no users, there generally isnâ€™t a passion to create. Once your start actually have users, itâ€™s easy to forget that our users come in many forms. They have different skills, different styles, and different abilities. They use our sites in many different ways. Letâ€™s discuss the way that users use our site and remember the users we forget.','regular','overview','ux',0,'http://aaronjorbin.github.io/wcphilly2014/#0','Many discussions about user experience make poor assumptions about our users. This talk is designed to change that discussion to focus on the types of users that are often forgotten.',0,0,0,'2014-09-30 23:50:29','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(242,97,'Continuous BDD with AutoPhing','Phing is a powerful tool enabling you to automate almost all of your tasks at Build, Development and Deployment. Create a working environment for yourself and your fellow developers where the hard stuff never has been so easy. Take a look in what Phing can do for you and even how WE can automate the automation.','regular','handson','continuousdelivery',0,'','We will use a tool called Autophing. https://github.com/CrazyAwesomeCompany/autophing',0,0,0,'2014-09-30 23:51:31','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(243,98,'Building Command Line Applications with Symfony Console','Symfony\'s Console component has revolutionized command-line PHP applications. From the clean, extensible, object-oriented design down to the pretty colors and output formatting, it has never been easier to build high-quality command line tools in PHP. We\'ll cover how to structure your apps, how to handle input arguments and output formatting, as well as how to package your application into an executable PHAR.','regular','overview','other',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-10-01 00:38:59','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(244,98,'PHP Anti Patterns','Most programming conferences these days have a talk on object-oriented design patterns. Everyone is happy to tell you how you SHOULD be writing code. In this talk we will cover how NOT to write PHP. I\'ve scoured the internet for examples of common pitfalls for PHP developers from beginner to advanced. We\'ll take a lighthearted yet serious look at issues like security, performance, code style, quirks of the language, and more.','regular','overview','crossingphp',0,'','I\'m looking forward to giving this talk at PHPWorld in November 2014, and am excited for opportunities to give it at regional conferences!',0,0,0,'2014-10-01 00:40:23','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(245,98,'Ship code faster with Kanban','Scrum is so last-decade. The Kanban method for managing software projects lowers the barrier to shipping working code and dramatically reduces the project management overhead for engineers participating in the process. In short, Kanban allows engineers and product groups to deliver value to the business at a very rapid pace, while still maintaining some sanity. Kanban is an excellent complement to the technical aspects of a continuous delivery process.  We\'ll learn what Kanban means to your team, how to get started transitioning to it, and how to avoid common mistakes.','regular','overview','continuousdelivery',1,'','',0,0,0,'2014-10-01 00:41:15','2014-10-01 00:41:55'),(246,98,'Make it Searchable','With data available on the internet doubling at an amazing rate, the modern web is increasingly focused on search. There are many ways to implement search in your PHP application. Some of them are downright terrible, while others are truly amazing. This talk will introduce you to the basics of various search engines like Solr, Sphinx, and ElasticSearch. Weâ€™ll learn strengths and weaknesses of each as well as how to integrate them into your existing PHP application. Every application has differing and often very niche needs for search, so our goal  is to show you whatâ€™s available and help you make an educated selection for which type of search is right for you.','regular','overview','other',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-10-01 00:41:43','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(247,98,'Scaling PHP Applications With Redis','Redis is a hybrid NoSQL database that\'s sits in the sweet spot between document databases like MongoDB and key-value stores like memcache. Learn the basics of Redis data structures, common commands, and how to connect to Redis from PHP. We\'ll finish with some cookbook-style examples of how you can add Redis to your existing application with minimal effort and get some nice performance gains.','regular','indepth','architectures',0,'https://speakerdeck.com/jimbojsb/learn-to-love-redis','I\'ve given Redis talks at Zendon multiple times as well as to local groups. It\'s one of my favorite technologies and I keep this talk up to date with the latest Redis features so it\'s a little new / different every time I give it.\n\nNote: slides are from an older version, but would be similar',0,0,0,'2014-10-01 00:43:06','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(248,99,'The Twelve-Factor App: Best Practices for PHP on Platforms-as-a-Service','Horizontal scalability has always been at the core of PHP application design, and in the cloud, that approach shines the brightest. But to fully leverage the power and convenience of PaaS offerings such as Heroku, it\'s worth following certain best practices and methodologies when developing applications. This presentation covers all the steps from code and dependency management over configuration to maintaining dev/prod environment parity, and will demonstrate just how easy it can be to deploy and scale a PHP application on Heroku.','regular','handson','other',0,'','https://joind.in/user/view/343',0,0,0,'2014-10-01 00:47:46','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(249,99,'Elephants in the clouds: mastering PHP on Heroku','One of the first cloud platforms around, Heroku helped shaped the form of modern PaaS. Long beyond its Ruby roots, it now supports a multitude of languages, including, most recently PHP.\n\nThis workshop explores the benefits, characteristics, pitfalls and approaches of the platform, and walks the audience through the preparation and creation of applications, their configuration, and all the best practices and methodologies that will allow them to get the most out of Heroku upon their first deploy, from dependency management over development/production parity to scaling up (and down again).\n\nFor the brave ones, we\'ll sprinkle in some advanced Web server configuration, performance tuning and even a round of HHVM and Hack.','tutorial','handson','other',0,'','https://joind.in/user/view/343',0,0,0,'2014-10-01 00:48:33','2014-10-01 00:49:44'),(250,99,'HHVM and PHP7: The Next Generation of PHP Engines','The release of Facebook\'s HHVM implementation of PHP and its impressive performance has fueled a new era of engine optimizations for PHP, as Zend have responded with \"PHPNG\", a fully refactored Zend Engine that aims to lay the groundwork for future improvements to the engine while maintaining compatibility with previous releases and likewise offering a big boost in performance. With this refactoring now scheduled to land in PHP 7 and the continuous development of HHVM that brings it closer and closer to full feature parity and compatibility with Zend PHP it\'s time to look at both engines, their roadmaps, their unique features, and the various pitfalls that are awaiting developers who are looking to take advantage of the next generation of PHP engines.','regular','overview','phpfuture',0,'','https://joind.in/user/view/343',0,0,0,'2014-10-01 00:49:30','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(251,99,'Designing HTTP Interfaces and RESTful Web Services','A lot of Web Services today claim to be RESTful APIs. But are they really? Do the URLs accurately identify resources? Are the powers of HTTP leveraged properly? What is \"Hypermedia\", what is the Uniform Interface, and what is the secret behind the HATEOAS acronym that is so essential to the REST architectural style? This talk gives answers, guidelines and examples that show what REST really is about and why Hypermedia matters.','regular','handson','other',0,'','https://joind.in/user/view/343',0,0,0,'2014-10-01 00:50:24','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(252,100,'Deploy to the a smart cloud in one command','Leveraging a few open source tools, to make you life easier deploying to several environments to the cloud at a push of a button.\nHow to have your deploys organized and run in minutes instead of hours, plus based on open source code and easily portable between vendors.\nLeverage corporate features, services and security through the new IBM platform as a service (PaaS) Bluemix.\nCreate, manage, expand your infrastructure in a fast and intuitive way, take the infrastructure management out of the way focus on your code.','regular','overview','virtualization',0,'','Tools used: \nCloud foundry: http://www.pivotal.io/platform-as-a-service/pivotal-cf\nIBM Bluemix PaaS: http://www.bluemix.net\njoind.in: https://joind.in/11448',0,0,0,'2014-10-01 04:44:23','2014-10-01 04:44:46'),(253,102,'A recommendation engine for your PHP applications','Nowadays a lot of websites try to guess what we could like:\n\"Recommendation for you in books\"\n\"People you may like\"\nSounds familiar, isn\'t it? Wouldn\'t be cool if you could do the same in your application? Well, this session is for you! In the first part of this talk recommendation systems will be introduced, focusing on collaborative filtering algorithms (CR). After that we\'ll dive in Prediction.io, an open source machine learning server for software developers to create predictive features, such as personalization, recommendation and content discovery. In the last part we\'ll cover the integration details with a PHP application','regular','overview','architectures',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-10-01 10:00:11','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(254,102,'Implementing data synchronization for mobile apps','Today mobile apps are everywhere. These apps cannot count on a reliable and constant internet connection: working in offline mode is becoming a common pattern. This is quite easy for read-only apps but it becomes rapidly tricky for apps that create data in offline mode. This talk is a case study about a possible architecture for enabling data synchronization in these situations. Some of the topics touched will be:\n- id generation\n- hierarchical data\n- managing differente data types\n- sync algorithm','regular','indepth','crossingphp',1,'','',0,0,0,'2014-10-01 10:03:10','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(255,102,'Vagrant and Puppet for fun and PHProfit','Creating disposable virtual machines for development purpose is an easy task today, thanks to Vagrant. Moreover, the usage of tools like Puppet can streamline the machine configuration, making it reproducible and predictable. The same configurations can also be used to feed other environments (production, qa, ...) shortening release cycles and giving a boost in terms of productivity\n\nIn this session we\'ll see how to achieve the aforementioned goals starting from Vagrant and how to use it to create a new machine with the basic configuration via Vagrantfile, giving particular attention to network configuration, shared folders and the differences between providers  \n\nAfter that, puppet will be introduced in order to provide the configuration for a lamp stack. Creating and organizing a manifest file, finetuning the configuration, managing different environments, installing new modules via librarian-puppet and in the end deploy the same server on the cloud should convince you to try it yourself!','regular','overview','virtualization',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-10-01 10:06:15','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(256,102,'Deploy a PHP App on Google App Engine','PHP was added to the languages offered by Google App Engine about a year ago. This session will focus on porting an existing app on gae. We\'ll start talking about the main characteristics of the app engine platform, which kind of services are available (persistence, storage, queue and so on) and how to use it. Then the PHP installation of app engine will be discussed, highlighting implementation choices and limitations.\nThe second part of the talk will go into implementation details in particular about what tweaks are needed to run an existing app on gae e.g: how session is managed, logging is performed and how to interact with the file system not forgetting about deploy','regular','overview','phpfuture',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-10-01 10:06:52','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(257,102,'Develop REST and SOAP API with Zend Framework 2','A case study about implementing an api with two different interfaces, REST and SOAP, using Zend Framework 2 for a multi-tenant application. During this presentation several topics will be touched, starting from the design choices. In particular we\'ll see how to provide two really different interfaces by encapsulating logic in services and plugging them in a zf2 app. Next, we\'ll see how data persistence is abstracted via repositories and a custom implementation of a data mapper, not forgetting data validation Since SOAP and REST interfaces require different kind of responses we\'ll discuss about building different views with viewmodels and renderers. Authentication is always a delicate topic so I\'d like to spend few words on how different schemes are implemented and integrated. Since we are talking about a brownfield project the last part of the talk will be focused on integration with legacy zend framework 1 code and testing','regular','indepth','architectures',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-10-01 10:08:18','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(258,53,'From nightmare legacy code to a professional application with a modern framework','Of course you know about testing, clean code, and continuous integration, but it just seems impossible to apply these concepts to the nasty legacy application that you are in charge of. This workshop will give you the tools to transform it into a testable, modular, collaboration-friendly application running on a modern PHP framework. We start with a legacy application that nobody wants to touch out of fear of breaking it. We will resolve dependency issues by introducing Composer and set up a build pipeline. We will wrap the application in a web-framework so that in the next step we can break it into modular pieces that will allow us to test components individually. After small refactoring steps to simple design patterns we can take advantage of dependency injection frameworks. We will cover topics such as Composer, Autoloading, Unit Tests, Integration Tests, and Dependency Injection.\n\nRequirements: basic Git knowledge, basic understanding of MVC frameworks (e.g. Symfony); a Linux or Mac laptop with Git and your favorite PHP IDE installed','tutorial','handson','devlife',1,'','The workshop will include many code examples and hands-on exercises for the participants to get their hands dirty. For CI and Git server infrastructure, we will provide our own devices.',0,0,0,'2014-10-01 12:09:52','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(259,103,'Journey from startup to enterprise, a tech talk','This is a tech talk, from a developer perspective that will cover a 5 year long journey of growing/building a web application from startup to enterprise. \n\nWhile starting with a short overview (pros/cons) of building it using our own bare metal servers instead of using popular cloud solutions, showing some architecture details of running a 300.000.000 pageviews a month site, main focus will be sharing our expiriences on scaling, performance, building a better team, implementing new technologies and some of the organizational details that helped us on the way. \n\nAll of the slides are covered with at least one short but true story of what happened and how we have handled it.','regular','overview','devlife',1,'http://slides.com/mirosvrtan/njuskalo-hr','I\'we already spoke on this subject, in variations depending on audience and given time slot length in ZgPHP meetup, ViennaPHP meetup and PHPDay and PHPCon Polska conferences.',0,0,0,'2014-10-01 21:40:32','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(260,95,'Large scale PHP: energy analytics system','A story from the trenches, documenting the challenges met during the construction of a PHP-based energy management analytics solution that tracks and helps optimize the energy usage of over 10.000 buildings, developed by a team of dozens of people. This project challenged everything about the organization that built it, from the lowest details of how the code was written, to the highest echelons of corporate decision-making. At this scale, there is no room for mistakes, and yet we still made plenty. Come learn from our mistakes and our successes.','regular','overview','architectures',0,'','For contractual reasons I can\'t reveal the customer, but I can freely talk about the process and technical challenges. There are no slides yet, but they should pretty much write themselves because I can just tell the story of building the system front to back and the (all too many) challenges we met along the way.',0,0,0,'2014-10-01 21:58:34','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(261,87,'Bring your workflow into 2014','Over the past few years the PHP community has changed its development processes dramatically for the better, in no small part due to the large number of tools available to help aid development. Iâ€™ll talk about a small selection of these game-changing tools and demonstrate how you can optimise your development workflow in such a way it both benefits you and the quality of your resultant application but avoiding the potential confusion for new (and old) contributors and bloat to your processes when using these tools.','regular','overview','testing',0,'','Touches on testing for part of the talk but is not centred around it does encompass the Testing category however is not soley about that.',0,0,0,'2014-10-02 23:48:17','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(262,87,'Getting off the Island','There are many FOSS projects out there - such as phpBB, Drupal, Wordpress, MyBB and Joomla - that are web applications designed for end-users and have, due to a range of factors, have become very isolated from the rest of the open source community. I\'ll be explaining why this is such a bad thing, how these projects are beginning to change their philosophies and how frameworks, libraries, and the PHP FIG can help these projects to \'get off the island\'.','regular','overview','phpfuture',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-10-02 23:49:54','2014-10-03 00:36:09'),(263,87,'Making yourself a better developer','[Almost] every developer creates code and makes working applications. So what distinguishes between a \'Good Developer\' and a \'Bad Developer\' and how do we truly become better at \'developing\' when we always have the same eventual outcome, a working application. \n\nWe are all looking for ways to make our code more scalable, ensure it has good maintainability, try and develop \'good code\' faster, use well respected standards and methods of development, ensure code is nicely crafted and valuable, and make things easy for new developers to walk in and pick up where you left off. But how do we actually go about making ourselves better at our job in a way that affects not just all of these outcomes I\'ve mentioned, but also, making sure that we are building ourselves to be true better developers, who are better because the end product, the product an end user has to use and is delivered to your client/employer, is better and not just the processes that you take to develop/maintain it.','regular','overview','other',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-10-02 23:50:48','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(264,87,'PHP FIG: Making php normal','Some of you may have heard of PHP FIG. Most of you will have heard of PSR-0 (or another PSR). And almost all of you have used something that follows a PSR. So what is the fuss all about? Come and find out about PHP FIG as an organisation; the PSRs of the past, present, and future; and how PSRs are used in libraries and applications we use every day.','regular','overview','other',0,'https://speakerdeck.com/michaelcullum/fig','Previously done at PHP Hampshire (UK User Group)',0,0,0,'2014-10-02 23:52:02','2014-10-02 23:52:17'),(265,87,'Converting a website to a new religion: Symfony','When you have a huge website and you decide to make the move to Symfony, it can be a very daunting prospect of having to rewrite your entire website on top of the Symfony framework. Weâ€™ll go through how this can be done as smoothly as possible with a large enterprise size website, piece by piece, deploying your site every step of the way, following along with the example of phpBB, an organisation going through this process, to discover the right and wrong way to go about it and many tools you can use on enterprise-scale Symfony applications to help along the way.','regular','overview','other',0,'https://speakerdeck.com/michaelcullum/converting-a-website-to-a-new-religion-symfony','Previously presented at Symfony Live London 2014',0,0,0,'2014-10-03 00:34:08','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(266,87,'Silex vs Symfony, Micro vs Full Stack: The Final Showdown','There is often a lot of confusion about when one should use a micro-framework and when one should use a full stack framework. Firstly weâ€™ll dive into detail about the different theoretical advantages &amp; disadvantages of the two and when it is most appropriate to use them. Then review Silex micro-framework and Symfony Full Stack and compare many aspects such as performance, readability/maintainability, the ability to micromanage your application and ease of development on a variety of different scales of application from your simple hello world to a large enterprise site.','regular','overview','other',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-10-03 00:34:47','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(267,87,'phpBB, Meet Symfony','The recently released phpBB 3.1 was released with a large number of backend changes including moving over to use many Symfony Components, Twig and many more external libraries, akin to those changes in Drupal 8. In this talk Iâ€™ll discuss how we moved to these new pieces of vital infrastructure, how it impacted our entire architecture and way of thinking, and why we attempted to â€˜Get off the Island and into the Wildâ€™.','regular','overview','other',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-10-03 00:35:13','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(268,87,'Bringing phpBB into the 2010s','phpBB is a forum software that has been around since 2000 and is possibly one of the oldest still developed and widely used FOSS [Free &amp; Open Source Software] projects around. In 2007 phpBB 3.0 â€˜Olympusâ€™ was released and since then we have embarked on an adventure for the next major release of phpBB â€“ 3.1 (Also called 3.2 and 4.0 in the past). This talk goes over where phpBB has come from since the Olympus release, the mistakes weâ€™ve made and finally how we made it to making 3.1 a finished product, built using Symfony Components. Furthermore I will outline the different development workflows &amp; release cycles weâ€™ve tried and go over what worked and what didnâ€™t.','regular','overview','phpfuture',1,'','',0,0,0,'2014-10-03 00:35:38','2014-10-03 00:41:20'),(269,104,'Getting Started with Continuous Integration','Continuous integration is a big idea, but what if your projects - and availability to implement new things - aren\'t big? Is continuous integration worthwhile for every day projects? Learn more about what continuous integration actually is, what tools are available to help you implement it, and how you can make it work for you, even in the small stuff.','regular','overview','continuousdelivery',0,'http://www.treelinedesign.com/slides/','This talk has gotten very good feedback on Joind.in:\nhttps://joind.in/user/view/2821\nand on Meetup: http://www.meetup.com/fox-cities-php/events/114977612/',1,0,0,'2014-10-03 15:43:57','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(270,104,'Get Started with PHP','Whether you are new to programming or are just looking for a refresher, this tutorial will get you started with the basics of PHP. Through building a pizza order form, we\'ll discuss and view code for strings and arrays, conditions and loops, sessions and cookies, form validation and basic security, as well as writing your own functions. Questions are welcomed!','tutorial','handson','crossingphp',0,'http://www.treelinedesign.com/slides/','This talk has gotten very good feedback on Joind.in:\nhttps://joind.in/user/view/2821',1,0,0,'2014-10-03 15:45:29','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(271,104,'How to Start a User Group','Do you wish there were a user group near you, but you can\'t find one? That\'s your cue to start one! Don\'t worry, it\'s not as hard as you think, and you are not alone. Learn about what resources are available to you and how to get things moving. The benefits of building the community around you are more than worth the effort!','regular','overview','devlife',0,'http://www.treelinedesign.com/slides/','This talk has gotten very good feedback on Joind.in:\nhttps://joind.in/user/view/2821',1,0,0,'2014-10-03 15:47:10','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(272,104,'Be a Bold Coder','Do you cringe when you have to show someone else your code? Have you ever complained about terribly written code only to discover it was yours from six months ago? Coding is a constantly evolving field. How can you keep up? Learn what standards are out there to help you keep your code clean, what tools can help you proof your code, and where to find information on best practices so you can stay current and boldly share your code with others.','regular','overview','devlife',0,'','This is a new talk, so I don\'t have feedback on it specifically, but I have received lots of good feedback as a speaker:\nhttps://joind.in/user/view/2821',1,0,0,'2014-10-03 15:48:36','2014-10-03 15:50:19'),(273,104,'Mentoring: Change the World One Hour at a Time','It\'s a tough world out there. There are so many new things to learn, and the list of need-to-know\'s changes every day. How do you keep up? How do you move ahead? Find a mentor - but wait! Isn\'t this a dog-eat-dog field where admitting you don\'t know something is the death of your career? Maybe back in 1995, but this is the new age of open source. Collaboration and sharing of information reigns. Find a mentor to help you excel, but more importantly, find someone to mentor. Being a mentor is challenging, rewarding, and keeps you on your toes. Learn what it takes to find a mentor, be a good mentor, and what tools can help you build your mentoring relationship.','regular','overview','crossingphp',0,'','This is a new talk, so I don\'t have feedback on it specifically, but I have received lots of good feedback as a speaker:\nhttps://joind.in/user/view/2821',1,0,0,'2014-10-03 15:50:06','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(274,104,'How to Speak at a Conference','Have you ever thought about giving a talk at the user group or at a conference but weren\'t sure what to talk about? Weren\'t sure how to format your slides? Weren\'t sure where to even start? Beth Tucker Long has spoken over 30 times in the last few years at various conferences around the world. Learn some tips for finding a topic, creating your talk, and engaging your audience. After the talk, Beth will be on-hand to work with you to develop your talk ideas, write your abstract, and find a call for papers or user group to submit your ideas to.','regular','overview','crossingphp',0,'http://www.treelinedesign.com/slides/','Feedback from Meetup:\n\nVesna Vuynovich Kovach\nExcellent meta presentation! Beth is so relaxed and confident as a speaker, it\'s hard to believe she was or is as nervous as she says -- so it\'s inspiring to hear of her journey to become an ace presenter! Plus, she helped me and others come away with customized lists of potential presentations we could do.\n\nCharlene Wroblewski\nGreat presentation. Thank you Beth for giving me ideas of talks!\n\nSaundra\nI was very excited about the topic and I was not disappointed. It was a wonderful privilege to get attend this presentation! Everything was spot on and I learned a great deal. After this presentation rather then feeling forced to give a talk at work I believe I may actually be able to enjoy giving a talk in the future. What a great feeling to actually be given tools and ideas which both make you feel more prepared and confident going into something that before I just dreaded. Thanks Beth!\n\nFeedback taken from:\nhttp://www.meetup.com/madisonphp/events/207068502/',1,0,0,'2014-10-03 15:52:11','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(275,104,'CMSMadeSimple: Simple for You, Simple for Your Customers','Tired of trying to convert HTML/CSS files into a theme for WordPress? Frustrated with teaching non-technical users to use the Drupal admin panel? CMSMadeSimple is quick to install, very easy to theme, and a breeze for non-technical users to manage with their clean, easy-to-learn admin panel. You can write blocks of custom PHP code that are run using Smarty-like tags, so your users can add code to their pages without ever seeing the PHP (or breaking it). Add to this, a library of modules that are installed with the click of a button in the admin panel, and CMSMadeSimple is a clear winner! Learn how to install, theme, and expand CMSMadeSimple, going from \"nothing\" to \"ready to deliver\" in the span of this single talk.','regular','overview','other',0,'','This is a new talk, so I don\'t have feedback on it specifically, but I have received lots of good feedback as a speaker:\nhttps://joind.in/user/view/2821',1,0,0,'2014-10-03 15:53:27','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(276,104,'How to Write a Book','Curious about what it takes to write a book? Want to give it a try, but aren\'t sure where to start or which path to take? Learn about the differences in publishing options (from self-publishing to large publishing houses), how to build an audience, best practices for editing and reviewing, how to market your book, and more!','regular','overview','other',0,'','This is a new talk, so I don\'t have feedback on it specifically, but I have received lots of good feedback as a speaker:\nhttps://joind.in/user/view/2821',1,0,0,'2014-10-03 15:53:59','2014-10-03 15:54:38'),(277,104,'The Only Girl in the Room','The news has been filled with stories of sexism in tech. These stories cover major, obvious instances that, hopefully, are not common in our everyday lives. So why is sexism (and inclusion for everyone) getting so much attention? Have you ever thought \"I believe that it\'s tougher and I want to help, but I\'ve never seen it happen?\" Our day-to-day definition of normal is not as inclusive as we think it is. Come get an inside look at what kinds of daily things happen that make it very difficult to be a woman in tech.','regular','overview','crossingphp',0,'','This talk would also work well as a panel discussion, and I would be happy to help put together a panel of speakers if you\'d like. This is a new talk, so I don\'t have feedback on it specifically, but I have received lots of good feedback as a speaker:\nhttps://joind.in/user/view/2821',1,0,0,'2014-10-03 15:58:06','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(278,104,'I\'ve Been Hacked, Now What?','Put on your trench coat and grab your magnifying glass as we walk through investigating a real-life hacked WordPress website. You\'ll experience first-hand what tools can help you find the vulnerability and the point of entrance. Learn what the hacker might have left behind, how to seal up the most common problem areas, and how to set up notifications to help you spot a hack more quickly in the future. Even though we will be going through a WordPress website, most of the tools discussed are applicable to any website.','regular','overview','security',0,'http://www.treelinedesign.com/slides/','This talk has gotten very good feedback on Joind.in:\nhttps://joind.in/user/view/2821\nand on Meetup: http://www.madisonphp.com/events/109982102/',1,0,0,'2014-10-03 16:01:23','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(279,104,'Usability Basics','Not everyone has access to a user interface designer, but that doesn\'t mean that usability is out of your reach. Come learn the basics of usability through examples and discussion. Find out what kinds of simple changes can make a big difference to your users. We will also cover how to do usability testing for your site and will practice analyzing sites from a user\'s perspective.','regular','overview','ux',0,'http://www.treelinedesign.com/slides/','This talk has gotten very good feedback on Joind.in:\nhttps://joind.in/user/view/2821',1,0,0,'2014-10-03 16:05:27','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(280,105,'Getting Started with Package Development','Beginner and intermediate package developers may want to check out this talk. I will talk about all the necessary steps that take your package from beginner level to hundreds of installs per day. From extremely beginner steps like register auto-loading and packagist webhook to a great readme documentation and framework agnostics.','regular','indepth','other',1,'https://speakerdeck.com/hannesvdvreken/getting-started-with-package-development','I previously did this talk at a local meetup and at laracon.eu (https://joind.in/11678)\nResponse has been positive.',0,0,0,'2014-10-03 23:37:12','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(281,105,'Are you sure you understand REST basics?','Most people think they understand rest. GET, POST, PUT and DELETE. But many people struggle to design an API for soft-deleted resources, or relationships without attributes like stars, friendships, likes, etc. In this talk I will go over the REST basics in a slightly different way. I will give some pointers that most people seem to forget like the difference between PUT and PATCH, or the fact that DELETE on a collection isn\'t a good idea. I will demonstrate every item with a good and a bad example of an API call that is in use by one of the biggest API providers like Twitter, Github, Instagram, Foursquare, etc.\n\nWhen all basics are covered I will show some more advanced solutions like soft-deletes and star implementations, again accompanied with good and bad implementation examples. I hope to educate fellow developers because using a badly designed API can be frustrating from time to time. So by doing this I hope to improve our life quality.','regular','overview','phpfuture',0,'(on their way)','This will be an iteration of a talk I gave at a company internal conference.',0,0,0,'2014-10-03 23:46:10','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(282,105,'Vagrant eco-system','An in-depth talk about Vagrant, Vagrant Cloud, Vagrant share, Ngrok, Vaprobash, Laravel Homestead, ... combined with Environments to do good Continuous Integration.  Tools to improve teamwork and Continuous Delivery within projects.','regular','overview','devlife',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-10-03 23:50:39','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(283,63,'You know where I am, don\'t you?','Geolocation seems to be everywhere. We are having a look backwards to how the basics evolved and why that is still relevant, check for different ways to do geolocation and find out what pros and cons there are for them. We will hear some history, see some code and have some apples and oranges.','regular','overview','ux',0,'','I\'ve done that one already on a short notice on a barcamp. It\'s not on joind.in or Lanyrd though so sorry, no other reputations.',0,0,0,'2014-10-04 07:38:11','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(284,63,'Enterprise Authentication Systems','In Enterprise-Environments we often don\'t need password-hasing as user-credentials are available via a central repository. We are having a look on how to authenticate users via One-Password vor all, SingleSignOn and Certificates. We will dabble in Code and some background-Information','regular','overview','security',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-10-04 07:39:09','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(285,63,'And then the user can download this as PDF','Often this simple User-Story can provide sleeples nights. We will have a look at the different ways to create PDF-Files and see a good share of libraries that are available for that. We will also touch Signed and Tagged PDFs as well as Accessibility.','regular','overview','ux',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-10-04 07:40:05','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(286,63,'Transition from MySQL to PostgreSQL','So we\'ve set up our shiny cool new PostgreSQL! And now? How do we get our existing Data from our old (MySQL) Database into the new one? What do we have to consider? And why should we make the transition in the first place? We will look for at least some answers to those questions.','regular','overview','architectures',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-10-04 07:41:09','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(287,107,'How to Annoy Your Friendly Neighborhood SysAdmin','Say you\'re in a foul mood. You\'re angry at your local SysAdmin for not giving you root access to the servers. What code could you write to make his life harder? How can you annoy a sysadmin with some simple lines of code?\n\nThis talk will go into detail on what you as a PHP developer can do to make the life of SysAdmins all over the world harder. The main takeaway would be that you don\'t do it anymore, of course. I\'ll cover, for instance, how to make debugging applications harder, how to write code that is sure to set a server on fire, how can you crash a MySQL server or a remote Memcached instance, ... Learn all of this and more!','regular','overview','ux',1,'','',1,0,0,'2014-10-04 14:42:34','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(288,108,'Compose your own framework','When PHP 5.3 came out it was a game changer. PHP was no longer just a scripting language that you could just throw in a few scripts just for fun and get things going. At that point PHP became a language of choice, introducing autoloader, namespaces and proper OOP.\n\nThe next awesome addition came in a few years later in the form of dependency management. Composer brought sanity and simplicity. Enabling us to select components we need and easily integrate them in our systems.\n\nAs developers, at some point in our lives we get into the mode of developing our own framework. In some cases it is just because we can and in others because over time we have created a toolkit with functionality that we most often use.\n\nWith composer, we can do that much easier. \n\nIn this talk I will be looking into creating an MVC framework using a selection of components. \n\nThe best solution for your project is a custom solution for your project. There are no one framework that fits-all. Now we can use dependency management with composer to create the best custom framework for a particular project.','regular','overview','phpfuture',0,'','I am the organiser of the PHP East Midlands (@PHPem) user group in Leicester, UK. Recently, at PHPNW14 I was one of the Unconference organisers.\n\nThis talk adds a more interesting twist on the most common thing a developer tends to do after their 1st year of working with PHP; creating their own framework. As PHP gets more powerful and as PHP developers we gain more experience there are things we all can do that in custom projects we can do so much better than the generic frameworks.\nSo, use composer and integrate the best components you can get for the particular project you\'re working on. And that framework will be very powerful for that particular customer. Of course we can re-use components and through that create our custom tookit/choice of components that we can re-use.',1,0,0,'2014-10-04 18:02:43','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(289,109,'Malicious cryptography in PHP apps','Cryptovirology studies how to use cryptography to design malicious software, given that public-key cryptography can be used to break the symmetry between what an antivirus analyst sees regarding a virus and what the virus writer sees. This talk explains how to create, for educational purposes, a simple cryptovirus in PHP able to infect a PHP app and encrypt data such as database records or user uploaded files using public key cryptography with OpenSSL.\n\nSeveral strategies to hide the virus will be discussed. Simple ones like using different encodings and more advanced strategies such as polymorphic and metamorphic code. Finally, we will see how we can defend ourselves from this kind of attacks using hash functions and PHAR signatures.','regular','overview','security',1,'(for Symfony2) http://www.slideshare.net/raulfraile/kernelinfect-creating-a-cryptovirus-for-symfony2-apps','This talk can be an interesting and funny way to learn cool topics such as public key cryptography, hash functions, antivirus signatures or polymorphic code.',0,0,0,'2014-10-05 01:11:55','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(290,109,'How GZIP compression works','Data compression is an amazing topic. Even in todayâ€™s world, with fast networks and almost unlimited storage, data compression is still relevant, especially for mobile devices and countries with poor Internet connections. \n\nFor better or worse, GZIP compression is the de-facto lossless compression method for compressing text data in websites. It is not the fastest nor the better, but provides an excellent tradeoff between speed and compression ratio. The way Internet works makes it also difficult to use newer compression methods.\n\nThis talk examines how GZIP works internally, explaining the internals of the DEFLATE algorithm, which is a combination of LZ77 and Huffman coding. Different implementations will be compared, such as GNU GZIP, 7-ZIP and zopfli, focusing on why and how some of these implementations perform better than others. \n\nFinally, we will try to go beyond GZIP, preprocessing our data to achieve better results. One example of this is transposing JSON.','regular','indepth','other',0,'http://www.slideshare.net/raulfraile/how-gzip-compression-works-js-conf-eu-2014','',0,0,0,'2014-10-05 01:14:04','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(291,109,'Steganography: hiding your secrets with PHP','Steganography consists of hiding a secret message within another message. Unlike cryptography, steganography tries to achieve security through obscurity, hiding the very presence of the message. Ideally, the steganographic message will look identically to a normal message.\n\nThis talk examines different techniques to hide messages using steganography from the perspective of a PHP developer. From more classical techniques such as hiding an image within another image using the least significant bits of each pixel, to more advanced ones like using TCP/IP packets.','regular','overview','security',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-10-05 01:14:45','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(292,69,'The power of HTTP Cache and ESI for performant page delivery','For web sites with frequent content changes, like news portals, an optimal cache strategy is crucial for serving millions of page views. To just cache every page statically is usually not an option as editors want to see the changes immediately. With the new version of eZ Publish CMS, which is based on Symfony PHP framework, content caching is based on HTTP Cache. This enables much tighter integration with reverse proxies like Varnish and better control of cached pages. Also, Symfony provides ESI capabilities for controlling reverse proxy cache even on block level so invalidating a whole page is not expensive.','regular','overview','phpfuture',0,'','',0,0,0,'2014-10-05 12:34:04','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(293,110,'Unit Testing sucks (and it\'s our fault)','Most people I know write tests and they hate it. They feel fooled by empty promises of easy refactoring and increased development speed, but they are getting none of those things. What are they doing wrong?\n\nIn this talk we try to analyze why tests are good, and how can we maximize their value. Focusing on communcation, making the tests self-express their purpose, is one of the key practices where programmers fail. In order to be able to change a line of code, we have to understand what\'s the code doing. This is no different for tests. Trying to minimize the effort needed to reach this level of understanding, makes the maintenance less painful.\n\nThrough real examples, we\'ll see how applying simple techniques, we can make the tests pleasant again. We\'ll also discuss how much testing is needed and how different styles of testing can provide you various benefits in different scenarios.','regular','indepth','testing',1,'','',0,0,0,'2014-10-05 12:47:07','0000-00-00 00:00:00'),(294,69,'Deeply integrated eCommerce solution (Sylius) with CMS (eZ Publish) over common framework (Symfony)','There are many great CMS solutions out there and number of eCommerce systems as well, especially developed with PHP.  Integration between those two is very loose and similar to any kind of heterogeneous connecting. One of the side effects of recent emergence of great PHP frameworks is the chance to have the CMS and eCommerce built on same conventions which enables much tighter integration. Concretely, eZ Publish CMS version 5 is being refactored on top of Symfony and a new eCommerce played showed up lately built on Symfony too. This presentation will share first experiences of integrating those 2 systems, not by doing standard import/export/sync kind of integration but introducing a glue that makes the two work on same Symfony application.','regular','overview','phpfuture',0,'','This talk should be interesting from 3 perspectives: \n- for CMS audience: getting shop features\n- for ecommerce audience: getting CMS features\n- for Symfony framework: 2 different solutions could be integrated on app level\n\nThe integration is still work in progress, but I already have a lot of interesting things to share. Should be much more till the conference :)\n\nCheers',0,0,0,'2014-10-05 13:05:42','0000-00-00 00:00:00');
